<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina-Military     12-12 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Military,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers To Get 20 Percent Pay Raise This Month, Plus Bonus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The armed forces will receive pay raises of 20 percent in December with a $ 100 bonus, an official report said Monday. Soldiers who mounted a four-day uprising this month had demanded raises. The government's news agency, <ORGANIZATION> Telam </ORGANIZATION>, cited `` reliable sources'' for its report of the raises. It gave no details in its two-paragraph story. The military uprising broke out at a base on the outskirts of the capital on Dec. 1 and moved to another base nearby before the mutineers agreed to return to their units. The revolt left three people dead. Civilian President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> denied reports at the time that he was forced to make concessions in exchange for the surrender of the rebellious troops. Soldiers have complained that they _ like other public employees _ have lost significant purchasing power as raises failed to keep pace with increases in the cost of living. The military received a 30 percent raise in July and 12 percent in October. The cost of living rose by 26 percent in July and 9 percent in October. The latest raise would be well ahead of inflation, which last month increased by 6 percent. The government has tried to control military salaries partly in an effort to harness inflation. In addition, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has blocked the 1988 budget because it wants more federal funds for the provinces. The military share of the total budget has shrunk to about 2 percent of gross domestic product from about 4 percent during military dictatorships of 1976-83.
</TEXT>
