<FIRST>u a AM-Texas-Executions 2ndLd-Writethru a0795 12-12 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas-Executions, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0795,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Grants State In One of Two Scheduled Executions Early
Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court issuing stay;
other execution still on. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Hawkins, 65,...'.
It is scheduled for after 1 a.m. EST, but could go hours later;
leads will be expedited. Abbe is cq in 8h graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A convict dubbed the `` traveling rapist'' received a stay of execution late Monday for the rape-murder of a 19-year-old woman, but a second man was still slated to be put to death by injection early Tuesday for the killing of a restaurateur. The high court granted an application for a stay of execution for <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> late Monday, hours after turning down a similar request from <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, whose execution was still scheduled for after midnight. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arberg </PERSON> said the application was filed at 9:30 p.m. EST and the order sparing <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> was entered at 10:25 p.m. with Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> dissenting. He was sentenced to death for the 1976 rape-slaying of a 19-year-old woman. Earlier Monday, the nation's high court voted 7-2 to refuse the appeal filed by lawyers for <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, 39, a native of <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, who was convicted of killing a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> restaurant owner during a robbery. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 allowed capital punishment to resume, no state has executed two inmates in a single day, although two inmates, and in one case three, have been executed on the same day in separate states. Before Tuesday's scheduled executions, 28 inmates, including two this year, had been put to death by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> prison officials since 1976. The tally is the highest of any state. Before the issuance of a stay, the two were to be executed in the same death chamber, with <PERSON> Landry </PERSON> scheduled first. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, 45, faced injection for the rape and stabbing death of <PERSON> Abbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> of <PERSON> Borger </PERSON>, who was killed after <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> entered her apparently unlocked home. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>' case Monday went to the 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> after a federal district judge in <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Halbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>, reversed a stay he issued Friday. State attorneys had appealed his action. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> also has a second death sentence for the abduction and slaying of a 12-year-old Amarillo girl. He has been dubbed the `` traveling rapist'' after admitting to some 40 rapes, prosecutors said. <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON>, bypassed lower federal courts and had appealed directly to the high court. <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, a former electrician, was sentenced for the shooting death of <PERSON> Kosmas </PERSON> <PERSON> Prittis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Prittis </PERSON>, 33, a Greek immigrant, was robbed of more than $ 2,300 and fatally shot in the head while he and his family were closing their restaurant. Last January, <PERSON> Landry </PERSON> came within three hours of execution before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> issued a stay. In appeals for each inmate, defense attorneys cited a case pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> involving <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> death row inmate <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Penry </PERSON>. That case challenges the legality of executing mentally retarded inmates. `` This man is n't retarded,'' assistant attorney general <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>. `` I do n't think that's going to fly with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, an 11th-grade dropout, has a lengthy criminal record, including arrests for sexual assault and abuse of a juvenile, assault, family neglect and petty larceny.
</TEXT>
