<SECOND>AM-Cuban Exiles,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 200 Cubans Arrive In Miami; Had Been Stranded In Other
Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 200 Cubans came to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> over the weekend as part of a program to reunite Cuban-Americans with relatives who left <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> but have been stranded in other countries. About 190 Cubans arrived Saturday and an additional 20 arrived Sunday on flights from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Some 370 more Cubans were expected to arrive Tuesday and Thursday on flights sponsored by the Cuban <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. The refugees were greeted with cheers as they arrived. `` I'm elated,'' said <PERSON> Gilfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Landa </PERSON>, 21, as he hugged his brothers, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 19, and <PERSON> Yoeidy </PERSON>, 14. The two brothers had just arrived to join <PERSON> Gilfredo </PERSON>, who arrived in 1980 during the Mariel boatlift. `` They're going to learn English,'' he said. Since the foundation program began Sept. 11, 805 former Cubans have arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. Under the guidelines of the program, relatives or friends of the refugees promise to pay travel costs and provide financial support for two years. Foundation chairman <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Mas </PERSON> <PERSON> Canosa </PERSON> said there will be more flights from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and possibly <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The foundation can bring up to 1,500 refugees into the country this year.
</TEXT>
