<HEAD>Flights Delayed After Break-In At Airport Control Room</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a dozen flights were delayed at <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> when a man broke into a control room and disconnected hundreds of fuses from the air traffic control system, police said today. The incident cut communications between airport controllers and flights using the airport for about 40 minutes on Sunday, said a local police official who spoke on condition of anonymity. Six departures and 11 arrivals were delayed for up to half an hour. Police arrested a 26-year-old man they described only as a professional golfer. The official said the man may have entered the closely guarded communications control center when employees were at lunch. Police using a duplicate key entered and overpowered the man, who shouted that he was acting `` at the guidance of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>,'' the official said. His identity was withheld pending investigation of his mental health.
</TEXT>
