<FIRST>r i PM-Botha-Mandela     12-12 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botha-Mandela,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela Overshadows Botha's Efforts To Ease Pressure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is campaigning doggedly to improve <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s image overseas, but he faces constant reminders that success will be limited until he comes to terms with <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. Among those conveying that message in recent days were <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s best-known novelist, black and white corporate executives, and two leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators who were rebuffed curtly when they asked <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> if they could meet the jailed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader. Even the government's recent decision to transfer <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> to a prison farm staff house, complete with swimming pool and patio, seemed to underscore the special stature of the 70-year-old black nationalist. `` They are showing that he is the major kingpin in the constitutional future of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalling </PERSON>, parliament member from the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Perhaps the most dramatic evidence of the influence wielded over <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> came in court testimony last week on behalf of 11 black activists about to be sentenced for treason and terrorism in the same courthouse where <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> received a life sentence for sabotage in 1964. Most of the 11 treason defendants were affiliated to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition which the trial judge said had collaborated with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. The defense lawyers, instead of repudiating the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, summoned several of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most respected opposition figures to speak about their support for and understanding of the outlawed guerrilla movement. <PERSON> Nadine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordimer </PERSON>, the country's foremost novelist, said she considered <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> her leader and blamed her fellow whites for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s political violence. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Motsuenyane </PERSON>, a black bank chairman, said of <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>: `` Unquestionably, he is my hero.'' Similar statements came from a university administrator and the leader of a black homeland. In a subsequent magazine interview, a prominent Afrikaner business leader, <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON>, said he wanted to meet <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> `` man to man'' to discuss a peaceful political settlement. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has declined to spell out his plans for <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> as he presses ahead with an unprecedented campaign to ease international pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. In the past few weeks, he has commuted the widely denounced death sentences of a group of blacks known as the <ORGANIZATION> Sharpeville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Six </ORGANIZATION>, freed two elderly black political prisoners and endorsed a tentative peace plan that could end South African rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. All these steps, as well as <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s transfer, have been welcomed in Western capitals. But always, the pressure to deal politically with <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> resumes. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> also is under fire for continued repression of dissidents at home while he tries to impress power brokers abroad. Even a seemingly benevolent gesture, the recent release of detained black newspaper editor <PERSON> Zwelakhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, had a harsh edge to it. <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, like several other freed detainees, was prohibited from returning to his job, restricted to the area around his home and barred from anti-government political activity. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Senators <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, at the close of a one-week fact-finding trip, acknowledged Saturday that <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> had taken some positive steps but said they came away with a feeling of pessimism. `` If those who are working for real change are foreclosed from using non-violent political methods, it is our great fear that they will be forced to turn to methods that will undoubtedly lead to violence and tragedy,'' the two Democrats said. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, `` deeply disappointed us by wanting to talk only about the past, not trying to engage and assess and share ideas about the future.'' Even if <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> were released, opposition leaders say the gesture would mean little unless he and other prominent black militants, young and old, are allowed to engage freely in politics and to work for a one-person, one-vote system. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> says he is not willing to even discuss such a system, and there is no sign that <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s release would mean an easing of restrictions on opposition activity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Crary </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> news editor in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and has been reporting from East and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since 1985.
