<HEAD>Dustin Hoffman Joins Film Role Model For Preview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An autistic man who served as a model for <PERSON> Dustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s latest movie character watched the premiere of `` Rain Man'' with the actor three rows behind him. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, 28, was one of three autistic people <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> studied to prepare for the role of <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, an idiot savant who inherits $ 3 million from his father's estate but has no concept of money. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, director <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levinson </PERSON> and producer <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> to help raise funds for the <ORGANIZATION> Autism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which is run by <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>. About 1,500 people attended Sunday's benefit at the ornate Keith-Albee Theater. The center said it expected to get $ 30,000 to $ 35,000. `` It's not something that's happened to us before, coming to a town which has a family in it which was the inspiration for our film,'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> told the 600 people attending a dinner following the premiere. `` It's just a very moving experience for myself and my wife, and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> and his wife, and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> and his wife. `` We just made a film that's going to play for, you know, a month or two, or whatever, in cities in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and around the world and be put out on -LRB- video -RRB- cassette and put on shelves and seen once. `` You people have <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> in your community for the rest of your lives, and I would take that any day of the week, and I think that's a really important thing because he is a very special person who shines through this ... magic he has. Autism is an affliction in which the brain does n't process information correctly. Some autistics are self-abusive and lack social skills but excel in music, math and art. Generally, though, autism is misunderstood, said Mrs. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. `` I had people say, ` Is n't it nice your little boy knows how to draw,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> gave the movie credit for advancing knowledge of autism, telling <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, `` You have done with one film what we have been trying to do in our field for 25 years.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said, however, `` If we do one-tenth of what Mrs. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has done, we will have made a little advance.''
