<HEAD>Protestant Schoolgirl Crosses The Sectarian Divide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, a 16-year-old Protestant, had never met a Roman Catholic until she went to a memorial service for the victims of an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bombing and ended up holding hands with two nuns. That moment at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, when the minister asked everyone in the overflowing congregation to join hands and pray, marked a turning point in <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON>'s life. She had been crying for the 11 people killed in <LOCATION> Enniskillen </LOCATION> on Nov. 8, 1987 and was so wrapped up in the service she did n't realize she had picked up the hands of two nuns who were sitting beside her. `` I went home and I thought, ` I'm just really fed up that I have to hate this woman because she's wearing a nun's habit, I have to hate this fellow because he's a Catholic.' It just went over and over in my mind, you know, what am I going to do?,'' she said. `` I'd never met any Catholics, never, never. ... My mom and dad are very good, they really are. They did n't keep me away from Catholics. It's just where I lived there were n't any,'' she said. In <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, with its history of sectarian animosities, it is common for youngsters, and even adults, never to have met someone of another religion. Many of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s 1 million Protestants and 600,000 Catholics live in neighborhoods segregated along religious lines, and all but 1,000 of the province's 350,000 children attend schools that are almost entirely Protestant or Catholic. <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON> is studying for college entrance exams at mainly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grosvenor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in east <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. After the <LOCATION> Enniskillen </LOCATION> memorial service, she decided to try to arrange an exchange with a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> high school. `` I never thought it would be anything big, just a small meeting,'' <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON> said. `` I was a very quiet person ... but something inside of me said, ` I think you should really advertise this,' and before I knew what I was saying, I asked ... if I could -LRB- address -RRB- the school assembly. `` Well, I went and did that assembly, and they clapped and they clapped and I was just shocked. I did n't think anybody felt the same way I did. And there were hundreds of them. ... They said this is the right thing we're doing.'' The first exchange late last year was with a group of <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> students from two schools, Our Lady of Mercy and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s. As the Grosvenor students waited for the Catholics to arrive, <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON> said, `` they were literally trying to think what these Catholics were going to look like. Are they going to talk funny and what are their names going to be like? `` Because we'd never met, we just had these ideas about the other side, and then when we came together, we just realized they were just like us.'' Over the past year, the students have exchanged further visits. Friendships have grown outside school, with frequent visits to local discos, restaurants and the movies, and shared stays at a government-sponsored camp. The Grosvenor girls have also participated in a play, `` Bridges of Celebration,'' with boys from <ORGANIZATION> Corpus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> secondary school in west <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, an Irish <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> stronghold. It filled the Opera House in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> and will be performed again in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> in February. Recalling the first rehearsal, on neutral ground at <ORGANIZATION> Queen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leanne </PERSON> said: `` When they first walked in ... they just sat down and stared at you I said, ` Oh dear, what's this going to be like?' But then we got to know them and we realized they were great.'' She has no illusions that her activities will change the country. `` No way. I'm never going to become a Catholic and none of them are ever going to become a <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> just because they've met,'' she said. `` But just the fact that we are meeting and becoming friends ... it is harder to hate someone if you know them.''
