<HEAD>Community Jailhouse For Pregnant Inmates Seeks To Preserve Mom-Baby
Bond</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new kind of state prison _ for pregnant inmates only _ opens today in an effort to keep new mothers and their babies together. Although a few other prison systems in the country make efforts to allow mothers to remain for a time with their infants, the <ORGANIZATION> Neil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Roxbury </LOCATION> section will offer features unavailable elsewhere. Separating women and babies at birth causes `` a serious rupture in mother-infant bonding,'' said <PERSON> Lyla </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, co-director of Social Justice for Women, a private, non-profit advocacy group for women prison inmates. The group will run the $ 550,000 program under a contract with the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correction </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a historic step for the state and the country, to show respect for the mother and infant bond,'' Ms. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said last week. Currently, inmates in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> are separated from their children and returned to their cells within days of giving birth. Inmates of the 15-bed facility will be confined to the building but have access to counselors, drug rehabilitation, help in readjusting to society and medical care during pregnancy and after. The first resident, expected to be admitted in January, will find an atmosphere more like a halfway house than a jail. Guards will wear civilian clothes. Only women eligible for early release will be considered for admission, and it is expected that they will complete their sentences at the house. `` Three years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> decided some immediate action was needed,'' Ms. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said. `` We had been working with women at -LRB- the state prison at -RRB- <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>. We saw the numbers of pregnant women growing.'' About 50 pregnant women go through the state prison system every year; there were 17 prison births in 1986, the last year for which figures were available. The average sentence for women convicted in this state is four months, usually for drug-related crimes and prostitution, correction officials said. Since 1980 the number of women imprisoned in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has risen 239 percent, an increase Ms. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> attributed to the general trend nationwide toward incarcerating people and away from sexism. Early in this century women routinely kept their babies with them in prison until people began to worry about the stigma attached to anyone who claimed a prison as their birthplace. More recently, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> started allowing babies born in prison to stay with their mothers until their first birthday, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON>, deputy superintendent for services at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> prison at <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. `` The bonding that results is very positive, both for mother and child, the way the babies develop and mature,'' <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, qualified pregnant inmates receive a 60-day furlough 30 days before they are due to give birth so that delivery can occur outside prison. But most women imprisoned in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, like those in other states, must return to their cells 40 to 72 hours after giving birth. Prison officials around the country said they knew of no such community-based program and said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> program sounded like a good idea. `` I see when the women come in here that one of the hardest things is being separated from their children,'' said <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, associate warden of prisons at the federal minimum-security prison for women in <LOCATION> Alderson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>
