<HEAD>Bowen: Bush Has Hands Full with Medicare Spending Spiral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will have its hands full trying to cap Medicare's spending spiral without cutting into the quality of health care the program provides to 32 million Americans, says outgoing <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>. `` One the reasons it's going to be tougher is because of the massive new numbers of old people that we have coming along,'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said. With overall Medicare costs growing at about twice the rate of inflation, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said the $ 100 billion program is a natural place to look for savings. `` At the same time we have to walk a very tight line and make sure we are not reducing the quality of care and access to care,'' he said in an interview. `` It is my judgment that we're getting close to that level now and we have to be very cautious about going too deep.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> declined to discuss specifics of the final budget the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration will submit next month, but department sources have acknowledged agreeing to about $ 6 billion in net reductions in projected Medicare outlays, mostly by holding down payments to doctors and hospitals. The physician portion of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> _ Part B _ is growing about 15 percent a year and Democrats and Republicans alike in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have said it will undergo close scrutiny in budget deliberations. Beyond the cuts he has agreed to for the next budget, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said, `` We are getting close to the time where further ratcheting down could cause some deterioration in the quality of care and perhaps even access to care.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, who will be 71 in February and plans to retire in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, noted that projections call for the number of people over the age of 100 to increase from 25,000 to 100,000 over the next decade. Not only will they tend to require more medical attention, but many also will used up savings and `` might become a bigger burden'' on public assistance, he said. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, a former two-term governor of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> who said running that state was easier than running the huge <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> department, said his greatest accomplishment was getting President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to back a catastrophic-illness insurance addition to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> in the most sweeping expansion of the program since its birth two decades ago. `` Getting the president's approval over the objections of so many in the Cabinet, that was the tough part,'' said <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>. `` Once the president gave his approval, then it became a lot easier to try to contain the number of additions <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted to add to it.'' On the other hand, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he is disappointed he has been unable to get states to move more quickly to solve medical malpractice insurance problems which he said are threatening access to health care in some regions. He said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration should be ready to introduce federal legislation to override the states on the issue unless they move quickly. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he was not suggesting such a step during the coming year, `` but certainly within four years'' unless the states act. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said there is a remaining need for special emphasis on AIDS `` because of the emotional response of the people. People are scared to death.'' `` I hesitate to single it out as a disease to be treated differently from others, but I think as yet it does need to have a little extra special treatment,'' he said. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he has not been consulted by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> transition officials for a recommendation on who should succeed him. But he said he hopes the incoming president will not view the appointment as minor. `` When you're talking about a kinder and gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, you're talking about <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said of the huge agency that has a larger budget than the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and embraces such programs as Social Security, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and welfare The department also includes the sprawling <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> umbrella that covers such well-known agencies as the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and the Centers for Disease Control. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he hopes <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will give the new <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> secretary authority to pick the heads of those major agencies. `` I think loyalty is one of the most important attributes of somebody who is working for you and the appointing authority sort of draws that loyalty,'' he said. `` I think you can get a lot more accomplished and better serve the public if you have a team rather than somebody who you never knew and never worked with. Maybe you would n't develop the confidence in them you should.''
