<HEAD>After First Dance, School Board Still Wants Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURDY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first dance in this 100-year-old Ozark town's high school is just a memory, but the students who thought it was `` a blast'' may not get an encore. The school board is appealing a court ruling that its policy against school dances is unconstitional. A federal appeals court allowed Saturday night's dance while the matter is considered. Officials restricted the dance to <ORGANIZATION> Purdy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s 161 students, saying they wanted to avoid any chance of trouble. Among those barred were reporters and photographers, and even an alumnus who was the lead plaintiff in the federal lawsuit that brought dancing to <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> <PERSON> High </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>, a 1987 graduate, got only as close as the basketball game that preceded the homecoming dance. `` It's OK, though _ I won,'' <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> said as he watched the game and greeted old friends. `` It's still worth it. The idea was to allow <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> students to have a dance, and we did that.'' <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>, a business school student, and 20 other <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> students and parents sued in 1986 to overturn the school board's written policy banning dancing. Longtime residents in this town of 900 say <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> has never been without a ban on social dancing in the schools. Some have said they associate dancing with drinking, drugs and illicit sex. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> ruled this summer that the school board's ban promoted the values of those who oppose dancing for religious reasons. The board appealed <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s order that they stop enforcing the ban, but the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> is not expected to rule in the case before next year. The dance ban evoked comparisons to the hit movie `` Footloose'' about a similar ban in a fictional town. Although barred from dancing at school, <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> students have held dances at the community center or in neighboring towns. But they said that was inconvenient and unfair. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Buxton </PERSON>, superintendent of the <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> school system, said about 85 students attended Saturday night's dance. He said it went smoothly, but he refused to comment on whether other dances could be expected. Student council president <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said board members attended the dance. But the board members, who sat on the sidelines during the dance talking among themselves, apparently did not cramp students' style. `` It was a blast, we had a great time,'' Miss <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said. `` It was really fun, everybody's dancing,'' said <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON>, a senior who left the dance early. But Miss Francisco, 17, added that the dance had caused controversy and bitterness in the southwestern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> town. `` I do n't think it was worth all that,'' she said. Miss <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, appearing tired but happy after a day that included a college entrance exam and the history-making dance, said early Sunday that she was n't ready to plan another dance. `` I'm still thinking about cleanup for this one,'' she said.
