<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings     12-12 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Base-Closing Panel Will Meet Year-End Deadline, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A presidential commission studying the nation's more than 3,800 military installations is closing in on its goal of determining which ones should be shut down Former Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> Republican who is co-chairman of the 12-member panel, says it will meet its year-end deadline of recommending which bases should be closed. But <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said a final list has yet to be prepared by the commission, which will report to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` People keep asking about a list and wanting to know how many bases, but we do n't have a goal in terms of numbers,'' he said. `` We have n't made any final decisions yet.'' The commission is an attempt to untie a congressional knot that has blocked the Pentagon from closing any bases since 1977. Legislators, loathe to lose the jobs that bases provide, have erected a long and complicated series of barriers to individual closings. `` Closing bases is tough for any congressman,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` You're talking lost jobs and that means unhappy voters. This is near and dear to all our hearts.'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said he does n't know how many bases will be on the final list, but <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> predicted `` the figure will likely be 20 to 25 bases, perhaps a few more.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, who said he has purposefully remained aloof from the panel's work, estimated that annual savings will be about $ 2 billion. Besides evaluating data from the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, the commission is also listening to petitions from congressmen and their constituents. Last week, Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., delivered more than 13,000 letters from Enid, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, urging the panel not to close <ORGANIZATION> Vance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> Earlier, legislators from northeastern states ranging from <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> had written the panel, urging that <ORGANIZATION> Sunbelt </ORGANIZATION> states suffer the most reductions because they said those states had the most bases. After the <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' panel finishes its work, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> will have until Jan. 15 _ five days before he leaves office _ to accept or reject the entire list. He ca n't make any other changes. If <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> approves the list as expected, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could only block the closures if the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> each pass a disapproval resolution. That resolution could be vetoed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, meaning it would effectively take a two-thirds vote in each chamber to block the shutdowns. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> explained that his panel is using a complicated set of criteria to make its decisions. First, installations are being grouped by military mission; for example, all Army depots, all <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> fighter bases, all <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ports for surface ships. Then bases in a particular category will be evaluated for five factors _ mission suitability, including geographical location and ease of deployment; physical facilities in place; the quality of those facilities; quality of life for personnel, such as housing; and community support. Bases at the bottom of each `` mission'' list will be considered for closure, partly by determining if other, higher-ranking bases can become `` receiving'' facilities. Next, cost evaluations will be done, environmental factors such as hazardous waste problems will be considered, and the impact of the lost jobs will be weighed. `` It's an extremely complicated process,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` We have a huge amount of information to evaluate and judgments to make.'' The Pentagon and the services have n't offered any lists. `` What we have done is asked the services for information, a tremendous amount of information,'' he said. `` We're checking that information by sending staff members and commission members out to the bases in some instances, talking to base commanders and local people.'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> insists politics is n't an issue. `` This the most non-partisan committee I've ever been associated with. Believe me, that's the truth.'' `` We do n't look at our charge as having anything to do with politics. We have n't looked at whose district a base is located in,'' he said. `` Obviously, everybody else in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> approaches it from the perspective of politics, but we have n't.''
