<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There were cats with no hair. Cats with too much. Blow-dried cats. Brushed cats. Cats from animal shelters and cats with pedigrees to meow about. The 600 felines at the International Cat Show held in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> this weekend attracted more than 8,000 humans. `` Most of us have multiple breeds,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> `` I own a Persian, several <PERSON> Maine </PERSON> <PERSON> Coons </PERSON> and Chartreux.'' He said cats undoubtedly reflect their owners' personalities. `` If a person is very flamboyant and outspoken, they'll go for a flashy cat, like a black or white Persian,'' said <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON>. `` Someone who is shy and reserved would go for a much more mellow cat, a British Blue or an American Shorthair. `` But a lot of people like bigger and better so they go for the big cats like <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coons </ORGANIZATION> or Rag Dolls, which are 36 inches long.'' A cat named <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> won the Supercat Contest. The long-haired Siamese and tabby mix is named for singer <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>. His owner, <PERSON> Linn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hom </PERSON>, said she may enter her $ 25 cat from an animal shelter in future contests, but she wo n't alter his strict training regimen: `` All he does is sleep and eat all day.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Patriot <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> showed up in this southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> town. <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> have visited, too. Their appearances have been thanks to teacher <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON>, who began dressing up in historical costumes to perk up his `` boring'' history classes. `` After <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON>, I even had a couple of kids come after me wanting autographs,'' said <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON>, laughing. `` I had one woman call me up and say, ` Will you tell my boy <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON> is dead?''' <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON>, 42, conceived his gimmick three years ago when he was tapped to teach history to seventh graders. He had taught science for 16 years, but his history background was limited. `` To me, it was very boring,'' he said. `` I felt that they needed something that they could relate to at that time.'' So the next day he came dress up as <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> for a class on the Revolutionary War. <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON>, who has no formal acting training, recalled the first time he wore the costume he felt `` silly.'' `` You ought to see all the people give me second looks,'' he said. `` I do n't know who was more dumbfounded, the students or the staff _ because teachers do n't dress weird.'' <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON> became principal of Arlington Grade School in September. But that has n't stopped his theatrics. He's treated the school to <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON> and `` the unknown pilgrim.'' He also performs before civic groups. `` Once I get into the costume, I never respond to anything other than that person,'' said <PERSON> Alsman </PERSON>. `` It's serious to me because I think American history is not something to be laughed about.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state has $ 3 million in checks it ca n't seem to give away. Companies and residents across <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> have not cashed thousands of checks worth almost $ 3 million issued by the state <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, 1985, and 1986. Even governmental agencies have been lax. In 1986, for example, about 25 checks to townships, boroughs, cities and county governments totaling more than $ 30,000 were uncashed, according to department records. The blame may simply lie in the foibles of human nature, but for department officials it's a serious problem they're trying to solve. `` Why have n't they been cashed? Who knows?'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>, executive assistant to state Treasurer <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` You almost have to ask the question ` Why have n't auditors caught this?''' The volume of unclaimed payments has led the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to start a program to trace the recipients of wayward checks. Since Nov. 21, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION>, and his staff have returned $ 38,640 to various municipalities. `` Human nature being what it is -LRB- the recipients -RRB- just put them in drawers or use them as book marks. Or kids find checks of their parents after they've died. We're just trying to get money back to the people,'' <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said.
