<FIRST>r w PM-Deficit     12-12 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deficit,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Security, Taxes Eyed By Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Republican co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says the government should consider taking back some of the Social Security benefits paid to higher-income individuals. <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> expressed optimism Sunday that the 12-member panel eventually will produce a consensus report on cutting the federal deficit, with the emphasis on reduced federal spending. `` The position all of us have taken is that we're going to address this based on cutting the spending,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a former transportation secretary in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Meet the Press'' program However, he added, `` this does not mean if we are not able to address the issue on that basis, that there are not a number of members on the commission who would prefer a tax increase.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> specifically mentioned, as `` a last resort,'' some sort of consumption tax that would be adjusted according to each individual's ability to pay. He also offered the term `` rebates'' to describe other revenue sources which do not involve raising taxes. Among these rebates, he said, would be taking back some of the Social Security benefits paid to people with other incomes over $ 90,000 a year, and collecting repayment of some Medicare benefits from the estates of wealthy elderly recipients who die. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said he did not think much of the savings could be achieved in military spending. `` Over half the budget is now in entitlements and interest. Unfortunately, that's where we're going to have to go if we're going to find reductions in spending,'' he said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' Democratic counterpart on the panel. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, appeared on the same program and said he believes that simply cutting spending wo n't be enough. `` I must tell you that in my judgment I have not found sufficient spending cuts to make up the shortfall'' in meeting a deficit-reducing target, said <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>. Such a finding by the panel would be directly at odds with President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign pledge not to raise taxes. Democrats are turning up the heat for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to show how he would close the $ 35 billion gap in meeting next year's deficit-reduction goal. `` I have n't seen a way to get there without some increased revenue. Hopefully we'll find it. If we do n't, I'm going to be for some increased revenue,'' said <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a former Democratic national chairman. Tax increases, while viewed as political poison, have been identified by many economists as the only realistic way to slash deficits and calm nervous financial markets. Though <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> has expressed similar opinions in the past, he was unusually blunt in Sunday's public appraisal. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> said he would consider so-called `` sin taxes'' on alcohol and tobacco, or a gasoline or other broad-based energy tax, as likely sources for the needed revenue. Such ideas have received broad support from many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> also agreed that Social Security payments to high-income Americans _ such as himself _ should be taxed. Upper-income recipients of Social Security now pay taxes on half their benefits under a provision that was part of a 1983 change in the law. Some commission witnesses have suggested boosting that level to 85 percent.
</TEXT>
