<HEAD>20 Men, 12 Woman Selected 1989 Rhodes Honorees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 20 men and 12 women named <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rhodes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scholars </ORGANIZATION> represent 26 states and include a martial arts expert and a 23-year-old doctoral candidate who started college at age 12. Many of those awarded 1989 Rhodes Scholarships for two years of study at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> showed strong interest in using their education to battle AIDS, poverty, hunger and homelessness, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Rhodes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scholarship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>. The group includes students with aspirations in politics, medicine and writing, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said Sunday, adding that at least three worked to support themselves while attending college. The scholarship recipients were chosen during meetings held nationwide Wednesday and Saturday. Four winners are from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, three from <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and two from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> had with five winners, <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> had four and <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> two. One of the winners, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clemente </LOCATION>, works 20 hours a week as a waitress and squeezes in volunteer work with the Meals on Wheels organization for the needy while attending the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON> expects to graduate in May with a double major in political science and international relations with a minor in peace and conflict studies. `` When I finish at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> I would like to work at an international institution,'' she said. `` I would like to work in arms control, like in western European-United States relations. `` Someday, I think I'd like to teach college. But I'd like to have some kind of effect on policy first,'' she said. Another winner was <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubois </PERSON>, who entered <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> at age 12. <PERSON> Dubois </PERSON>, who has published numerous research papers in high energy physics, expects to receive his doctoral degree from the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> next year. Another winner was <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Uphoff </PERSON>, who won first place in a second-degree black belt taekwondo competition in 1986 and was ranked among the nation's top 10 competitors in the martial arts field in 1986 and 1987. <PERSON> Uphoff </PERSON>, a natural sciences and public health major at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, plans to study law at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> before going to medical school. The Rhodes Scholarships were established in 1902 by the estate of <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, a British philanthropist and colonialist. He had hoped the scholarships would contribute to world understanding and peace. Among the qualities sought in scholars are proven intellectual and academic excellence, integrity, respect for others, the ability to lead and use their talents fully. Scholarship winners will receive college and university fees and a stipend to cover living expenses. Women have been allowed to apply since 1976. A total of 2,532 American students who have received the scholarships since the program started in 1903. To qualify, scholars must be unmarried and between ages 18 and 24.
