<HEAD>Earthquake Relief Makes Unlikely Bedfellows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 From the Jewish state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to the Moslem nation of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the earthquake in Soviet <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> spurred nations across the world to set aside political differences and rush to the aid of the stricken Soviets. Children opened their piggy banks, musicians offered their art and a search dog wearing a Star of <PERSON> David </PERSON> on his chest was flown into the region as part of an international mission of mercy. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> relief organizations announced that 23 countries worldwide collected about $ 44 million in aid, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. In <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, the donations were so great they could n't all fit onto one plane. A Soviet aircraft loaded with about 80 search and rescue workers, six dogs and 9 -LCB- tons of medical supplies and winter clothing was delayed for hours at Mirabel Airport on Sunday while workers tried to cram everything aboard. Armenians in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> were organizing a medical team and collecting money to help victims, the official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. Though Soviet-Iranian relations improved somewhat with the increasing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, they have often been strained. Iranian leader <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has backed Moslem rebels fighting Soviet and government troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, a 42-member Israeli rescue team headed by an army general flew to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital, to help search for earthquake survivors. The team included experts specially trained in operating heavy cranes, several doctors, and an Alsatian shepherd dog named <PERSON> Tim </PERSON>, who is trained to sniff people under rubble and wore a red Star of <PERSON> David </PERSON> on a white chest cloth. Two other planes were scheduled to fly to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today with a 46-member medical team, equipment and 4 -LCB- tons of medical supplies. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> broke diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war and does not officially recognize the Jewish state, but relations have been gradually warming. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' Armenian community collected millions of dollars for relief. `` This little girl came with her grandfather, and she apparently had a piggy bank that she was saving for Christmas. She said ` Grandpa, instead of me getting something, why do n't I give this''' said <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barsamian </PERSON>, who is working with the <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> chapter. A hastily assembled telethon that ran from midnight Saturday to 6 a.m. Sunday on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> drew $ 2.9 million in pledges, said <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> station KSCI-TV. The telethon was shown on that station, on cable channels throughout <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and on independent stations in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told reporters that four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes had already arrived in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to provide help. The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> branch of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Narodny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, the Soviet state bank, said late Sunday that donations to earthquake relief from the British public had reached $ 1.04 million. Organizers of British relief efforts announced a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> concert to raise money for victims. Conductor <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON>, flutist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Galway </PERSON> and cellist <PERSON> Mstislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> are among those scheduled to perform Saturday. Almost 30 tons of emergency relief supplies, mostly blankets and clothing, were flown out of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, officials said. The supplies were donated mainly by individuals who drove them to the airport from throughout southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Not all the relief efforts went smoothly. A Dutch medical relief crew was refused visas to assist in the rescue operations, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. The source said Soviet diplomats claimed no more foreign relief was needed. Some foreign relief workers said they ran into snags upon reaching the disaster areas. `` The relief effort until you reach the spot here has been very good,'' said <PERSON> Sverre </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilde </PERSON>, a Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officer. `` But here on the spot there is no control.''
