<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fireworks Explosion Kills 61</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with four grafs to update death toll. Picks up 4th pvs,
``They can't ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Illegal fireworks exploded in a crowded street market Sunday and started a chain reaction and fire that spread to five buildings, killing at least 61 people and injuring 45. `` We'll be searching all night. They're still finding bodies,'' said <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Padillo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> commander at the scene. Floodlights lit the narrow street and an alley as rescuers dug into the night, putting bodies on stretchers, tagging them and putting them in ambulances. A bulldozer began plowing away the rubble. At least 61 people were killed, Commander <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejia </PERSON> <PERSON> Guadarrama </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> said early Monday. `` They ca n't get inside the storerooms, but they are full of bodies,'' said <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Castanon </PERSON> <PERSON> Romo </PERSON>, city director of medical services. `` You can no longer talk of survivors.'' At least 11 of the dead were children, officials said. <PERSON> Padillo </PERSON> said at least 45 people were injured, but an official on duty at <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> headquarters put the number at 83. Two firefighters were among the injured, medical workers said. The first explosion apparently was in a market stall set up in a narrow street leading to the popular Merced market and jammed with Christmas shoppers, said <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> worker <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>. Fire spread to a two-story building of candy and fireworks shops, where fireworks also were stored, and to a building of candy shops next door. A city legal official, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON>, said the fireworks were being sold illegally. The shops `` were all full of people buying,'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, another rescue worker said. After the explosions began, an estimated 500 people streamed from the building screaming, `` Get out, get out,'' said <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON>, who was working in shoe store less than 100 feet away. `` At first it sounded like bullets. Then there were more and more and then the explosion,'' <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON> said. The narrow street was crowded with people buying fireworks for the celebration of the Day of the Virgin of <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> on Monday. The explosion began with one crate of fireworks on the end of the street nearest the Merced, said <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrade </PERSON>, who lives next to one of the buildings that caught fire and was in the street at the time. He said boxes of fireworks kept exploding down the street. Windows shattered throughout the block. Spent Chinese firecrackers, charred wood and comic books, twisted metal and tangles of high tension wires littered the street. As smoke billowed from the second floor of the building more than two hours after the fire was reported at 2:40 p.m., six young men on the third floor refused to leave. `` We're staying here to hold onto our things,'' one shouted to police. `` If it were your house, you'd do the same.'' Police sent firemen and police officers into the building. By about 5 p.m. fires had been extinguished in a six-story building across the street and a four-story building down the block. Some smoke also was coming from one floor of an apartment building. For at least an hour, the white smoke could be seen billowing from the site from more than two miles away. As darkness fell, a bulldozer began plowing away the rubble. Distraught relatives searched for missing relatives while vendors and residents vented anger at Mayor <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camacho </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON>, who walked through the water-soaked debris of burned metal, canvas street stalls, and scattered merchandise. `` Many children died here, Mr. <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON>,'' said one man. Earlier, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, a leader of the area's commercial association, said it had been protesting illegal sales of fireworks. He complained that people who do n't belong to the group come in and sell fireworks without permits during the holidays. `` These present a great danger ... to the shops,'' he said. District Attorney <PERSON> Ignacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> <PERSON> Lechuga </PERSON> said that fireworks are illegal to sell without a permit. `` This does not mean there is going to be an attack on Mexican culture,'' he said. `` These things -LRB- fireworks -RRB- are part of Mexican culture.'' `` It's a case of corruption,'' said <PERSON> Andrade </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Angelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Peredo </PERSON>. `` We do n't want street vendors selling fireworks here.'' For years, the Merced was the main market in this city of 18 million, supplying dozens of other markets and individual customers. A new main market was built on the edge of the city in 1982, but the Merced remains important because of tradition and its location about half a mile from the main Zocalo Plaza in a densely populated area.
