<HEAD>School Project Goal: Help Save Wilderness Trail</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Josh </PERSON> <PERSON> Farnsworth </PERSON> stood on a mountainside with snow blowing around him and the wind cutting through his coat. He reluctantly pulled off his mittens to write down the name of the 40-foot tree towering in front of him. `` I think I'm going to call it ` Three Splits,''' said the 9-year-old, as he scrutinized the maple that split at its base into three separate trunks. Then, he measured the base with his scarf and paced off the distance from the tree to a trail marker 15 feet away. <PERSON> Josh </PERSON> and other pupils at <ORGANIZATION> Derby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in neary <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> will use the information to find sponsors for dozens of trees along the 265-mile Long Trail, a hiking trail that runs north-south from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The proceeds will be used by the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> to buy some of the 67 miles of unprotected, privately owned land along the trail. `` The Long Trail is one of the treasures of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. This is one of the few true wilderness experiences on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>,'' said teacher <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Westin </PERSON>. The project also is introducing dozens of fourth, fifth and sixth graders to a different way of learning science, history and math, and a way to apply their skills to benefit their community, he said. The Long Trail program, which includes a pupil-produced history book about the trail, began this fall at a school that has earned a reputation for developing unusual, creative projects that extend beyond its red brick borders and into the 4,200-member community on the Vermont-Quebec border. The school just won an award from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and Local History for last year's project, a set of 109 short stories the pupils prepared and read on a radio station. The school also was honored recently as a finalist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s A + award for its projects, <PERSON> Westin </PERSON> said The projects begin in <PERSON> Westin </PERSON>'s `` Challenge Room,'' a classroom where he was told five years ago to establish a program for gifted pupils. But the program is `` really open to anybody in the school who has a serious interest. It's not just for kids with high IQs,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, guidance counselor. Individual pupils participate for six weeks, three days a week, about 45 minutes each day. Or the projects can involve entire classes, like <PERSON> Josh </PERSON>'s. Earlier this month, he and his classmates boarded a bus for the half-hour drive to the Long Trail on <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Peak </PERSON>. Up on the trail, the youngsters fanned out to pick a tree. Ten-year-old <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenness </PERSON> sat in the snow in front of her tree, a gray birch with roots raised to form a hole above the soil. `` What does it look like?'' <PERSON> Westin </PERSON> asked. `` A troll's house,'' <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> answered. `` Oh, beautiful,'' he said in praise. <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> said the project helps her learn in a way that's more enjoyable than sitting at a desk. `` You learn about nature,'' agreed classmate <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Castl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> said the projects help develop an interest in the outdoors. `` I do n't think it's going to turn them all into environmentalists, and that's not our goal. But I would like them to be at least as aware as they are of video games or what's going on in sports.''
