<HEAD>Cuban Exile Awaits Extradition After Hijacking Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Cuban exile tricked into thinking he had diverted a jet with 128 people to <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> faces extradition from Grand Turk for only the second hijacking attempt of a domestic <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airliner in 2 -LCB- years, officials said. Weary but unharmed, the 121 passengers and seven crew members aboard the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 flight from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> arrived in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Sunday evening. They said the hijacker was not violent and was shocked when he was arrested on Grand Turk, part of the British colony of Turks and <LOCATION> Caicos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> southeast of the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. `` He was horrified to realize he had been tricked,'' said passenger <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blattner </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, identified the would-be hijacker as <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, 26, who left <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> during the 1980 Mariel boatlift <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrence </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> office said the suspect remained in <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turk </LOCATION> and extradition proceedings were scheduled to begin today. A device that <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> claimed to be a bomb proved to be harmless, officials said. <PERSON> Blattner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> apparently wanted to return to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to see his ailing mother. `` A couple of times he leaned over some people and told them everything's going to be all right,'' said passenger <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Patri </PERSON>. The pilot of the Flight 469 was able to get permission to land on <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turk </LOCATION> island where police were able to convince <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> he was in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, who acted as an interpreter during the hijacking, said <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> tapped him on the shoulder and gave him a letter that said in red ink `` This is a hijacking.'' He told <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> he had a bomb and said it would be activated by his watch. `` He said ` I want to stay in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Please tell the captain, we go to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>,'' according to <PERSON> Motta </PERSON>. <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> said the man was very nervous, and that the plane banked to land on the first island it approached. `` As they landed he saw a fire engine -LRB- and several cars -RRB- and said ` Really, we are not in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. I know the cars in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>,''' <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> said. The pilot and the interpreter convinced him that a civilian would have to greet him, and when he left the plane he was arrested, <PERSON> Motta </PERSON> said. It was the first hijacking of a domestic <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flight since May 3, 1986, when a man hijacked a <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> commuter jet with 11 other passengers and two crewmembers en route to <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and demanded to go to <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>. The plane landed at <LOCATION> Hillsboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and the hijacker was arrested. Hijackings to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> were common in the late 1960s and early'70s, prompting the security measures now commonplace at airports. The only previous hijacking involving a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial flight this year occurred in October, when three soldiers in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> stormed aboard an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> during a period of political turmoil in their country. On May 25, a flight mechanic without a pilot's license stole a private jet in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> News </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, and took it on a 1,600-mile joyride to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, where he shot himself as authorities closed in.
