<HEAD>Illegal Fireworks Strewn Amid Fire Debris</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to UPDATE death toll.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strewn throughout the charred, water-soaked debris of what hours before had been a thriving street market were the fireworks that set the market and five buildings ablaze. It happened Sunday, the eve of the Day of Virgin of <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION>. One of the ways Mexicans honor their patron saint is by shooting skyrockets, Roman candles and other fireworks. They keep firing them sporadically through New Year's. Though barred by a little-enforced law, fireworks abound in markets like that on Corona Street, especially during national and religious holidays. A woman of about 60 said authorities have sometimes confiscated the fireworks. `` This year there was nobody. Nobody came to take the fireworks away,'' she said. `` The street was completely full of fireworks. It was full of people. The Day of <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION>. So many dead. My God.'' Authorities early today did n't know what ignited the fireworks, triggering the series of explosions and fire that killed at least 70 people. Some witnesses said a spilled gas tank was to blame, others a carelessly tossed cigarette. But the fire scarred both sides of <LOCATION> Corona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, whipping through the well-known Candy Market, an apartment building, two other structures containing apartments and shops, and yet another where fireworks were stored and sold. `` All these people, it took away part of their lives,'' said <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Guera </PERSON>, who has a market stall and ran to the scene after the first explosion. `` They lost everything, and they live from one day to the next.'' <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> rescue worker <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Guayaberra </PERSON> said 22 of the victims died in one structure next to the apartment building. `` Most of those found dead there were huddled together. Burned,'' he said. Many of them were on upper floors and apparently had shut themselves inside the building to escape the flames, dense curtain of smoke and popping fireworks outside, <PERSON> Guayaberra </PERSON> said. The smoke lifted to reveal the remnants of a bustling marketplace. A child's pail lay on its side in the muck; nearby, a pair of women's shoes. On a table sat blackened soot in the classic pyramid shape that fruit sellers use. Red, yellow and blue berries and the candy <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> street was known for were scattered about. Red and silver Christmas rope draped across the remains of a food stand. Dozens of gasoline cans, like those used to cook tacos and other typical Mexican fare at open-air stands, littered the street. And everywhere, in the grime of <LOCATION> Corona </LOCATION> street and an adjacent alleyway, were Chinese firecrackers, skyrockets and Roman candles.
