<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> launched a bid to stay in office, saying he had `` kept our city together'' in troubled times after the death of Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> announced his candidacy Sunday for next year's special election as a new poll showed him trailing <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> in a one-on-one race for the Democratic nomination `` I look forward to the contest. I know it wo n't be easy,'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> told about 700 supporters at a rally at a downtown hotel. `` I need your help and your hard work and your prayers.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, 54, enters a field of six other candidates who have announced they are vying for his job. The election will be for a two-year term, the remainder of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s second four-year term. `` In the past 12 months, I have been on the firing line day in an day out,'' he told his supporters. `` I've taken some shots, fairly and unfairly, but I have kept our city together and we've made great progress through some very difficult times.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> was elected acting mayor by fellow aldermen during a raucous <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meeting last December after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the city's first black mayor, died of a heart attack. The new mayoral poll, published in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, showed <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> beating <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> by a margin of 59 percent to 30 percent. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> is the son of legendary Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who ruled <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for more than 20 years until his death in 1976. The telephone survey of 1,038 registered <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> voters showed <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> beating <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s chief rival for the support of black voters, by a 56-34 margin. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> are black. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would give <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> the toughest opposition in the mayoral race, garnering 40 percent to <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s 52 percent, according to the poll, which was conducted Dec. 2-5 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on Saturday said he was not a candidate. Political analysts said the survey was very early and did not mean much. `` I do n't put much stock in December polls when the election is the last day of February, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, a professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> University </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> set April 4 as the date for a special election. The Democratic primary is scheduled for Feb. 28. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> has between $ 2 million and $ 3 million in a campaign war chest. `` He's got a large kitty, so obviously he's going to be able to get his message across,'' the analyst said The Democratic primary has generally been tantamount to winning the general election in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s recent history. But that changed somewhat in 1983 when a white <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate made a strong showing in a losing effort against <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The other announced Democratic ca