<HEAD>Prominent Union Leader Given Bail After 900 Days In Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an unexpected move, a court today granted bail to a prominent union leader and four other black activists held for up to 30 months while on trial for treason. The <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> granted bail to <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>, head of the country's largest metalworkers union, and four co-defendants charged with attempting a political takeover of <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>, an inpoverished black township adjoining <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON> was released on bail of 10,000 rand, or $ 4,200. The others each paid $ 2,100. Four of the men, including Mayekiso, spent more than 900 days in custody, while the fifth had been held almost 700 days. The case was adjourned last month and is to resume in February. The trial has attracted international attention due to <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>'s position as general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metalworkers </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and because many activists view the prosecution as an attempt to stifle peaceful anti-apartheid activity Conditions of bail bar the defendants from entering <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>, addressing meetings or granting press interviews. The government alleges that the defendants organized rent and consumer boycotts and sought to undermine the security forces in 1985 and 1986, the height of nationwide black unrest. <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> was one of the most militant townships at the time, and dozens of people were killed in clashes with security forces. In several recent court cases, authorities have taken actions designed to give the appearance of leniency toward anti-apartheid activists. Last week, a judge in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> sentenced four prominent activists to prison terms of six to 12 years following their conviction on treason in a three-year trial. Most observers expected the sentences to be much harsher. In November, President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> granted clemency to the <ORGANIZATION> Sharpeville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Six </ORGANIZATION>, a group of blacks convicted of murder in the mob killing of a black township councilor. Their deaths sentences provoked an international outcry, and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> decided to give them lengthy prison sentences instead. In the past two years, the government has sought to restore control by detaining or restricting leaders of <PERSON> Mayekiso </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Alexandra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> while undertaking a $ 38 million development program in the township. <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>, wedged between affluent white suburbs, is one of the country's most squalid urban townships. Many of the 120,000 residents lack electricity and toilets, and water comes from communal taps.
