<HEAD>Court to Study University Tenure Issue in University of
Pennsylvania Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case capturing the attention of some leading universities, agreed today to study a university's attempt to withhold confidential information from a faculty member who says her denial of tenure was due to illegal discrimination. The court said it will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> officials accused of discriminating against a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> woman denied promotion to full professor. But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had the authority to hear it. The university's appeal was supported by <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>. Lawyers for the other schools said that forcing universities to reveal confidential statements about those being considered for professorships will inhibit candor by those who evaluate tenure candidates. The case began with a complaint by <PERSON> Rosalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tung </PERSON>, an associate professor of management at <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>, after she was denied tenure at the university's <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Tenure is a lifetime appointment to the faculty. Ms. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> filed a complaint with the federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> charging she was the victim of discrimination against women and people of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> race. The commission subpoenaed the university's confidential peer review records for Ms. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> and five other male candidates considered f