<HEAD>Court Rules on Garbage-Privacy Issue in Nebraska Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, already having ruled that privacy rights do not extend to garbage left at curbside for pick-up, today refused to treat differently garbage discarded closer to home. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a convicted Fremont, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, man had no privacy right in garbage cans left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door. Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, today's order sets no national precedent. But it defeats <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON>'s challenge to his conviction for possession of cocaine and gambling records and for promoting gambling. Fremont police and Dodge County Sheriff's deputies, without obtaining a court warrant, searched through the contents of garbage left outside <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON>'s trailer home and outside the tavern he and his roommate owned. They found `` bet sheets'' used by bookmakers. Police previously had been tipped that <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON> was involved in bookmaking. After obtaining a search warrant, law enforcement officers raided <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON>'s home. They found gambling materials and some cocaine inside. <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON> was sentenced to three years probation. The <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON>'s conviction and sentence last Sept. 2, rejecting arguments that the warrantless search of the garbage left for collection on his property violated his privacy rights. The nation's highest court voted 6-2 last May 16 in ruling that police do not need a warrant before sifting through garbage left in plastic bags at curbside. `` It is common knowledge that plastic garbage bags left on or at the side of a public street are readily accessible to animals, children, scavengers, snoops or other members of the public,'' Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> wrote for the court then. `` The police can not reasonably be expected to avert their eyes from evidence of criminal activity that could have been observed by any member of the public,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> court said <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON>'s challenge must fail in light of the May decision. `` Garbage left for collection at a designated location and accessible to the public shall not be accorded constitutional protection'' whether it is on or off someone's private property, the state court ruled. The case is <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, 88-697.
