<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to reinstate a $ 4.5 million libel award won by a former prosecutor against the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>. The justices, citing the lack of `` a properly presented federal question,'' let stand a <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that requires a new trial for <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>'s lawsuit against the newspaper. <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>, now a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> lawyer in private practice, formerly served as an assistant district attorney in that city. He sued the Inquirer and several of its reporters and editors 15 years ago over two series of articles published in late March and early April of 1973. The first series of articles indicated that <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON> had participated in an illegal wiretapping scheme. The second series reported that <LOCATION> Sprague </LOCATION>, at a time when he headed the district attorney office's homocide division, had prevented the bringing of homicide charges against the son of a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> State Police official. The series implied that <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>'s treatment of the case was motivated by personal favoritism. At trial, reporter <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> testified that information for one of the articles about the homicide case came from a confidential source. He refused to identify the source when <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>'s lawyers demanded he do so. The trial judge, noting that <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> was legally entitled to withhold the name under <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s `` shield law,'' told jurors they should not consider any evidence derived from such sources. The state's shield law, similar to those in many states, says no one connected with a news-gathering organization can be forced to disclose confidential sources to any court or government investigation. The jury ruled for <LOCATION> Sprague </LOCATION>, awarding him $ 1.5 million in compensatory damages and $ 3 million in punitive damages. A state appeals court threw out the award and ordered a new trial, and the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld that ruling last May 31. `` The reporter's information is properly admitted and no adverse inference may be drawn from the invocation of the shield law,'' the state court said. It said jurors should be told that invocation of the shield law `` does not establish an affirmative inference either as to the reliability of the source or as to the validity of the information received.'' Plaintiffs and defendants are free to offer evidence or arguments about reliability and validity, the state court said. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> concluded, `` If the shield law is invoked by the defendant to avoid disclosing a source, no inference either favorable or adverse may be drawn ... as to the reliability of the unidentified source or as to the accuracy of the information supplied.'' The case is <LOCATION> Sprague </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, 88-671.
</TEXT>
