<HEAD>Court Upholds Voting Rights Ruling in Arkansas Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today upheld a voting rights ruling that led to the election of a black <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member from <LOCATION> Crittenden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The court, by an 8-0 vote, ruled against an appeal by Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> officials that had challenged the election of <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> as a state legislator. The case began when blacks in <LOCATION> Crittenden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> filed a voting rights lawsuit attacking the county's at-large system for electing two House members. The suit contended that the system deprived black voters of a chance to elect a black to the House. A special three-judge federal court agreed last April that the system violated the federal Voting Rights Act. The three-judge court threw out the results of a March 8 primary election in which <PERSON> McGee </PERSON>, who is black, was defeated by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockley </PERSON>, who is white, for the Democratic nomination. The lower court split the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voting district into two single-member districts, and on Sept. 20 <PERSON> McGee </PERSON> won the nomination. That was tantamount to election on Nov. 8, since no Republican ran for the seat. <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> and the other state officials said the federal court improperly threw out the results of the first primary and ordered a new election. But the federal court said the voting rights law was violated, although it did not find intentional discrimination against blacks. The law does not require minority groups to prove intentional discrimination before getting courts to order election changes. The three-judge court noted that there is ample evidence that black voters in <LOCATION> Crittenden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> were deprived of a chance to elect one of their own. It said its conclusion is supported by evidence of highly racially polarized voting. One of the new single-member districts created by the lower court has a population of more than 60 percent black. Today's decision, not accompanied by any opinion, upheld the three-judge court ruling. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, hospitalized last week for treatment of pneumonia, did not participate in the vote. The case is <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 88-554.
