<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal in Death of Marine in Virginia Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case it previously used to give military contractors sweeping immunity from being sued, today rejected an appeal by a family seeking damages for the death of a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> helicopter co-pilot. The court, without comment, refused to order a new trial in a lawsuit stemming from a 1983 helicopter crash in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. A federal jury in 1985 ordered helicopter manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Sikorsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> to pay $ 725,000 to the family of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>, who drowned April 27, 1983, when his CH-53 helicopter crashed <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> and the three other crew members survived the crash impact. The three others escaped through emergency hatches, but <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> was unable to open his hatch against the pressure of the water. His family said the design was defective, arguing the hatch should have opened inward to permit escape. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in May 1986 threw out the jury award against <ORGANIZATION> Sikorsky </ORGANIZATION> and its parent company, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in an important 5-4 ruling last June, substantially upheld the appeals court decision. The high court said a military contractor is protected from suit when it makes equipment conforming to `` reasonably precise'' Pentagon specifications and the company warns the government about any potential dangers of which the company is aware. But the justices sent the case back to the 4th Circuit court to determine whether the appeals court improperly acted as a trial court and decided factual issues. The 4th Circuit court said in August it did not usurp the jury's function `` No reasonable jury could have found for -LRB- the <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> family -RRB- on the facts presented,'' the appeals court said. `` It is clear in this case that the military contractor defense was established as a matter of law.'' In its latest appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> family argued there are factual issues that should be submitted to a jury. The family said, for example, there is a question whether the government actually approved Sikorsky's design and whether the government's specifications for the escape hatch were reasonably precise. The case is <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>, 88-677.
