<HEAD>Court Asks Administration Viet of Fine Against Maryland Paper Mill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today asked the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for its view of a fine of nearly $ 1 million against a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> paper mill operator for failing to comply with a federal clean water law's reporting requirements. The court said it wants to hear from <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers before acting on a challenge to a key provision of the act authorizing citizens and environmental groups to sue alleged polluters. The court is not expected to say whether it will grant full review to the case before hearing from the administration, which could take months. <ORGANIZATION> Simkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> runs a paper mill in <LOCATION> Catonsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, on the banks of the <LOCATION> Patapsco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> sued the company for failing to monitor and file quarterly reports on discharges into the river from Aug. 1, 1981, to March 31, 1984. Under the federal Clean Water Act, the company's permit to operate the mill required it to monitor discharges and report them. <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> faced fines of up to $ 10,000 a day, or a total of $ 9.77 million. A federal judge assessed penalties of one-tenth that amount, $ 977,000, payable to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. There was testimony that the company's plant supervisor did not regard sampling of its discharges as a priority. The <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with members nationwide, charged that <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> had discharged copper into the Patapso at 10,000 times the safe levels for fresh water, and that oil and grease in the river from the mill were twice the allowable limit. The company said the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> did not have the legal authority to sue it because the club suffered no direct injury, and also that the suit should be dismissed because it was filed after <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> stopped violating the law's reporting requirements. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last May upheld the fine. The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> established that at least one of its members who uses the <LOCATION> Patapsco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for recreation was injured by <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON>' violations. Fines for failure to monitor and report possible pollution `` can be an important deterrence against future violations,'' the appeals court added. The appeals court, citing a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision, said such private citizen suits under the clean water law may not be `` based upon wholly past violations.'' The appeals court added that <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> was violating the law at the time the suit was filed in late 1984. The company did not file a complete quarterly report until January 1985, nearly three months after the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> filed suit. `` It is true that <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON>' failure to sample occurred solely before <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> filed suit,'' the appeals court said. `` But <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON>' monitoring obgligations were not designed to be a mere academic exercise.'' `` Unless a permit holder monitors as required, it will be difficult if not impossible for state and federal officials ... to know whether or not the permit holder is discharging effluents in excess of the permit's maximum levels.'' The appeals court also noted that <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> began monitoring its discharges after it was alerted by the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> that it was about to be sued. The case is <PERSON> Simkins </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, 88-660.
