<HEAD>Meteor Shower Coming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shooting stars will brighten skies around the world tonight and tomorrow night, offering viewers plenty of chance to make a wish in areas with clear skies. The Geminid Meteor Shower is one of the year's most spectacular examples of shooting stars, according to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory, with the best show coming in the hours after midnight on Tuesday and Wednesday mornings. Up to 50 meteors per hour will be visible if skies are clear, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>. Meteors are caused when tiny chunks of space debris, usually no larger than a grain of sand, enter the Earth's atmosphere and burn up. This shower is caused by bits of an extinct comet and will be visible all over the sky.
