<TEXT>
 Sixteen Filipinos who survived the infamous Bataan Death March while serving in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> during World War II have been awarded medals 46 years after their ordeal. Army Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paulson </PERSON> recognized the veterans' sacrifice at a ceremony Sunday featuring a flyover by five World War II vintage aircraft The 16 honorees, many infirm with age, received the Bronze Star and Prisoner of War medals for their internment by the Japanese following the 65-mile forced march blamed for the death of 10,000 abused, ill and undernourished prisoners. The Japanese forced about 78,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Filipino soldiers to make the five-day walk in strong tropical heat after surrendering following heavy fighting in 1942. `` The brutality was incredible. I saw people decapitated for falling behind,'' said march survivor and author <PERSON> Mariano </PERSON> <PERSON> Villarin </PERSON>. The veterans, who settled in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> after the war, were honored with the medals after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> recently passed a bill recognizing them as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen and acknowledging the trials they endured.
