<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Age Suit,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Avoids Decision on Pennsylvania Age-Bias Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, avoiding a decision on an important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment, today dismissed the case of a laid-off <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> man. By an 8-1 vote, the justices said in effect that they had made a mistake when agreeing to decide whether <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON>'s lawsuit against his former employer, <ORGANIZATION> Harbison-Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refractories </ORGANIZATION>, should proceed to trial. The court's action was carried in a one-sentence, unsigned decision dismissing the case as `` improvidently granted.'' Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> dissented. The effect is to leave intact an appeals court victory for <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON> that clears the way for further trial court proceedings in his case. <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Dresser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, sells specialized ceramic brick products primarily to steel producers. <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON> worked as an installation specialist for <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON> from 1965 to 1982. In July 1982, several employees of <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON>'s Iron and Steel Marketing Support Group were laid off, including <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON>. He then was 55. <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON> sued in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> in 1984, contending that he was laid off and not recalled to work because of his age. His lawsuit pointed to a 39-year-old installation specialist with less seniority who was not laid off until November 1982 and then recalled eight months later. Lawyers for <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON> contended that the other employee, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Faust </PERSON>, was retained because of his more diverse work experience. A federal judge threw out <PERSON> Brieck </PERSON>'s suit, ruling that <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON> had articulated legitimate, non-discriminatory business reasons for laying off <LOCATION> Brieck </LOCATION> while retaining a younger man with less seniority. But the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the suit last year. The appeals court ruled that an employer charged with violating the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act can not avoid trial by articulating legitimate business reasons if the suing employee presents `` a reasonable inference that the employer's proffered explanation ... is unworthy of credence.'' The appeals court added: `` The question is not whether the employer's asserted reason is plausible, but whether there is also evidence of record which, if credited, could render the reason implausible.'' Lawyers for <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON> had argued in a session before the justices Oct. 31 that the appeals court ruling would virtually eliminate pretrial dismissals in employment discrimination cases. The case is <PERSON> Harbison-Walker </PERSON> vs. Brieck, 87-271.
