<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a ruling likely to mean millions of additonal dollars for some hospitals, today barred the government from retroactively applying rules limiting reimbursement paid to hospitals treating Medicare patients. By a 9-0 vote, the court rejected <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive application of the government's reimbursement formula. The justices upheld a ruling that awarded more than $ 2 million to seven hospitals. The administration said more money could be at stake. The government in 1981 adopted a rule that excluded from the Medicare reimbursement formula for private hospitals the wages paid by hospitals owned by the federal government. The idea was to save money by not applying national pay scales to private hospitals in areas with lower wage levels. But the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> adopted the new rule without allowing a time for the public to comment on the proposal. The formula was challenged by private hospitals and thrown out by a federal judge as a violation of proper rule-making procedures. The federal agency adopted the rule again in 1984 using the correct procedure. But this time the department applied the rule retroactively to reimbursement sought by the hospitals beginning July 1, 1981. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today upheld a ruling by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here that the formula may not be applied retroactively. `` Our interpretation of the Medicare Act compels the conclusion that the