<HEAD>Survivor: Car Split Like a `Ripe Tomato'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Train Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One moment <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> was heading toward <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> aboard a commuter train, and the next he was scrambling through a rail car roof that had `` split open like a ripe tomato. `` We were sitting next to the aisle in the buffet and when the crash happened we were thrown down the train,'' <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> said today as he awaited treatment for a head injury at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. `` All I can remember is dust and debris as you've never experienced it in your life.'' <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION>, was among more than 100 people injured when a British Rail commuter train slammed into a stopped train at <LOCATION> Clapham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> during this morning's rush hour and then a freight train on an adjoining track rammed into the wreckage. Dozens were killed. `` There was furniture and enormous lumps of metal flying everywhere,'' <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> said. `` You see pictures of things like this but when you're in the middle of it, your life goes in front of your eyes. `` The whole of the buffet car disintegrated,'' <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> said. `` The roof split open like a ripe tomato and that's how we got out. We tried to find people underneath the rubble but there was so much debris, there was nothing we could do. `` I think the woman who was in there was dead _ and there was a man lying dead on the tracks we we got out,'' <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Underhill </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Farnborough </LOCATION>, said there was `` a hell of a bang'' as his train approached <PERSON> Clapham </PERSON>. `` The train seemed to shoot backwards and the guy opposite me flew into my face,'' said <PERSON> Underhill </PERSON>, who also was taken to St. <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s. `` Amazingly enough, there was not a lot of panic. It was fairly calm and people were helping one another to get out. I saw one man helped out who had lost his foot and there were many others with terrible injuries.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Mintram </PERSON>, 37, of <LOCATION> Bournemouth </LOCATION>, received 20 stitches at the scene for a head wound. `` It seemed to me, the coach I was on, half -LRB- the people -RRB- were OK and half were bad news,'' he said. He said the woman sitting next to him was killed. `` There was no panic. None whatsoever, no screaming,'' <PERSON> Mintram </PERSON> said. `` We were out in 30 seconds. We climbed out through the roof. There were no seats left. It was a rubbish heap.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Crump </PERSON>, 40, from King's Somborne, was in the back car of the train that hit the stopped commuter train. `` Surprisingly there was no panic whatsoever. I suppose we were in the most fortunate part of the train. We had heard the bang and a terrible screeching sound,'' <PERSON> Crump </PERSON> said at the crash scene. <PERSON> Alun </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, an ambulance worker, was in the same train. `` There was a school on the other side of the track and the people there started taking in the injured. They reacted remarkably quickly and efficiently,'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. `` There was a doctor on the train and we both rendered first aid where we could.'' <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Larner </PERSON>, 36, from <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION>, said he saw people with metal in their bodies. `` A woman was trapped with metal which was in her chest and we just started to get people out immediately,'' he said. `` It was the most horrible sight I have ever seen.''
