<HEAD>Nation's Oldest Synagogue Celebrates 225th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's oldest synagogue celebrated its 225th anniversary by expressing gratitude for the religious freedom it has enjoyed. `` We have been a symbol -LRB- of religious tolerance -RRB- for both the Jewish world and the gentile community,'' Rabbi <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said Sunday. Almost 300 people of differing faiths crammed into the Touro Synagogue for a traditional Friday night Sabbath service that was seasoned with references to the holiday of Hanukkah. Hanukkah, which means dedication, commemorates the cleansing and resanctification of the Temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Maccabees </ORGANIZATION> following their victory over the pagan Greco-Syrians in 165 B.C. The Maccabees' struggle, said temple President <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusinitz </PERSON>, is `` the first recorded battle for religious freedom in history.'' This year, he also noted, the dedication celebrated by the holiday parallels the rededication of the landmark synagogue. Participants in the Sabbath service and various parties this weekend felt `` a combination of pride and at the same time a certain gratitude to the Jewish and gentile communities that welcomed us,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. In 1759, 100 years after the first Jewish families sailed into <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, the community decided to build a synagogue. The congregants, who by this time numbered 35 families, hired architect <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>. It is assumed that <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, a Quaker who had never seen a synagogue, based his design on <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Touro </PERSON>'s description of his childhood synagogue in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Touro </PERSON> was the temple's cantor. `` There are enough similarities between the two that we feel they have to be related,'' <PERSON> Kusinitz </PERSON> said. The brick building, which stands 95 percent intact, `` is a mixture of Colonial architecture with traditional Jewish motifs,'' <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. `` As simple as it is on the outside, it is as beautiful on the inside,'' <PERSON> Kusinitz </PERSON> said. In 1790, two years before the enactment of the Bill of Rights, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> issued a letter from the synagogue promising the new government of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would give `` to bigotry no sanction, to persecution no assistance.''
