<TEXT>
 Beside the graves of former slaves and the work of a modern arsonist, people from six states proclaimed that the burned <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bethel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AME </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fork </ORGANIZATION> would once again serve its tiny congregation. Frequently vandalized through the years, the church was rebuilt after it was destroyed by arson in April, only to be torched again in October. A suspect in the second fire is awaiting trial. `` It's like when you lose a loved one,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennet </PERSON> of the 200 people who attended the gathering Saturday in this southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> town about 25 miles north of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` People come and you did n't even know they cared.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who lives in nearby <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> and is not a member of the congregation, said he attended out of respect for those who lost their church. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ewing </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> heard about the rally while attending a stamp collecting convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. He stopped by on his way home and wrote a check for $ 300. <PERSON> Ewing </PERSON> urged others in the audience not to become bitter about the fires. `` It takes only one or two individuals to upset the progress,'' he said. Last year, racial epithets were carved into the walls of the church, which serves a predominantly black congregation, and swastikas were spray-painted on the building. `` People feel that after the civil rights movement of the'60s that racism died. It did n't. But if we work together, we can kill it,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roach </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION>. The Rev. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, pastor of the 25-member congregation, estimated that Saturday's donations would amount to $ 10,000 to $ 12,000. Rebuilding the church is expected to cost about $ 65,000. The church in this town of 2,600 residents was founded in 1863. Its yard is adorned with headstones, both recent and decades old. In some cases only jagged hunks of rock mark the graves. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said many of the former slaves who founded the church are buried there. Authorities said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON>, 19, of <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> confessed to setting the October fire and is awaiting trial on one count of arson. He has not been linked to the earlier blaze. <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON>, who is white, said he was not motivated by racism but by rumors from friends that the building was used by devil worshipers.
