statement on Senate seat planned this afternoon.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President-elect <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> will be replaced in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by conservative Republican Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, a former aide recently elected to a fifth term as an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> congressman, a party source said today. The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> would make a formal announcement of the appointment later in the day. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s other senator, Republican <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, also were scheduled to make a statement on the subject this afternoon, according to a <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> spokesman who declined to divulge any other information. Coats, 45, was elected in 1980 to fill the 4th Congressional District seat <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> vacated to run for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. He worked in <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s congressional office in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, from 1976 to 1980, and was known to have <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s backing in the jockeying to pick a new senator for <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. In the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, Coats has compiled a staunchly conservative record. His rating for 1986 from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> was 82 percent. His rating the same year from the liberal Americans for Democratic Action was 10 percent. He is a supporter of aid to the Nicaraguan Contras and to the Angolan rebels. In 1984, he attempted to attach an amendment to an omnibus education bill that would have cut off federal aid to schools and states banning voluntary school prayer. The amendment was defeated. Calls to Coats' office were unreturned today. <PERSO