<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON> has made a career of following <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> _ first as his aide, later as a congressman and now as the vice president-elect's apparent successor in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` We call them the two Dans because <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON> worked for him and followed him to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, the 4th District Republican chairman. Coats, 45, was expected to be formally named by Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> this afternoon to fill <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat for the next two years, according to a source in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Coats' rise to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> marks the second time in his career he has filled a vacancy left by <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. In 1980, Coats, then <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s district representative, won his first term in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> House in the same year his boss won the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat Although their careers have followed similar paths, the two men are different in background and style, friends say. Coats was born in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Wheaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and then served in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. He received his law degree by attending night classes at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, a native Hoosier, also attended the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> law school while serving in the National Guard during the Vietnam War. Four years older than <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, Coats joined <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s staff in 1976 after working as an assistant vice president and legal counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In contrast to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, an exuberant campaigner, Coats is `` very low-key,'' said former Secretary of State <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simcox </PERSON>, who went to law school with Coats. <PERSON> Simcox </PERSON>, who had been in the running for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s seat, said of Coats: `` I think a great deal of him. He's an outstanding person.'' Gates called Coats, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> resident, especially attentive to his constituents' wishes. `` He's not ultra-conservative. He really studies what the people want and votes that way. He takes a lot of surveys,'' said <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>. `` He really cares for his people.'' That attentiveness has translated into significant vote-getting appeal, the party official noted. In fact, Coats has never received less than 61 percent of the vote in the northeastern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> district. On Nov. 8, he won 62 percent of the vote in defeating <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, a Democrat who lost to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> in the 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race.
