<HEAD>Court Grants Treasure Hunter Right to Salvage Pirate Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that a treasure hunter has the right to recover cargo and artifacts from the submerged 18th century pirate ship `` Whydah.'' In a unanimous opinion, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' highest court rejected the state's claim of sovereignty over the wrecked wooden sailing vessel, lying beneath the sand in the waters off <LOCATION> Wellfleet </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> where the it foundered in April 1717. `` The ill-fated <LOCATION> Whydah </LOCATION>, nearly three centuries later, has sailed into this court's jurisdiction as the subject of a dispute between contemporary treasure seekers and the would-be modern sovereign of the coastal waters,'' Justice <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> wrote for the high court. He described the case as `` a conflict mired in competing claims of title to the shipwreck and its cargo, involving issues of federal maritime and admiralty law, and disputed dominion over submerged lands in the marginal sea.'' In November 1982, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> and his salvage company, <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surveys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, found `` an unidentified, wrecked and abandoned vessel'' one mile off <LOCATION> Wellfleet </LOCATION> under about 14 feet of water and 5 feet of sand. Since 1983, Maritime Surveys, using sophisticated sensing and recovery technology, has recovered numerous artifacts from the site, while waging legal battles with the state, the federal government and rival treasure hunters over who owns the wreck of the commandeered English merchant ship. Gold, silver, cannons and pistols recovered from the ship have been valued at $ 14 million to $ 25 million, and the total bounty is estimated in the hundreds of millions of dollars. After winning his claim of ownership to the <LOCATION> Whydah </LOCATION> in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> was sued by the state, which asked a state <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to confirm its claim of title to the vessel and its cargo. The <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appointed <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> temporary custodian of the wreck, and on that basis, he won a permit from the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> to salvage the ship. Later, faced with claims from <LOCATION> Clifford </LOCATION>, the state and other searchers, the state court granted <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>'s company title to the vessel.
