<HEAD>Detention Center Destroyed In Cuban Uprising To Be Rededicated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with dedication. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKDALE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new $ 17 million federal prison was dedicated today in this western <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> town, replacing the detention center that rioting Cubans burned in a night of terror 13 months ago. The new beginning gives townspeople the chance to look to the future, but they should not forget the rioting, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Veron </PERSON> warned in his dedication speech. <PERSON> Veron </PERSON> recalled watching the television coverage of the prison going up in flames as <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> detainees rampaged through the <ORGANIZATION> Oakdale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` I can not understand how these defendants wanted to burn down these excellent facilities they had, and think by burning them down and taking hostages they would gain their freedom,'' said <PERSON> Veron </PERSON>. `` It is not up to me, and I express no opinion on the conduct the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should take against those that destroyed $ 15 million in taxpayers' property.'' More than 1,000 Cuban inmates awaiting decisions on whether they would be freed or sent back to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> rioted and took 28 employees hostage on Nov. 21, 1987, at the <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION> center. The siege lasted eight days, and the hostages were released unharmed. Although <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> officials do not want to answer specific questions about security, the new facility has some obvious differences from the old one. Within the 40-acre prison, two of the four dormitories are isolated by a high chain-link fence and a guard post. Also added is a maximum security building, which has over 50 individual cells. Each cell door has a small hole and each inmate must put his hands through that hole to be handcuffed before the door is opened. The showers also have bars. The new <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION> facility will handle prisoners who have been sentenced by federal judges to prison terms. Under construction at the site is a $ 14 million federal deportation center, which will open in November 1989 to handle detainees. The rebuilt prison has 265 inmates at this time and can accommodate 1,300, prison officials said. There are 400 guards. The deportation center will have 1,000 beds and perhaps as many as another 400 guards, said a spokesman for Warden O.C. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. About 200 people shivered through the rededication ceremonies in the open-air basketball court on the prison grounds. None of the inmates was in sight and the prison looked empty. Despite last year's riot, Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mowad </PERSON> said he looked forward to reopening the prison the community worked so hard to secure and was so proud of when it opened in 1986. `` If someone had been killed there probably would have been more bad feelings,'' he said recently. `` We're ready to get on with the program.'' The town's economy has fluctuated since the riot, and unemployment in <LOCATION> Allen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> is about 11 percent, <PERSON> Mowad </PERSON> said. `` It was 31 percent back in January 1982 when we first started this thing. It was the highest in the country,'' <PERSON> Mowad </PERSON> said. `` It was n't all the prison, but it certainly has been a major reason why unemployment -LRB- went -RRB- down.'' Rioting at the federal prisons in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> two days later erupted shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> had agreed to take back more than 2,500 of the 3,800 Mariel refugees who were locked up nationwide at the time. More than half were in the federal detention center in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>. The takeovers ended after the government agreed to a moratorium on deportations and a one-time-only <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> review of each <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decision.
