 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. NCAA-Discipline The court, in a setback for college basketball coach <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>, bolstered the power of the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> to discipline its member schools. The 5-4 ruling also could help the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collegiate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in its effort to police drug use by athletes at state-run member schools. The court said the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION>, in disciplining <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>, did not violate the constitutional rights of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Las </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegas </ORGANIZATION> coach because the athletic body acted as a private organization, not one operating with governmental authority. The case is <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>, 87-1061. MEDICARE The court barred the government from retroactively applying rules limiting reimbursement paid to hospitals treating Medicare patients. The court, in a 9-0 ruling likely to mean millions of additional dollars for some hospitals, rejected <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive application of the government's reimbursement formula. The case is <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1097. EVIDENCE The court ruled that a government investigator's conclusions and opinions are not `` hearsay'' and may be used as evidence in federal trials. The justices reversed a federal appeals court ruling that had ordered a new trial in a wrongful-death lawsuit against the makers of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> airplane in which two people crashed six years ago. But today's 7-2 vote appeared to make a new trial necessary, because the justices also ruled that the plaintiffs' lawyers wrongly were limited in presenting their case. The case is Beech Aircraft vs. <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>, 87-981. GARBAGE The court, having already ruled that privacy rights do not extend to garbage left at curbside for pick-up, refused to treat differently garbage discarded closer to home. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a convicted Fremont, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, man had no privacy right in garbage cans left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door. Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, today's order sets no national precedent. The case is <PERSON> Trahan </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, 88-697. TENURE The court agreed to study a university's attempt to withhold confidential information from a faculty member who says her denial of tenure was due to illegal discrimination. The court said it will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> officials accused of discriminating against a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> woman denied promotion to full professor. But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had the authority to hear it. The case is <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-493. LIBEL AWARD The court refused to reinstate a $ 4.5 million libel award won by a former prosecutor against the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>. The justices, citing the lack of `` a properly presented fed