<HEAD>Sonja Henie's Frozen Heart Sculpture Finds New Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sonja </PERSON> <PERSON> Henie </PERSON>'s icy heart wo n't be left out in the cold when the warehouse where it has been stored for nearly 48 years is demolished to make room for a frozen foods plant. The blue-green ice sculpture was presented to the famous Norweigian skater and movie star during a Valentine's Day 1941 performance at the Ak-Sar-Ben Coliseum _ the star's one and only appearance in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. Miss <PERSON> Henie </PERSON> said she would return for it some day. But she died in 1969 without ever claiming what <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> newsman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuralt </PERSON> once called `` the longest-running, open-ended, most enduring publicity stunt of all time.'' <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON>, who was an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> publicist when he carved the heart, said Miss <PERSON> Henie </PERSON> found her appearance in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> less than heart-warming. Among other things, he said, she was upset that high costs cut into her profits. `` All she was really interested in that night was to get it ... out of the dressing room because it had green-blue dye and it was dripping on her dressing room floor,'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON>, now an executive for <ORGANIZATION> Litton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, office. So the heart was taken to the <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Storage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> warehouse near the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and there it has remained over the years, gaining in notoriety as it shrunk from its original 100 pounds to about 60 pounds. `` It is highly flattering that something made 45 years ago out of the most perishable substance on earth _ frozen water _ would still be in existence in a cold storage warehouse in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> said. When plans were announced to tear down the warehouse to make way for a new <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> frozen foods complex, there was some concern about the fate of the heart. But <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Storage </ORGANIZATION>, said he has moved the sculpture to his company's new warehouse in a converted meat-packing plant. `` It's in a box in a room with a lot of raw materials for making pet food _ liver, salisbury glands, items like that,'' <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON> said. `` I'd hate to throw it away. I'd probably get in trouble.'' `` I suppose some good-hearted guy will continue to take care of it,'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> said. `` It has been kind of like a relay race. There have been 10 or 12 people who had custody of it from one time to another.'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Elk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, said he hoped to visit the heart during a trip to <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> later this month. He recalled how the ice show's promoter approached him in 1941 about a publicity stunt, but warned <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> that Miss <PERSON> Henie </PERSON> was n't always friendly. <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> carved the heart out of a keg of ice and presented it to Miss <PERSON> Henie </PERSON> at the Valentine show. As the promoter had warned, however, she gave <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> the cold shoulder. `` As kind of an exit line, I said we would keep it until she came back to <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> again,'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> said. `` We put it in the back of a pickup _ it was 10 degrees below zero that night. After the show we took it to <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Storage </ORGANIZATION> and stored it there. It was forgotton until I came back after World War II and was in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> for Christmas before the victory march in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Oldfield </PERSON> said no one has tried to buy the heart but that the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> has called about it. `` They found somebody with a 36-year-old cake in storage and they were toying with the idea of a strange category that would include such things, but nothing came of it,'' he said.
