blocking the suspension and continued coaching. The <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> had violated <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>'s constitutional rights by failing to afford him due process during its lengthy investigation Today, however, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned the lower court order in ruling that the athltic organization, lacking governmental authority, was not required to adhere to constitutional standards in its probe. <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>'s lawyers had warned that lifting the court order against the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> could mean the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> may throw <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION> out as a member if the university refuses to suspend <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>. Individuals and private organizations generally can not violate someone's constitutional rights. Only a government and its agents can do that because the Constitution protects against governmental, but not private, wrongdoing. The <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> is a private organization representing nearly 1,000 colleges and universities, more than half of them state-run. Today's ruling could enhance the organization's power to investigate drug abuse by athletes by not requiring it to observe constitutional restrictions in probing for abuses. In other action, the court: _ Barred the government from retroactively applying rules limiting reimbursement paid to hospitals treating Medicare patients. The court, in a 9-0 ruling likely to mean millions of additional dollars for some hospitals, rejected <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration arguments that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive application of the government's reimbursement formula. _ Ruled that a governfment investigator's conclusions and opinions are not `` hearsay'' and may be used as evidence in federal trials. The justices reversed a federal appeals court ruling that had ordered a new trial in a wrongful-death lawsuit against the makers of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> airplane in which two people crashed six years ago. _ Having already ruled that privacy rights do not extend to garbage left at curbside for pick-up, refused to treat differently garbage discarded closer to home. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a convicted Fremont, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, man had no privacy right in garbage cans left outside for collection four feet from his home's back door. Unlike the court's decision last May in a case from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, today's order sets no national precedent. _ Agreed to study a university's attempt to withhold confidential information from a faculty member who says her denial of tenure was due to illegal discrimination. The court said it will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> officials accused of discriminating against a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> woman denied promotion to full professor. But the justices indicated that they will be studying a very narrow issue in the case _ one dealing with which trial court had the authority to hear it. _ Refused to reinstate a $ 4.5 million libel award won by a former prosecutor against the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>. The justices, citing the lack of `` a properly presented federal question,'' let stand a <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that requires a new trial for <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>'s lawsuit against the newspaper. _ Rejected an appeal by a family seeking damages for the death of a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> helicopter co-pilot. The court, without comment, refused to order a new trial in a lawsuit stemming from a 1983 helicopter crash in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The court previously used the case to give military contractors sweeping immunity from being sued. In today's high court opinion in the <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON> case, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> is properly viewed as a private actor at odds with the state when it represents the interests of its entire membership in an investigation of one public university.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the fact that <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION> could forfeit its standing as a basketball `` powerhouse'' if it is kicked out of the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> does not mean the university was forced to fire <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>. `` That <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION>'s options were unpalatable does not mean that they were nonexistent,'' he said. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Dissenting were Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. White, in an opinion joined by the others, said <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement to abide by <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> rules governing conduct of its athletic program made the <OR