industry. However, <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said the controversy has not been confined to his agency, noting that a lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> has resulted in an injunction prohibiting <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> from harvesting mature timber on some lands the agency administers in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. Also, the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is being challenged in court over its 1987 refusal to designate the owl a threatened or endangered species. Meantime, authorities in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> voted last week to deny a place on the state list of endangered or threatened species to a robin-sized seabird called the marbled murrelet after biologists were unable to determine the bird's population. `` We simply do n't have good baseline data on the murrelet's population size nor any trends indicating changes in that population,'' said <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON>, chief of the wildlife division for the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> The Oregon chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> had petitioned to place the bird on the list under the new Oregon Endangered Species Act last January.
