<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today threw out a <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> man's sodomy conviction because he was barred at his trial from questioning the alleged victim, a white woman, about her living with a black man. By an 8-1 vote, the justices overturned the conviction and 10-year prison sentence of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Olden </PERSON>. The court expressed skepticism about the alleged victim's testimony that she did not consent to have sex with Olden. Olden and a friend, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, were indicted on kidnapping, rape and forcible sodomy charges. Both men, who are black, were accused of forcing a young white woman to have sex with them after they met her at a bar in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, Ky. The woman initally told police she was raped by four men; later said she was raped by Olden and <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, and at trial said <PERSON> Olden </PERSON> was the sole rapist. She also testified at trial that Olden threatened her with a knife, although in earlier statements to police she did not allege that he was armed. Olden and <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said the woman consented to having sex with them. At the trial, the defendants' lawyers sought to introduce evidence that the woman was living with another man, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, who is black and a half-brother of Olden. The defense lawyers said the woman concocted the story of being raped to prevent <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> from learning the truth that she consented to sex with the defendants. The trial judge refused to let the defense lawyers question the woman about whether she was living with <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>. The judge said allowing evidence of an inter-racial living arragnment would have created `` extreme prejudice'' against the woman. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was acquitted. Olden was acquitted of kidnapping and rape, but convicted of forcing the woman to commit sodomy. But today the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Olden </PERSON>'s right to confront his accuser was violated by excluding the evidence of the alleged victim's living arrangement. In an unsigned opinion, the court said, `` Speculation as to the effect of jurors' racial biases can not justify exclusion of cross-examination with such strong potential to demonstrate the falsity of -LRB- the alleged victim's -RRB- testimony.'' Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> dissented on grounds that the court should have held formal arguments in the case rather than summarily reversimg Olden's conviction. The case is Olden vs. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, 88-5223.
