<HEAD>Police Say Drinking Boy Stole Plane, Landed Safely At Busy Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 17-year-old boy who police say had been drinking because of family problems took a small plane on a three-hour flight through some of the nation's busiest airspace before another pilot talked him down. Air traffic controllers and some commercial flights were on alert Saturday night as the boy, who had only a few hours of flying instruction, zigged and zagged across major air corridors serving <ORGANIZATION> Newark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> airports. The boy, whose name was withheld because of his age, allegedly broke into a trailer at <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Middlesex </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and took keys to a single-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> 172, <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> police Sgt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said. `` He got the plane off the ground, and I guess nobody noticed because the airport is closed at night,'' <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said. `` It was pretty good in the dark.'' The stolen plane went unnoticed until the boy got about 18 miles away from the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> airport and began radioing a `` mayday'' distress signal, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahill </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which owns and operates the three major airports. The signal was heard all along the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> region's air traffic facilities, said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergen </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Fede