<FIRST>r w AM-WaterPollution     12-12 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Pollution,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Report Cites Lax Water Pollution Enforcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the states are not enforcing water pollution regulations against 150,000 drinking water sources serving 36 million travelers, workers, students and others drinking water outside the home, according to an internal <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report released Monday by a conservation group. Among these sources are those aboard trains, buses and airplanes, the report said. The group, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said it planned to sue the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> over deficiencies in enforcement of the Safe Drinking Water Act. The federation said it gave <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> the required 60-day notice of such suits on Monday. Such a suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> would seek an order requiring <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to perform duties spelled out in the act, said the federation's water specialist, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> The federation released an agency audit of so-called non-community systems carried out by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general. The inspector general in 1986 and 1987 checked water enforcement programs in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> where an estimated 3 million people were using those systems. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said in the report they believed those four states were representative of the nation, which has 150,000 non-community water sources serving 36 million people. `` State personnel in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> estimated that 40 percent of their -LRB- non-community systems -RRB- were out of compliance,'' the report said. `` The numbers were similar for <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> _ 40 percent in fiscal year 1986 and 29 percent in fiscal year 1987. The Federal Reporting Data System indicated only 7 percent of the -LRB- non-community systems -RRB- in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> had monitoring violations in fiscal year 1987. However, our review revealed that these numbers were substantuially understated.'' For coliform bacteria, to be checked every three months unless otherwise specified by the state, the report said: `` The state of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> estimated that 90 percent of the -LRB- non-community systems -RRB- did not comply with federal testing requirements.'' In the document, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said the shortcomings were `` a direct function of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s long-standing policy to place priority on assuring compliance by community water systems.'' Non-community systems have looser testing requirements than community systems, but even those were being ignored, the report said. In 1971-1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> was able to trace to non-community water systems 45 percent of 484 outbreaks of diseases carried by drinking water. An <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman did not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment on the report Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> comments in the document said the agency planned priority attention in the fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1 for the 20,000 non-community systems serving groups other than travelers, and `` will also consider'' requiring state and regional <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> offices to meet quotas for enforcement actions. A non-community system might be a single well serving a school, factory, restaurant, motel or campground. More generally, it is any system serving transients or non-residents, including supplies on buses, trains and planes even though those might get their water from public systems. Suppliers are supposed to post public notices when testing discloses a violation of standards, but `` We found only 11 of 826 monitoring violations had evidence of public notification in the file,'' the auditors wrote. `` State personnel admit that follow-up on public notification requirements is inadequate.'' In some violations, repeat testing is required to ensure that a standard is being met. Out of 145 violations of concentration standards that were checked, repeat sampling was required in 98, but `` only in two instances did the supplier initiate check sampling within the required 24 hours. We found no evidence of any check sampling at all for 28 of the 98 violations. ... In the remaining 68 instances, the supplier delayed the initiation of the check sampling process for periods ranging from two to 37 days,'' the report said. <LOCATION> Pennyslvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> issued notices of violations to suppliers in only 173 cases out of 371 cases in which notices should have been issued, and 56 percent of the notices were issued two months or more after the end of the quarter in which the violation occurred, the report said. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> were not reporting what enforcement actions they took, but the auditors found only seven notices to suppliers out of 600 violations. The states have primary responsiblity for enforcing the federal law except <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, where EPA is directly responsible. In addition, the agency is directly responsible for enforcement on Indian reservations and in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
