<FIRST>u w AM-WorkplaceIllness     12-12 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Workplace Illness,350</SECOND>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Report: Doctors Poorly Trained in Occupational, Environmental
Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most family doctors are inadequately trained to recognize and treat illness that stems from unhealthy environments at home or work, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> panel said Monday. But rather than criticizing individual physicians, the report from the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> committee said the fault lies with `` our highly sophisticated health care system'' in general because it is not geared toward preventive medicine. `` Lacking a solid foundation in occupational and environmental medicine, as well as in the related disciplines of epidemiology and toxicology, most primary care physicians are hard-pressed to keep up with developments in the field,'' the report said. `` Indeed, the general medical literature contains relatively little about occupational and environmental medicine.'' To counter that, the panel's most urgent recommendation was for establishment of a clearinghouse for doctors to call `` when confronted with a patient suspected of having an occupational or environmental disease.'' `` It should be designed so that a single telephone call satisfies the practitioner's informational needs,'' the report said. `` It could be based on an extension of the techniques used by the nation's poison control centers.'' The Institute of Medicine, a branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, is forming a new advisory committee specifically to draw up more detailed suggestions for such a clearinghouse. On a longer range, the panel that turned in its report Monday said physician fee schedules should be changed because `` the current procedure-oriented reimbursement system and the emphasis on efficiency of practice is antithetical to the desired emphasis on prevention.'' Eventually, the committee said, the focus must shift to medical schools, only half of which have a single faculty member `` primarily concerned with occupational health.'' `` Occupational and environmental medicine should be a vital part of the traditional student clinical assignments,'' the report said. `` Because preventative medicine is usually not taught in the clinical years, it is necessary that departments of clinical medicine include occupational and environmental medicine as part of their third - and fourth-year teaching programs. The report also called for more research into occupational and environmental medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
