<HEAD>Pravda Recommends Criminal Charges Against Builders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Charges should be filed against the `` scrap-builders'' of shoddily constructed buildings deatroyed by the earthquake that killed more than 50,000 people in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, Pravda said Monday. The Communist Party newspaper recommended the action in a scathing artlcle about apartment buildings in the devastated region that crumbled into `` concrete and metal graves over victims who were buried alive.'' `` In fragments of concrete panels, it is impossible to know whether there is more sand or more cement,'' it said of the wreckage in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, a city of 250,000 where more than three-quarters of the buildings fell. `` It is time to answer the question, how many criminal cases were filed against the scrap-builders and what was the outcome?'' Pravda asked. `` Who closed their eyes to the warnings of the seismologists, here and in other regions?'' All construction in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is handled by government agencies. American earthquake experts have said a quake of the same strength would have killed only 1,000 people in heavily populated <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> because of the difference in building techniques. Concrete-slab apartment buildings were hastily built throughout the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the past 20 years to ease a chronic housing shortage. The Kremlin has sent a commission to <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> to determine why so many buildings disintegrated in an area where where builders supposedly used construction techniques designed to survive quakes. Authorities have said the temblor last Wednesday was stronger than expected in northwestern <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Photos of the ruins show entire sections of high-rise residential buildings sheared off, with no evidence of steel reinforcing bars at stress points as required in Western countries. `` If the construction of the buildings was better, maybe less would have been destroyed,'' <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bibin </PERSON>, deputy chief of Soviet construction, told a news briefing Monday. A broken slab on which was writtren `` This piece of concrete is not to be used,'' lay in the rubble Monday in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>. Short supply is common in Soviet industry and workers often use the defective or makeshift to finish projects. <PERSON> Bibin </PERSON> said the earth shook vertically during the quake, causing buildings constructed of concrete slabs to collapse. He also said the earth was soft in some areas. `` Why did buildings from three years ago collapse while those of three or five stories built under -LRB- former leader <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> are still standing?'' President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> demanded on television Sunday night. In <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, older low-rise apartment blocks stood unscathed while `` everything built in the years of stagnation collapsed,'' Pravda said, using the Soviet term for the regime of the late <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. `` Geophysicists more than once warned builders of the high seismic activity in northwest <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but stubbornly they continued to raise five - to nine-story buildings,'' the paper said Acccording to <LOCATION> Bibin </LOCATION>, every building more than five stories high collapsed. <PERSON> Kagik </PERSON> <PERSON> Avakyan </PERSON>, a resident of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the city had no buildings taller than two stories until 20 years ago because of the threat of earthquakes.
