 elections and an ability to build a strong base to withstand a Democratic challenge. Coats has never received less than 61 percent of the vote in his northeastern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> district. Last month he won re-election with 62 percent. His selection makes no change in the Democratic-Republican split in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has announced he will resign, probably effective Jan. 2, to allow his successor to gain seniority by being sworn in before the rest of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Jan. 3. However, <PERSON> Coats </PERSON> said he expected to be sworn in with the rest of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Several other names had been mentioned as potential candidates for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s seat, including former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> political director <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>. Both took themselves out of contention several weeks ago. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said his wife was `` very gratified'' with <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>'s decision. Coats was born in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Wheaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and then served in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Like <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, he got his law degree at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. He worked as assistant vice president and legal counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> before going to work for then-Rep. <PERSON> Quayle <