<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> chose his predecessor's treasury secretary as ambassador to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday, another sign of his desire to alter the terms of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s huge foreign debt An announcement from the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Petriccioli </PERSON>, who has a master's degree in economics from <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, will replace <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> los </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, who began his six-year term Dec. 1, has said renegotiating terms of the $ 102 billion foreign debt leads his priority list, and he discussed it with President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at their meeting in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> last month. As Treasury Secretary for the last two years of de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s term, <PERSON> Petriccioli </PERSON> sought a postponement of debt payments because of the financial squeeze caused by the collapse of world oil prices in the early 1980s He negotiated an an agreement with creditor banks signed March 21, 1987, that included $ 7.7 billion in new loans, restructured $ 43.7 billion of the debt and decreased interest rates on $ 8.6 billion loaned in 1983-84. <PERSON> Petriccioli </PERSON>, 60, also worked out <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s purchase of several billion dollars worth of its foreign debt certificates at discount rates this year and helped enforce a `` solidarity pact'' of government, business and labor that helped lower annual inflation from 150.9 percent in 1987 to about 48 percent in 1988. By keeping interest rates high and the peso's value virtually steady against the dollar, <PERSON> Petriccioli </PERSON> also managed to accumulate an all-time record of $ 16 billion in foreign currency reserves last year. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has promised to lighten the burden of austerity economics on average Mexicans, whose real wages have been cut in half during the past six years. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has noted <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economic growth remained near zero during that period and said renegotiating debt payments is vital to provide money for industrial development. Foreign creditors have balked at <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s proposals to reduce the $ 13 billion it is paying in debt service this year. Debt service payments for next year are estimated at $ 16 billion.
