<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Journalist <PERSON> Loudon </PERSON> <PERSON> Snowden </PERSON> <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>, who wrote <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The View From Here'' column and chronicled the magazine's history in a 1986 book, died Monday of cancer at age 63. After serving in the Marines and graduating from college, <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> joined Life in 1949 as an office boy. In the 1950s he distinguished himself as a reporter, correspondent, bureau chief and staff writer. He was later known for his close relationship with the Mercury astronauts and wrote their personal accounts of their missions for Life. <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> started `` The View From Here,'' the magazine's first personal column, in 1964 and, despite interruptions, was writing it up until his death. In 1969, <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> was named Life's assistant managing editor and held that position until the weekly ceased publication at the end of 1972. He rejoined the writing staff for Life's revival as a monthly in 1978. In 1986, <PERSON> Knopf </PERSON> published <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON>'s `` The <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>,'' which tells the history of Life from an insider's viewpoint A memorial will be held in January. <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> is survived by his wife <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>, from whom he has been separated for more than a decade, and their four children. A son, <PERSON> Loudon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, is a well-known folk-rock singer and songwriter. He is also survived by his longtime companion, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, and their 6-year-old daughter.
