land of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> donated money, food and clothing Monday. Officials said about $ 50,000 had been collected. An Armenian priest tearfully embraced an 8-year-old boy as he dropped the equivalent of $ 20 from his piggy bank on the priest's desk <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> relief organization said it planned to send relief supplies, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. It was believed to be the first time <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has offered emergency help to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a former ally with whom political relations have been strained for nearly three decades. Other communist and socialist nations, including <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, rushed to send help, reports said. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> will send 20 helicopters to help with relief efforts, a foreign ministry official in <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> said Monday. The quake also shook <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s eastern province of <LOCATION> Kars </LOCATION> on the Soviet border, killing four and leveling 200 homes. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s efforts to help Armenians also come against a backdrop of longstanding hatred between the two peoples. Many Armenians still blame <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> for a genocide in 1915 that is said to have killed 1.5 million Armenians.
