<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said Monday his outlawed union Solidarity is ready to compromise for talks with Polish authorities and will strike only as a last resort. `` We are ready for agreement and compromise ... but we should be considered as free and independent,'' he told a news conference before ending a four-day visit to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` We are even ready to talk to the devil and consider that hell exists on condition that he recognize there is a heaven.'' About 200 cheering supporters at the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> airport chanted `` Bravo, <PERSON> Lech </PERSON>!'' to welcome the founder of Solidarity back from the first trip abroad <LOCATION> Polish </LOCATION> authorities have let him take since 1981. An impromptu reception committee made up of prominent Solidarity activists, fellow passengers and Solidarity members sang `` Sto Lat'' for <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> as he emerged from customs. The song is <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s equivalent of `` For He's a Jolly Good Fellow,'' and says, `` May he live one hundred years. Supporters thrust flowers into <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s hands and police cleared a path through the crowd of photographers. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that permission to make the trip indicated a changing government attitude toward reform. `` There is a process that we want to speed up and the fact that we are here is evidence of a quickening,'' he said. After two waves of strikes earlier this year, the Polish government offered negotiations to include the government, church and opposition. The talks reached an impasse after the government refused to legalize Solidarity, which was founded in 1980, crushed during martial law in 1981 and outlawed in 1982. Solidarity is demanding the government at least signal it will consider legalization before the union will join talks. The talks were necessary, `` but on the condition we are considered free and independent,'' said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize for creating the first independent trade federation in a communist state. He said the union should continue struggling to improve the lives of its members, but must do so without destroying the country. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> does n't need any more strikes right now. Strikes are a last resort, an ultimate weapon which can ricochet and hurt society,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. He said he had high hopes for Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s attempts to reform the Soviet system. The change in Soviet society `` is a process that does not bring immediate results. It takes time to change the way people think,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said, adding he did not wish to jeopardize <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms Surrounded by representatives from most of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s trade unions and Polish emigres sporting Solidarity pins, the Polish trade unionist was ebullient, thanking President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> for inviting him to attend ceremonies Saturday marking the 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. On Nov. 30, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> debated the chief of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s communist-backed official union in a live TV broadcast that was the first time since 1983 that he has appeared on Polish television. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> needs peace and pluralism. There is a place for both -LRB- Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and Solidarity,'' he said Monday.
