<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Monday refused to stop random drug testing of uniformed <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents but did not rule on the constitutionality of the program. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> denied a motion by a public employees' union for a preliminary injunction, noting that other courts have refused to halt ongoing drug-testing programs while the question of their legality is still pending. <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> did not rule on the merits of the challenge, saying he would issue an opinion within a week. But the judge indicated during a hearing that he might treat testing of police officers differently than regular civilian federal employees. The random drug testing was challenged by 1,013 uniformed <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officers who guard the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and foreign embassies in the nation's capital. The Uniformed Division Officers Association contends that the urine testing is an unconstitutional invasion of privacy. Just last week, <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> barred the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> from randomly testing 750 plant pest and animal disease inspectors, saying there was no justification for invading their privacy. <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> noted the inspectors did not carry weapons and were not considered law enforcement officials. In that decision, however, <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> upheld testing of individual employees suspected of being impaired by drug use while on the job. At Monday's hearing, <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON> said the officers were part of a paramilitary force and had a reduced expectation of privacy stemming from their enlistment in the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` They know what k