<HEAD>Governor OKs Plan for Overhaul of Chicago Public Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> signed into law Monday a bill calling for a sweeping overhaul of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s school system, which former federal Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> once labeled the `` worst in the nation.'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> signed the bill after a symbolic walk from a 105-year-old school that is closing to the gymnasium of a new $ 4.6 million school on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>. The legislation, he said, was `` an important first step.'' `` Parents and other community members have been given unprecedented opportunities with this bill to control their local school systems,'' the governor said in a statement. The much-debated measure, which takes effect in July, calls for a shift of authority from the school system's central bureaucracy to parents and principals in each of its 592 schools. It removes incumbent members of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and calls for the mayor to appoint a new board whose nominees are suggested by a grass-roots screening committee. The legislation also establishes local councils made up of parents, teachers and community residents. The councils _ one for each school _ will have power to hire and fire principals, draft plans for improvements and exercise some control over spending. School principals will lose tenure and work under four-year contracts to be renewed on the basis of performance. They also will have increased authority to fill teaching vacancies. `` While no law can ensure that our students will do better in the classroom, this legislation will provide a more direct and meaningful system that will be accountable for the education of our children,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said. The old school where the march to the signing ceremoney began Monday was built in 1883. It is to be razed to make more room for a high-tech research development. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> led a procession of students carrying blue and gold balloons from the old school to the new. They joined school board officials in cutting a ribbon at the new school. Before the students entered the building, they let their balloons float skyward. The reform movement that provided impetus to pass the bill grew in part out of a bitter teacher strike in the fall of 1987 _ the year then-Secretary <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> called <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> schools `` the worst in the nation.'' His comments helped fan a heated citywide discussion of schools and spur legislators to action. A bill similar to the one signed into law Monday was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> last summer, but that measure was caught in political bickering between <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> over control of an oversight board. The dispute was settled with passage of a new bill that gives oversight powers to the existing <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, created nearly a decade ago after an earlier financial crisis.
