<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three trains crashed into each other near a busy south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> junction during rush hour Monday morning, hurling bodies onto the tracks as the cars `` split open like a ripe tomato.'' Officials said they counted 36 dead. More than 110 of the estimated 1,500 passengers on the trains were hospitalized, 32 with serious injuries such as multiple fractures, crushed abdomens and amputations, hospital and ambulance officials said. The British <ORGANIZATION> Railways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said a preliminary investigation cast blame on a `` technical fault'' that arose after work on signaling equipment. `` It is sheer bloody hell, that's what it is,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant chief officer, surveying the scene at the <ORGANIZATION> Clapham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junction </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s busiest train crossways. Police and Fire Brigade officials said 34 people died in the crash and two died later at a hospital, bringing the death toll to 36. Some bodies were so badly dismembered that limbs were placed in separate body bags, adding to confusion about the toll, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>, a Fire Brigade divisional officer. Police inspector <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said some limbs were unaccounted for and therefore the toll could rise. The accident occurred just before 8 a.m. when a London-bound commuter train slammed into the rear of another passenger train that was stopped about 400 yards south of <LOCATION> Clapham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION>. The two trains were packed with 1,500 people, many of whom were standing. Rescue efforts began, but an empty freight train on an adjacent line then plowed into spillover wreckage and apparently hit some passengers who had scrambled onto the tracks. `` Bodies were cut in half, limbs were thrown around by the impact,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Winch </PERSON>, a doctor. Three cars hurtled into the air and onto an embankment and eight overturned. A fourth train, crowded with commuters, stopped a few feet short of the wreck, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> said. Rescue teams working under arc lights used heavy lifting equipment and hydraulic jacks through the early morning hours Tuesday searching the mangled debris for more trapped victims. Many passengers, dazed or slightly injured, were able to walk away, but <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambulance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said 114 passengers were taken to five local hospitals, 30 with serious injuries, and others were treated on the scene. Dozens of passengers were trapped, some for up to five hours, waiting for rescue workers to hack through dense underbrush alongside the tracks and to pry open roofs of overturned carriages. Others walked away in search of other transport to their jobs in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. A man clutched a crushed briefcase to his chest. Another, in a smart business suit, carried a blood-spattered raincoat. Seats were snapped from their mountings and strewn alongside the wreckage. Briefcases, newspapers and business documents littered the track and the embankment. A child's stroller lay atop one carriage. <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON>, the fire brigade's chief divisional officer, said all survivors were rescued by 1 p.m. but he feared `` there may be further bodies underneath'' the wreckage. It was the worst train wreck in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since 1975, when 43 died in a subway that crashed in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> tunnel. Forty-nine people were killed in a 1967 when a train derailed in south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Transport Minister <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> promised a full inquiry. <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers and railroad union leaders demanded that the inquiry examine allegations of overcrowding and cuts in safety spending on state-owned British Rail. The trains are not part of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s subway system. Rescue workers, many visibly distraught, used infrared cameras, metal cutters and cranes to free passengers. Emergency surgery, including amputations, were performed on the scene. Operations continued after nightfall, bathed in floodlights. `` Bodies were ripped apart and the trains were tangled together,'' said firefighter <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>. `` We had to use our heaviest cutting gear and it was like nibbling away at the wreckage just a little at a time.'' `` There were pieces of bodies lying all over the place. You could hear people moaning,'' said <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> of the ambulance service. Passenger <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> was in the buffet car of the moving train when the crash occurred and `` the roof split open like a ripe tomato.'' `` There was furniture and enormous lumps of metal flying everywhere,'' he said. `` We tried to find people underneath the rubble but there was so much debris, there was nothing we could do.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Emmanuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> near the scene of the crash was transformed into a makeshift clinic for scores of walking injured. Schoolboys scrambled down the banks to help rescue survivors. Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> and archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> expressed grief and condolences. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PER