<HEAD>Onset Of Winter Highlights Plight Of The Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4-5th grafs, bgng `Throughout the...', with 4 grafs to
add detail on how many people seek beds in lottery, UPDATE with
electricity use setting record. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Elsewhere,
life...'. SUBS last graf to CORRECT spelling of Ullmann sted Ullman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Kingston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is holding lotteries these days for beds, trying to be fair as it goes about meeting long lines at the shelter each day. Even in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, there's just no getting used to the kinds of demands that record cold can put on people. The first blast of the 1988-89 winter season Monday brought a record low for the date of 2 degrees, with most of the impact seen at shelters. At the <ORGANIZATION> Kingston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, seven homeless people were in line as the doors to the shelter opened at 6:30 a.m. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, in charge of admitting people to the shelter, said a lottery has been held before noon in recent days for the beds. Those who lose out are referred to other shelters or offered a blanket and the floor. He said that typically, about 60 people take part in the lottery seeking one of the 40 beds at the shelter available for transients. The other 20 beds at the shelter are used by residents who stay for months while they take part in a rehabilitation program. Throughout the city Sunday night, about 75 people were transported to shelters, and more were expected as the cold weather continues, Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. Electricity demand set a wintertime record in the region Monday and came close to surpassing the all-time record, a spokesman said. `` I do n't have a final number set for today yet, but we can definitely say we surpassed the previous winter record of 19,277 megawatts,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheperdson </PERSON> of the New England Power Pool. Monday's average peak load was between 19,400 and 19,500 megawatts, he said. The system record of 19,500 megawatts was set during a heat wave in August. Elsewhere, life went on, albeit at a slower pace. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> fishermen at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pier </ORGANIZATION> told of chipping ice off the bows with wooden mallets to keep trawlers from getting nose heavy. `` No grog. A lot of coffee,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, 38, a mate aboard the Olympia, an 86-foot fishing trawler that had just returned from a week at sea. `` As long as you're moving, it is n't bad,'' said <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, wearing four layers of long-sleeved shirts and a cap with ear flaps. `` The bad part is if we do damage. Then you've got to stop and mend it up. That's bare-handed. That's nasty.'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Southmayd </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> window washing service, said workers use a special non-freeze solution in bitter weather. `` I'm sure -LRB- any window washer -RRB- is miserable, but it's all in the line of work,'' Southmayd said. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cudyer </PERSON>, who runs the city's 24-hour hotline for citizen complaints, said her office received about 100 calls since the temperature took a dive Sunday. Most were about a lack of heat from tenants whose landlords seemed unprepared for the cold, she said. `` In winter it's inevitable. But when it was 50 degrees last week, they let the oil run out,'' she said. `` They were caught by the dramatic swing in temperature from 50 to 0 in a matter of days.'' The homeless problem in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> gets special attention from a city commission and a mayor who heads a national conference on the issue. At a city-sponsored summit Monday on the homeless, which was designed to begin building a groundswell of support for more federal participation in providing affordable housing, speakers said efforts must focus on moving beyond temporary shelter to permanent housing. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said the federal commitment to providing housing dropped off sharply during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The mayor also touted <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s pledge to provide a warm bed and hot meal for anyone on the streets. Results of a street-by-street count of the homeless have not been tallied yet, but <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said preliminary figures indicate it will top the 3,300 recorded in February. The number of city shelter beds has increased from 972 in 1983 to 2,754 this year. Shelter officials say they see more children than before. At the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, a special party was planned Tuesday for 350 children with actress <PERSON> Liv </PERSON> <PERSON> Ullmann </PERSON> and a live performance of the `` Nutcracker'' ballet.
