<HEAD>Three Van Gogh Works, Including `Potato Eaters,' Stolen From Museum</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with search, official saying stolen
Potato Eaters is most important version; CORRECTS style on van Gogh.
No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTERLO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three paintings by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, including his early masterpiece `` The Potato Eaters,'' were stolen from a national museum on Monday night, police said. The art theft appeared to be the biggest in Dutch history. The van <PERSON> Goghs </PERSON> were taken from the Kroeller-Mueller National Museum near the West German border by thieves who apparently gained entry through a broken window after closing hours, said police spokeswoman <PERSON> Bep </PERSON> <PERSON> Lijftogt </PERSON>. The two other paintings by the 19th-century Dutch impressionist were `` Dried Sunflowers'' and `` <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>'s Interior,'' she reported. Two guards were in the sprawling, single-story museum at the time, but they noticed nothing amiss, said police spokesman <PERSON> Dirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Talsma </PERSON>. Police immediately sealed off the 25-acre park in which the museum sits. A helicopter equipped with floodlights and police with dogs hunted for suspects on the heavily forested grounds. They suspended the search at 1 a.m. Tuesday and planned to resume at daybreak. No official valuation of the paintings was available from the museum, but the director of <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction gallery in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> said that if sold on the open market _ not possible for a stolen work _ `` The Potato Eaters'' could bring as much as <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Sunflowers. That painting brought $ 39.9 million when auctioned off in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in March 1987. `` The sky's the limit,'' <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s director <PERSON> Harts </PERSON> <PERSON> Nijstad </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. `` ` The Potato Eaters' is an enormously important painting. `` The Potato Eaters'' in the Kroeller-Mueller museum was the most complete of several versions of the same subject, according to <PERSON> Nijstad </PERSON>, who said a less important version sits in the van <ORGANIZATION> Gogh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. No estimate on the value of the other two paintings was immediately available, but <PERSON> Nijstad </PERSON> said all three were `` frightfully important.'' He speculated that the paintings were stolen for ransom, adding, `` Whether the ransom will be money-wise or political is something the future will tell us.'' The museum's silent alarm triggered a warning in the local police station at about 8:45 p.m. -LRB- 2:45 p.m. EST -RRB-, and police rushed to the museum. Completed in 1885, `` The Potato Eaters'' is one of van <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s most poignant depictions of poverty and hunger in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> It shows a farm family seated around a table eating potatoes by lamplight, the hunger evident on their angular faces. Five van <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> works were included in a list published two weeks ago of the top 10 prices paid for paintings at the world's two major auction houses, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s and <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' was sold last month for $ 53.9 million, the highest price paid for any painting in the world. The Kroeller-Mueller has dozens of <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Goghs </PERSON> exhibited in a special wing. The museum and surrounding estate were bequeathed to the nation in 1938 by art collector Mrs. H.E.L.G. Kroeller-Mueller. The theft was the latest in a series of recent burglaries at Dutch museums. In May, thieves broke a window and stole impressionist paintings by <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, French painter <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON> and Dutch painter <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>'s Municipal Museum. Those paintings were initially valued at up to $ 50 million, but art authorities later scaled down the estimated value. The paintings were later recovered in a raid on an <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> hotel spearheaded by an undercover policeman posing as a buyer of stolen art. That theft, mounted through a broken ground-floor window at a time when no guards were in the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> museum, prompted calls for stronger security in the nation's museums. The Kroeller-Mueller museum never before had a major theft, police spokesman <PERSON> Talsma </PERSON> said. `` The Potato Eaters'' was painted when <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> was living in a village in southern <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>. It is considered his most ambitious work from his Dutch period, before he moved to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1886 and came under the influence of Impressionism. The painting is done in dark colors in a rough style, which van <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> said in a letter to his brother was meant to illustrate the rough life that the peasants lived. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s artistic career lasted only 10 years, but during that time he produced about 850 paintings. About 50 of the paintings are still in private hands, according to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Roundell </PERSON>, who supervised the `` Sunflowers'' sale. A highly placed source at the <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gogh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> said on condition of anonymity last month that one great fear his museum had was that the record prices being paid for works by <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> would bring ideas of theft into people's heads. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> sold only one painting during his lifetime.
