<HEAD>Parliament Returns for Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s government announced its intention Monday to make sure <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> can start the free trade agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as scheduled Jan. 1. But his opponents said too many issues remain to be discussed for the legislation to be rushed through <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, called back into session for work on the trade bill. The prime minister's <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won 169 of the 295 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> in the hotly contested Nov. 21 elections, so it could force quick passage of the legislation. The measure will phase out all remaining tariffs between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> over a 10-year period. `` The people have spoken in a general election three weeks ago,'' Gov. Gen. <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sauve </PERSON> said in the formal `` throne speech'' traditionally opening a new parliamentary session in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. `` In the election, my government sought and received a mandate for its policies, including the free trade agreement between <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that is to take effect on Jan. 1, 1989.'' The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which won 82 seats in Commons, and the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 43 seats have said they will not stand in the way of ultimate passage but want extensive debate on the problems they believe the trade agreement will bring. The bitter debate over free trade that marked the fall election campaign would be renewed in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. One seat, won by a Conservative who died after the election, is vacant. Liberal leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, who led a self-proclaimed `` crusade'' against the trade agreement, said in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that he was not stalling the legislation. `` To insist on a thorough debate - that's not stalling,'' he said, noting that the popular vote showed more Canadians in favor of the two parties opposing the agreement than for the Conservatives. New Democratic leader <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> said he wanted amendments to be introduced to protect workers whose jobs are lost in company restructurings tied to the trade agreement. He told the <ORGANIZATION> CBC </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> won a mandate for the trade agreement, but `` he received no mandate to ramrod it right through Parliament.'' A delay of days, weeks or probably even months in completing the enabling legislation needed would not hinder the agreement. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has completed all its legislation for the agreement, signed by <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last Jan. 2. In <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, it passed the elected House of Commons last August but then was bottled up in the Liberal-controlled, appointed <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to force the election. The legislation approved last August has expired and the process now must be repeated in Commons.
