<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Assailants early Tuesday shot and killed a police major and his policeman son, who was organizing an anti-communist group in a rebel-infested neighborhood in <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, police reported. Capt. <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said that Maj. <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Negapatan </PERSON>, 59, and his son, <PERSON> Patrolman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Negapatan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, about 30, were standing on a street corner in <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> when three men and a woman emerged from a taxi. At least three of the four opened fire, <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said father and son were killed instantly and the assailants escaped. He said the elder <PERSON> Negapatan </PERSON> was administrative officer of the <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police force and the son, a traffic policeman, was organizing the anti-communist group in their neighborhood. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said it was not clear if the killers were <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas or ordinary criminals <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is a major metropolitan area, about 350 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Faced with an upsurge in urban violence, the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> military has begun organizing a new civilian anti-communist force, the <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Units </ORGANIZATION>, to assist in guarding villages and urban neighborhoods against the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Volunteers for the Units are to phase out vigilante groups and the <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, both of which have been accused of widespread human rights abuses in the fight against the rebels. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said on Monday at a meeting in <LOCATION> Cagayan </LOCATION> de Oro that members of the new militia will be rigidly screened, especially those who previously served in the <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has waged a 19-year insurgency to establish a Marxist state in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.
