<HEAD>Peruvian Miners Agree to Halt Crippling Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government and a communist-led mine workers' federation signed an accord late Monday to end an 8-week-old strike that has cost <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> nearly $ 300 million, Prime Minister <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON> said. Strike leader <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantoral </PERSON> said miners will resume work nationwide in three days, bringing an end to a paralysis in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s most important industry <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON> told reporters the strike cost the nation nearly $ 300 million, one-fourth of last year's mineral export income of $ 1.2 billion last year. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is a leading world producer of silver and copper and a major source of gold, lead and zinc. It traditionally received more than half of its hard currency earnings from mineral exports. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s 60,000 miners struck on Oct. 17 to force mine companies to honor a government-union pact permitting labor contracts in the mining industry to be negotiated jointly with all mining enterprises rather than on a company-by-company basis. The strike came as <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> entered a severe recession, marked by inflation expected to surpass 1,500 percent this year and a shortage of dollar reserves to purchase vital imports. Industry officials said strikers were being manipulated by communist guerrillas seeking to undermine the nation. The miners' federation denied it Terms of the new accord signed by <PERSON> Cantoral </PERSON> and other leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> and Metalworkers and by <PERSON> Villanueva </PERSON> were not immediately announced. Federation director <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said earlier Monday that the federation was demanding that the government promise to enact a law to force public and private mining firms to abide by the government-union pact. Such an agreement will greatly strengthen the miners' bargaining position during contracts, industry analysts said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s most important association of private mine owners, has strongly opposed joint contract negotiations. It says the federation will use its bargaining power to cripple the industry at will. Government and industry officials said more than half the strikers began returning to work last week. The federation, which represents dozens of mine unions, denied the report. Thousands of highland miners, many with families, marched on <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> after the strike began and set up camps around the city to publicize their plight. Miners engaged in street protests which at times ended in violence and arrests.
</TEXT>
