<HEAD>Soviet Premier Complains of Poor Relief Organization</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs with premier acknowledging bad
organization, complaining of building violations. Pick up 13th pvs
`Associated Press...' Edits to trim thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB4,MOS5-6,YER59</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Earthquake relief efforts in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> are hampered by bad organization, Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said Monday. Hope dwindled for people trapped in the rubble, and the smell of decaying corpses filled the air. Other officials said rescuers working around the clock with everything from their bare hands to fiber optic cameras have pulled more than 18,000 people from earthquake wreckage. `` The work is not going badly, but we would wish it to be more organized,'' <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> told foreign journalists at a news conference in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. He also said many people died unnecessarily in Wednesday's earthquake because poorly built houses collapsed into ruins `` We believe gross violations were permitted'' in designing and building the apartment houses that collapsed. `` If the homes had been of good-quality construction, something like this would not have happened,'' <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said. He said this view was shared by a government investigative commission and by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who visited the disaster area over the weekend. Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, published a scathing article Monday about `` scrap-builders'' who constructed shoddy apartment buildings that crumbled into `` concrete and metal graves over victims who were buried alive.'' Health Minister <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> estimated the temblor killed up to 60,000 people. <PERSON> Ryzkhov </PERSON> said it was certain that 15,000 had died, but the figure would problably rise to 45,000. Five days after the tragedy struck, shelter and salvage equipment remained in short supply. Reporting Monday from <LOCATION> Leninaken </LOCATION>, near the quake's epicenter, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, `` People wander among the debris of what used to be their homes, straining their ears in the hope of hearing the voice of a missing sister, father, brother or simply any human voice.'' Soviet television showed a worker in <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION>, where 60 percent of the houses were destroyed, bending a metal reinforcing rod in a collapsed concrete wall by hand, his face strained with the effort. Another man moved mounds of broken concrete with a shovel. A man and boy huddled over a fire in a small bucket, their only source of warmth during what the television announcer described as five nights on a pile of rubble because there were not enough tents. Snow and temperatures of 14-23 degrees Fahrenheit were forecast. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Shcherbina </PERSON>, a deputy prime minister who directed the cleanup after the April 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear plant accident, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>: `` We shall work without letup to save everyone still alive under the debris, even on the 10th and the 12th day after the disaster. We shall work for as long as there is a chance to save the life of at least one unhappy victim.'' He said more than 5,000 people had been rescued in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said 18,500 had been saved in the entire disaster area, which had a population of 700,000. But <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said at the new conference that only 5,398 had been saved throughout the region. He said 10 people were pulled alive from the rubble on Monday. Associated Press correspondent <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, a city of more than 25,000 before the quake, and said the smells of burning and decomposing bodies were everywhere. A British charity called <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> said its 14-member team in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> was using ultrasonic listening equipment and fiber optic cameras to locate survivors trapped under collapsed buildings. More than 200 search dogs were helping, and infrared devices that can detect the warmth of bodies trapped under rubble. Many of the nearly 1,000 foreign helpers have said local officials are not organizing the rescue well and interpreters to help translate the many languages are scarce. The second crash of a relief plane in two days was reported. All seven crewmembers died when a Soviet-built Yugoslav military transport loaded with medical equipment and other supplies went down 10 miles from the airport in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, capital of the Armenian republic. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Panyukov </PERSON>, first deputy aviation minister, made the announcement in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Local reporters said the An-12 cargo plane crashed before dawn because the pilot mistook a well-lighted highway for a runway. On Sunday, a Soviet military plane bringing soldiers to help the rescue effort crashed as it approached <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>'s airport, killing 78 people. Aid continued pouring in from abroad. Council of Ministers spokesman <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Voznesensky </PERSON> told the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference 38 foreign relief planes had arrived and the most, six, were from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> of the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> there was little hope of finding more survivors. He said the only people still alive would be those who found water and air where they were trapped. <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> quoted reports that only 150 people survived in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>; other reports say 10 percent lived. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Armenian </LOCATION> activists said demonstrators fought with soldiers because several nationalist leaders were arrested. One activist who avoided arrest, <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>, said by telephone three protests took place Sunday in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> because leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Karabakh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> were arrested. The committee has led a campaign for Armenian control of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a predominantly Armenian region of neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. He said soldiers and demonstrators fought during a protest near the railway station and several people were wounded. An editor at Armenpress confirmed the violence but said it did not appear to have been serious.
