<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescuers and officials trying to save survivors of the earthquake in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> said Monday they desperately need a better command system, more coordination, and better equipment. In addition, no Soviet troops were visible among the rescue workers in <LOCATION> Leninaken </LOCATION>, one of the hardest-hit cities in Wednesday's earthquake Instead, the rescue operations were being carried out mostly by friends and relatives of those still trapped. They used small tools like hammers and torches. Soviet Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said enthusiam was plentiful, but `` today the question is organization.'' He spoke at a news conference late Monday in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital. <PERSON> Sverre </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilde </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> disaster relief officer, said the rescue effort appeared well organized on the national and regional level, but locally in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> it was suffering from a lack of control. `` Here there are 50-60 people shouting in all directions,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> diaster relief officer <PERSON> Sverre </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilde </PERSON>, speaking of a rescue site he visited in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> on Sunday. `` It would have been much more reasonable to have an army captain or colonel in charge of it.'' Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> told reporters that more than 18,000 soldiers were in the earthquake area, but in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> none was seen helping with rescue operations. Asked about the situation, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said the soldiers were ensuring order in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> and helping unload relief supplies from cargo planes. They also said troops were involved in rescue operations in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, a city of more than 25,000 people that was almost totally destroyed by the earthquake. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said soldiers had cut off both cities to all but relief traffic. Two relief planes have crashed in heavy air traffic in the region. A crash of a Soviet military plane on Sunday killed 78 people, and one of a <LOCATION> Yugoslavian </LOCATION> military aircraft left seven dead early Monday. The Soviet premier gave high marks to the medical effort, saying doctors had performed 2,500 complicated operations in the field during the first 24 hours after the quake. However, area doctors said they badly need artificial kidney machines and blood-filtering devices. They hope to receive more of both from abroad. Veterans of rescue efforts for past earthquakes in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> say it is difficult to supply the remote Soviet area near the Turkish border. Rescuers, meanwhile, pleaded for more cranes and bulldozers to pull away slabs of concrete and other debris in an effort to free those still trapped in the rubble.
