<HEAD>Panamanian on the Slide but Noriega Strong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Panamanians are fleeing, unemployment is rising, the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> is suffering, the American military is steaming and bank profits are falling. About the only firm thing in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s grip on it. `` The country is going down the drain fast,'' said <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON>, leader of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He and <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Carles </PERSON> of the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> said up to 40,000 Panamanians have left in 18 months. Unemployment is up from 11 percent in 1987 to 23 percent. The treasury is in a bind and public employees went on strike, demanding to be paid on time. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administrator for the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> says his job may not be turned over to a Panamanian next year as required by the canal treaty and that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s anti-Noriega sanctions indirectly hinder operations at the canal, which is to be turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> at midnight Dec. 31, 1999. In recent months, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has imprisoned critics, changed election laws to make it easier for himself to run for president in May 1989 and closed four opposition newspapers, including <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>. The opposition is reduced to receiving news by facsimile machines from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Fax and photocopies, the No. 1 means of communication,'' <PERSON> Carles </PERSON> said in an interview. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s trip down the chute began in June 1987 with allegations that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> rigged the 1984 elections, laundered money and trafficked in drugs and arms. Relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, traditionally close because of the canal. took a nosedive last February when President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as head of the 15,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had the legislature dismiss <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> instead. <LOCATION> Washingto </LOCATION> refused to recognize the new president, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, and imposed economic sanctions in an effort to force <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out. Six opposition parties recently signed a petition calling for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s ouster and formation of a transition government for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s 2.2 million people. They have not yet decided whether to enter candidates in next year's presidential election, nor has the general said whether he will run. `` The people are scared to death,'' <PERSON> Carles </PERSON> said. `` How can we have elections if everything is under <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s control?'' Repeated calls were made to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s spokesman, Maj. <PERSON> Edgardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, and to leading members of the military-backed <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> but were not returned. Banks closed for nine weeks last March and figures issued by the government indicated deposits at the more than 100 institutions operating in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> dropped from nearly $ 30 billion to just under $ 8 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions put <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the same economic boat with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the other Latin American countries on which <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> imposed boycotts, and compounded problems that began with the political strife. `` This is one of the things that has really hurt the external image,'' said <PERSON> Edgardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasso </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, because `` the others are communist countries.'' The government limited bank withdrawals, putting a $ 100 ceiling on what could be withdrawn from savings accounts. Many Panamanians stopped banking and sold certificates of deposit for less than market value. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has taken up the time-tested cry of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> about a threat of imminent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion, except that in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s case about 10,000 American soldiers already are in the country <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is headquarters for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and the soldiers, nominally stationed here for the purpose of defending the canal, use the strategic location for intelligence gathering and spy flights over <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Officers of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> claim Panamanian troops trespass nightly on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military facilities, and have reported exchanges of fire in two dozen cases. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> was shot to death by a comrade in April. `` The goal is to embarrass the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and raise the level of a sense of vulnerability,'' a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said. The 1977 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties specify that the troops must leave when the 50-mile-long waterway is turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> but an accompanying pact requires the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to assure `` indefinitely a regime providing for the permanent neutrality of the canal.'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said the provision calling for a Panamanian to take over his job at the end of 1989 is up in the air because the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president must approve the choice and anyone `` who bears the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> imprint will never be acceptable.'' <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON> said canal operations suffer somewhat because, under the economic embargo, the canal commission can not pay its Panamanian employees' withholding taxes and the government has begun harassing workers for the money. `` The fact is they are so nervous right now it's affecting morale and that affects the efficiency of our operation,'' said <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>, a retired Army general. End Adv Tue Dec. 13
