<HEAD>Trouble at the Top of the Underworld in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOBE, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Each day children on their way home from school calmly walk past the headquarters of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest underworld syndicate, behind plastered beige walls in a classy residential district overlooking the sea. Across town, a red-tiled building controlled by the gang is within 100 yards of the <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courthouse </ORGANIZATION>. It bears the golden, diamond-shaped logo of the gang, which leaders wear on their lapels and which is printed on members' business cards. Over the past few years the Yamaguchi-gumi syndicate has waged a successful war of revenge against a major rival, doubled its membership and raked in millions of dollars annually, said <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s Organized Crime Control Office But all is not well within the criminal empire. The year's business for the 20,000-member syndicate traditionally starts Dec. 13, when ranking bosses gather at headquarters in this western port city for a formal celebration called `` koto hajime'' _ the beginning of things. But since gang leader <PERSON> Masahisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON> was killed by a splinter group's gunman in 1985, custom has forced the Yamaguchi-gumi to cancel the annual ceremony because it has no top don. <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON> was replaced by two men, acting gang leader <PERSON> Kazuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakanishi </PERSON> and `` young leader'' <PERSON> Yoshinori </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON>, who led the gang into a war to avenge <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON>'s killing, police say. Though that vendetta, which has left 25 dead and 70 injured by police count, now seems to be nearing an end, police say the long time without a leader has led to factionalism in the gang, weakening its pyramid-style command structure. Public reaction to the high-profile violence has also plagued the gang. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has low rates of violent crime and very strict gun-control laws. But gunfights have brought attention to the gangs, spawning grass-roots movements to rid residential areas of gang headquarters and offices. A Yamaguchi-gumi subgang in the central Japanese city of <LOCATION> Hamamatsu </LOCATION> was in the media spotlight until public opposition forced it to relocate last year. The gang is now on the verge of collapse, according to <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON> of the crime control office. But <PERSON> Masafumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON>, director of the office, said in an interview that the public outcry and tough police crackdowns also may have worked to the syndicate's benefit, putting many smaller gangs out of business or forcing them to seek Yamaguchi-gumi protection. A recent issue of `` Endless Advance,'' an in-house journal published by the <ORGANIZATION> Kyokuto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shinsei-kai </ORGANIZATION>, a large <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> syndicate, attested to the trend toward consolidation. In the 120-page edition obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> were photos of top underworld figures gathered for dinner at a posh <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> hotel to `` pursue friendly relations and cooperation'' and avoid intergang trouble. Technically, the Yamaguchi-gumi has only 86 members, but each of the top 86 controls a network of subordinate gangs, which, in turn, have their own `` kasa'' _ Japanese for umbrella. Top bosses rarely face prosecution for serious crimes as underlings take responsibility, sometimes even turning themselves in, since doing prison time can bring a promotion. According to an annual report by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, more than 86,000 gangsters in 3,201 gangs are spread across the country. Roughly 40 percent belong to the big three nationwide syndicates _ the Yamaguchi-gumi, the Tokyo-based Sumiyoshi Rengo-kai and the <LOCATION> Inagawa-kai </LOCATION>, also based in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> estimated total underworld income at the yen equivalent of $ 15 billion annually, but he added that `` is only a rough guess.'' Yamaguchi-gumi income sources include gambling, the protection racket, fraud, prostitution, money laundering and narcotics. These and countless other scams are backed up by front operations in construction, the stock market and real estate. Police believe the deaths of <PERSON> Hiroyuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> and his boss, <PERSON> Kazuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kengaku </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> stock market speculator, are shadier examples of what the Yamaguchi-gumi has done. The bodies of the men, who police allege had been kidnapped and held for ransom, were dug up Oct. 18 _ entombed in a slab of concrete. Two Yamaguchi-gumi affiliate members later confessed to the crime. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Kobe </PERSON> residents seem to accept the Yamaguchi-gumi's presence with a mixture of helplessness and inevitability `` I've never had any trouble with gangsters, but I suppose I'd prefer it if they'd leave,'' said a taxi driver `` The thing is, you'll never get rid of them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Dec. 15</NOTE>
