 Today is Sunday, Dec. 18, the 353rd day of 1988. There are 13 days left in the year. Today's Highlight in History: On Dec. 18, 1865, the 13th Amendment to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution, abolishing slavery, was declared in effect. On this date: In 1737, the most renowned violin-maker in history, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Stradivari </PERSON>, died in <LOCATION> Cremona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. In 1787, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> became the third state to ratify the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution. In 1813, the British took <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> in the War of 1812. In 1915, President <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, widowed the year before, married <PERSON> Edith </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolling </PERSON> <PERSON> Galt </PERSON> at her home in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In 1956, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was admitted to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. In 1957, the <LOCATION> Shippingport </LOCATION> Atomic Power Station in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, the first nuclear facility to generate electricity in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, went on line. -LRB- It was taken out of service in 1982. -RRB- In 1969, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> abolished its death penalty. In 1972, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> began its heaviest bombing of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to date during the Vietnam War. -LRB- The bombardment ended 12 days later. -RRB- In 1980, former Soviet Premier <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosygin </PERSON> suffered a fatal heart attack at age 76. -LRB- His death was not officially announced for two days. -RRB- In 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> unanimously approved a resolution condemning `` all acts of hostage-taking and abduction.'' Ten years ago: In the wake of his city's default on $ 14 million dollars in short-term notes, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kucinich </PERSON> announced he was laying off 20 percent of the municipal work force on Jan. 2 to conserve cash. Five years ago: <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spokesmen announced that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships had shelled Syrian-held positions in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s central mountains in immediate retaliation for an attack on two American reconnaisance flights. One year ago: <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, leader of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s political opposition, was married in a traditional Islamic ceremony to businessman <PERSON> Asif </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Zardari </PERSON> _ the man selected for her by her mother Today's Birthdays: Actor <PERSON> Ossie </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is 71. Former Attorney General <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> is 61. Rock star <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> is 45. Movie producer-director <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> is 41. Movie reviewer <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Maltin </PERSON> is 38. Thought for today: `` Parents spend the first part of a child's life getting him to walk and talk, and the rest of his childhood getting him to sit down and shut up. _ Anonymous.
