<SECOND>BC-APN--Retired Munchkin, Adv25,1102</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 drawing.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ He worked his way through college as a midget in sideshows at fairs and expositions. He became a living trademark for a national brand of wieners. But the highpoint of <PERSON> Meinhardt </PERSON> <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>'s career came when he landed the role of a Munchkin in `` The Wizard of Oz.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENNEY FARMS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are no yellow brick roads or wicked witches in this <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> retirement community, but there is a fugitive from the land of Oz. He's a Munchkin, name of <PERSON> Meinhardt </PERSON> <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>. Although it's been half a century, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> can still repeat the lines he sang as the Munchkin coroner in `` The Wizard of Oz,'' the 1939 movie classic starring <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. When the tornado dropped the house on the wicked witch, it was <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>, carrying a large death certificate, who sang, `` She's not only merely dead, she's most sincerely dead.'' The coroner had one of the nine speaking roles for the 116 little people who played Munchkins in the movie based on <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>'s books At the time the movie was filmed, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> was promoting <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> wieners as `` Little Oscar _ The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s Smallest Chef.'' He took a two-month leave of absence and headed for <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, where he was given the role in `` The Wizard Of Oz.'' <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> was 22 years old and only 46 inches tall. He had worked his way through college in midget shows at fairs. He's since grown to 4-foot-7. When the film was made, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says he had no idea it would become a classic. He was only familiar with the scenes in which he played. `` We did n't know what came before or what came after,'' he says. `` We had no idea what the picture was all about until we saw it released. `` At the time of its release, it was overshadowed by ` Gone With The Wind.''' `` Gone With The Wind'' won four Academy Awards, including best picture that year. `` It was only after CBS got the film in 1956 and used it for their promotions that it became as well known,'' he says. Now retired and living in this community established by <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Penney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>, 73, believes the movie has become an enduring classic because people saw it as children and still remember it. `` That's one factor, but the second basic factor is there is nothing in the picture that dates it,'' he says. `` There are no old vintage cars or old vintage streetcars and it's a fantasy picture that will be fantasy for generations to come. `` I have so many middle-aged people come up to me and say, ` I just bought the video of `` The Wizard of Oz'' for my grandchildren.' But after talking to them, you realize that it was they themselves who were most interested because it was nostalgia for them.'' Although <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> leads an active life as the horticulturist at <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION>, he and his wife, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, often travel to Oz reunions, including a recent one in <LOCATION> Chesterton </LOCATION>, Ind. `` One of the reasons why the Munchkins are getting attention is that all the major stars of the picture are gone, so there are just a few of us Munchkins left,'' <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says. There are fewer than 30 former Munchkins still living. `` It was 50 years ago and I was one of the younger ones,'' he says. `` Many of them were 30 and 40 years older than I was at time.'' <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says being involved in the movie was the experience of a lifetime. `` For a young man of 22 from a farm in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> to be in that atmosphere was naturally a big thrill,'' <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> said. He got to meet <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> and many of the other top stars at <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION>. When the little people chosen to play Munchkins were hired, each was measured for a costume. While the costumes were made, the Munchkins rehearsed their parts. `` As we marched, we had to be on a certain yellow brick on a certain note. We were all well-rehearsed. So when the costumes were finished, we were ready to do the shooting,'' he says. Work began at 6 a.m. each day and continued until 8 p.m. each night. <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says he ca n't remember what he was paid for his role in the movie, but remembers it was very low. `` By today's standards, people would say you were crazy to work for that,'' he says. <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Watertown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION> in 1915, was a member of the <LOCATION> Midget </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> cast at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> World's Fair in 1934. He also performed at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exposition </ORGANIZATION> in 1935 and the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Centennial </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s Fair in 1936. `` By working at these world's fairs as a midget, I was able to work my way through the university,'' <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says. He holds both a bachelor's degree in accounting from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> and a master's degree in business administration from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> says some short people resent the word `` midget,'' but that was the description widely used when he was in show business. `` My wife and I were both in show business, were both midgets. My wife worked from 1929 to 1932 as a member of <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s Royal Midgets, the largest midget troupe in vaudeville,'' he says. They have been married for 43 years. When <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> graduated from college, he was unable to get a job as an accountant because of his size. But his size worked to his advantage when he was hired as `` Little Oscar, the World's Smallest Chef'' _ a job he held for 30 years. <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON>, who wore a chef's uniform, traveled around the country doing cooking shows, school shows, lectures and handing out samples. `` I was on the road all the time, I never had an office job,'' he says. `` We were constantly on the road traveling.'' When `` The Wizard of Oz'' was released in 1939, <PERSON> Raabe </PERSON> performed a double duty. `` I traveled with the picture for six months,'' he says. `` I was being paid by <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>. I was getting the little promotion bit ahead of the picture and we passed out wiener samples in the lobby at the end.''
</TEXT>
