</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has six Emmys for two of the best TV shows ever. She is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fame </ORGANIZATION> and is co-founder of a studio that has made her one of the wealthiest women in television. She has nothing left to prove in her trade. Yet, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> is back in the trenches with a new <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> show called `` <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>.'' The show is near the bottom of the weekly <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> ratings, along with `` The <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> Show,'' a new effort by her former co-star in `` The <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> Show'' in the 1960s. She's struggling to survive in a ratings war that has changed radically since she reigned in the 1970s with `` The <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show.'' Independent stations, syndicated shows, cable, pay channels, video cassettes and the upstart <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> are all relatively new combatants in the ratings war. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, now mired ingloriously in third place, no longer brags that it's the <ORGANIZATION> Tiffany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. `` You ca n't run away from it because it's tough,'' says <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, whose last situation comedy, `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>,'' and two attempts at a variety show failed. `` Acting is what I do for a living. By that, I mean I live to act. As long as I'm healthy enough I want to find a medium to express myself. I hope to be playing old ladies in the near future. `` It has nothing to do with money. It has to do with the joy one has in plying one's trade. This is fun for me. It's rewarding.'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> obviously does not need the money. She's quite wealthy from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, which she co-founded with former husband <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinker </PERSON>, to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s TVS. She retains a 20 percent ownership. Eight years ago she moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for the stage play `` Whose Life Is It, Anyway?,'' then decided to stay. She has been married for the past five years to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> cardiologist, Dr. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>. They also have a home in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Duchess </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> says she has discovered such pastimes as gardening, walking and horseback riding. `` I've become almost bucolic,'' she says. Still, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who professes she gets homesick for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the instant she crosses the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, is back in <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> doing another sitcom. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, wearing a red warm-up suit with her hair cut stylishly short, is sitting on a couch in her trailer parked outside Stage 3 at the <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>. It's the same trailer she used for `` The <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show'' and was also once used by <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. Up close, despite her diabetic condition and too many years spent exposing her skin to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> sun, she looks as good as her bank account. She credits this to a change in lifestyle. She has quit smoking, does light impact aer