 <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> saw and this put us in at 8:30 p.m. after <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>'s new show, which is very broad.'' The writers strike gave them time to think it over. The first show was scrapped and the first show on the air was actually the second show. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> says she wants CBS to move the show because she feels its adult content deserves a later time slot. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> realizes it's impossible to avoid comparisons to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, her character in `` The <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show.'' `` But <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> is radically different from <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>,'' she says. `` Annie's more mature, more creative and not as compulsive. She can have a wrinkle in her skirt or a stain on her blouse. <PERSON> Annie </PERSON>'s a care-giver, she gives of herself to other people. She's not terribly organized She's a little cynical. She's free-spirited.
