</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> can speak with authority about very proper WASP matrons. `` I know a lot of those ladies,'' says the actress who grew up in an upper middle-class family in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` The way they lived is the way I lived.'' Proper is how many audiences view Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON>, too, from her role as the no-nonsense, wealthy, newspaper publisher <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pynchon </PERSON> on television's `` <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'' to the befuddled mayor in this season's surprise movie success `` The Naked Gun'' to her latest stage role, an upper-crust matriarch with a fierce family loyalty in the off-Broadway hit, `` The Cocktail Hour.'' The play, written by A.R. Gurney, gets its title from that particular time of day, usually before dinner, when drinks and good conversation are served. But in this case, the conversation is not so agreeable. A son has returned home to ask his parents' permission to present a play he has written about them. Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> plays the mother, a peacemaker who tries to soften the generational squabbles, and she walked off with glowing notices from the critics. The actress has worked before with <PERSON> Gurney </PERSON>, who also comes from <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> and from the same upper-class WASP society. It's a society <PERSON> Gurney </PERSON> has written about before in such plays as `` The Dining Room,'' `` The Middle Ages'' and `` The Perfect Party.'' `` Often when a playwright is writing a play, there comes a point when he wants to hear it,'' says <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON>, sitting in the living room of her Upper West Side apartment. `` So I've done a lot of readings of his plays. And when I read ` The Cocktail Hour,' I thought, ` It's the best play he's written.''' The actress knew she had to play this woman and drew the character from her memories of other women, her mother and even herself. But do n't ask her to explain how. `` This is very hard for me to talk about because it's all kind of subliminal,'' she says with a laugh. `` What I do is sit down right away and learn the role. That's when I make a lot of discoveries about the character I get so involved that I become that person. I know that sounds silly, but I really do.'' For Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON>, `` The Cocktail Hour'' has turned into particularly gratifying employment. It will keep her in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a while. For much of her career, she needed to travel for work. Still she has managed to maintain what she calls `` a real household'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It includes her husband, actor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sparer </PERSON>, recently seen off-Broadway as the father in the hit play `` A <PERSON> Shayna </PERSON> <PERSON> Maidel </PERSON>.'' The couple raised three children, now grown. Even when she was filming `` <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'' in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> was able to shoot most of her scenes in one day and come back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for the remainder of the week. `` My husband was here and my youngest daughter was just finishing up high school,'' she says. `` This is my home. But the producers were very good to me.'' Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> also had the luck of appearing in what was a quality television show. `` The topics that it dealt with were interesting and thought-provoking,'' she says. `` So it was a challenge for me.'' So was the character. In one episode early in the series' run, Mrs. <PERSON> Pynchon </PERSON> had a stroke, Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> recalls. The illness gave her an opportunity to explore the character further. She began using a cane for the role, something she carried over to later episodes, and then added other stroke-related characteristics to the woman's personality, like her having trouble remembering things. For most of her career, Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> has had to juggle family and career. There were stretches of 12-hour days when husband and wife never stopped running between family and career, particularly when they both were members of the APA-Phoenix repertory company in the 1960s. `` After working five or six hours rehearsing, then rushing home and getting dinner on the table and listening to problems about trigonometry or getting kids bathed and ready for bed, it cleaned out that period of time for me emotionally,'' she recalls. `` I could go back to the theater fresh and ready to do a show.'' It was good for the children, too. ` It made them more independent and helped them get along together,'' she says. Now they have left home and she can concentrate on her career. `` I love the work so I'm not averse to doing something that is n't necessarily going to reflect my 35 years in the business,'' she says A year ago, she was Klytemnestra in a production of `` Elektra'' by <PERSON> Ezra </PERSON> <PERSON> Pound </PERSON> at a miniscule off-off-Broadway theater for a miniscule salary. `` If it interests me, I'll do it.'' Right now, she still is fascinated by `` The Cocktail Hour,'' striving to make the production and her performance better. `` Although it's a play of language, it's economical,'' she says. `` Because language is so specific, you ca n't fool around with the words, changing them or changing the syntax because you will change the rhythm and often change the meaning. That is the hardest thing to do _ to get the words absolutely perfect. `` The woman I play is very smart about dealing with the rhythms of the family,'' Miss <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> says. `` Quite early on in the play, she says, ` I want to know what I missed,' and discovers what she missed was not very good. So she immediately drops it and then picks up and approaches it from a totally different point of view. But it's all done, I hope, as smooth as silk. She calms the waters.''
