 `` Paint Another Picture'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Darlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Love </PERSON> <PERSON> Darlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Love </PERSON> is one of the greatest rock' n' roll singers ever to grace our planet. Her work with <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Spector </PERSON> in the 1960s _ `` He's a Rebel,'' `` <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ron </PERSON>'' _ recorded under a variety of names, stands as the definition of the <PERSON> Spector </PERSON> sound. And `` Christmas -LRB- Baby, Please Come Home -RRB-'' is simply the best rock' n' roll Christmas record ever. That's why her first solo album, even with help from <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Petty </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> and master producer <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Iovine </PERSON>, is a disappointment. Love is n't the problem here. Thankfully, she's not one of those time-ravaged legends croaking their way to another payday; after more than two decades at it, she still sings stunningly well. The problem is the material, which is, simply, uninteresting. Too often, Love is forced to fight her way out of syntho-pop musical cliches, and that's a tremendous waste. Best is Petty's `` We Stand a Chance,'' which rocks a bit but is n't exactly `` He's a Rebel.'' And the inclusion of a straight cover of `` You'll Never Walk Alone'' _ yep, the same one <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> moans on Labor Day _ is simply puzzling. The record clocks in under 32 minutes, which, one assumes, is testimony enough to the problem Love had in finding worthy songs for this project. Since `` Paint Another Picture'' probably wo n't sell a zillion copies, here's hoping <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> gives her another chance. The notion of <PERSON> Darlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Love </PERSON> making rock' n' roll records again is exciting; it's too bad this record is n't _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer
