<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Richard Thompson Still Has a Sense of Purpose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> has been making records for over 20 years. His music, though, draws on sources much older. `` I hope that things like age are n't that important,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, 39, a guitarist, singer and songwriter who helped form the seminal English folk-rock group, <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention, in 1967. `` When I was 20, I was listening to people who were dead. You have to listen to everything.'' <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention seemed to work in the opposite direction of rock music at the time. Instead of being influenced by the psychedelic sounds of the Beatles on `` Sgt. Pepper,'' <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention incorporated music from previous centuries. Rather than use backward tape loops and distorted guitars, <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention experimented with the fiddle and mandolin. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who left the group in 1971, recalled the sense of purpose the members shared. `` We were concerned about reviving a traditional music in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. I listened to a lot of Scottish music. That's a thing that's important to me. We listened to traditional music and jazz and rock' n' roll. `` There was a great spirit of camaraderie and musical exploration. I remember a feeling of kinship with the bandmates at the time.'' And hit singles were not important. `` I never even thought about it. It never crossed my mind that I was going into the music business. I just found myself being a professional musician.'' His first solo album, `` Henry the Human Fly,'' came out in 1972, and combined folk-rock music with <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s hard-edged singing. The same year, he married <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, a former backup singer, and the two went on to record seven LPs together. In 1982, they released `` Shoot Out the Lights,'' one of the most acclaimed records of the year, but were divorced soon after. The popularity of the recording duo threatened to overshadow <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s solo career as fans speculated whether his often bitter love songs were about <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>. `` Songs are really work of the imagination,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said. `` I think it's putting too much of a limit to say this song's about this person or that person. It should be bigger than that.'' In `` I Still Dream,'' a ballad off his new album, `` Amnesia,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> sings: `` And I never was to know that I'd come to miss you so. But time winds down and I turned my back long ago.'' He stressed the song was not about his ex-wife. `` It's really a story song. It's not me. I'm telling a story about a guy whose life seems aimless. It seems dull and dead. He's compromised himself all the way. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> took six weeks to make `` Amnesia,'' and for the first time, recorded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Yankee, Go Home,'' another song from the LP, might impress listeners as an attack against American imperialisn, but <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> does n't see it that way. `` I see it as a friendly arm around the shoulder of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Saying how we in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> used to have an empire and it got frittered away. Finally, we've learned to adjust to this ` tragic' fact. Now it's your turn. It's time for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> not to be Number 1.'' On `` <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> on the Jukebox,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> deals with a subject familiar to most Americans: television evangelists. `` ` <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>' is the name of a hymn sung in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. It's a great song. I heard it played on a television show and was so alarmed that things would reach this point. `` Is -LRB- evangelist -RRB- <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggert </PERSON> the tip of the iceberg? What passes for spirituality?'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> says there is not yet an English equivalent to <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggert </PERSON>, but there is the possibility: `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is dying for someone like <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggert </PERSON>. That sort of professional sincerity. He'd be huge in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.'' Many of <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s songs have sad overtones. He sings about jealousy, lost love, death. But he noted that just because songs are about sad events, they're not necessarily sad songs. `` It's sad, but cathartic. Expressing sadness is n't such a sad business. It can make you feel quite good. I supposed I'm a really a realist.'' A realist, not a cynic. Rock was once considered a music for young people, but many of its greatest performers are now middle-aged and have struggled for a reason to continue. Not <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. `` Every once in a while, I step to one side and ask myself the reason I'm playing music. Having re-established the direction, it's easier to keep going,'' he said `` If you see music as experiment and education, there is no end to it. You're always looking for the next thing. If you're commercially successful and you see that as the end, there's going to be a real anti-climax. And <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> still believes in drawing on a wide array of music, regardless of how many records he sells. `` Rock' n' roll is now so multi-generational. You can fit almost every musical style in existence into rock music these days. I'm on the edge of it rather than the middle of it.''
</TEXT>
