<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Country Music's Proving Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERA GROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's a tiny nightclub sandwiched between an office and recording studio, and a children's clothing store in the chic <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> section of the country music capital. The Bluebird Cafe may be a few miles from the well-worn paths tread by tourists, but it's a gathering place for recording industry executives and those trying to get their attention. It's the place where country music stars of tomorrow yearn to perform, waiting up to four months for a precious spot on the tiny stage. It's country music's answer to The Comedy Store, the Improv and Catch a Rising Star. It's country music's proving ground. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattea </PERSON> got her break there. So did the Sweethearts of the Rodeo, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON>, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>. `` I started playing there about every three or four weeks, and within three months of starting there I got a record deal,'' said <PERSON> Mattea </PERSON>, whose `` 18 Wheels and a Dozen Roses'' was voted single of the year by the <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. When featured performers are presented Friday and Saturday nights, it's standing room for those without reservations and a tight fit for those who do have them. The intimate atmosphere is integral to the music. Owner <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> said she has no plans to move although the 6-year-old club seats only 130 or 150 sardine-style. `` It feels like a living room. Sometimes it's more intimidating because you can see every face in the room,'' <PERSON> Mattea </PERSON> said. Songwriter <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Knobloch </PERSON> agrees, but adds the closeness of the audience is a barometer of how new songs and songwriters are being received. `` The audiences are so close that they feel real involved in what you're doing. If you're good, they love you; if you're bad, they are polite and get up and leave,'' he said. About 90 percent of the crowd is involved in the music business and the remainder are tourists and locals, or `` real people'' as <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> calls them. `` I desire that people be specifically interested in the music, that listening to live music is enough and maybe having a glass of wine _ not picking somebody up,'' <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> said. `` The quality -LRB- of the performers -RRB- is always excellent. I maybe book one or two people I'm disappointed with in a year.'' <PERSON> Knobloch </PERSON> is often joined by fellow country-acoustic songwriters <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuyler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Bickhardt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlitz </PERSON> to become SKBS, one of the club's top draws. <PERSON> Schlitz </PERSON> wrote `` The Gambler'' for <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Knobloch </PERSON> created `` Used to Be Blue'' for <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bickhardt </PERSON> wrote the <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wariner-Nicolette </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> duet `` That's How You Know When Love's Right. <PERSON> Knobloch </PERSON> got his start at the Bluebird at a Sunday writer's night _ a night set aside for songwriters to perform their new compositions. <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> is deluged with tapes from those who know that playing a writer's night could mean a break. `` We make the music business accessible to the new guy,'' <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> said. `` But if it was n't for the Bluebird and some other places to play, you could never really function as a songwriter -LRB- in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> -RRB-. Appearing here is a crucial part of the process.'' Budding songwriters know this and the walls of <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON>'s claustrophobic office prove it Demonstration tapes fill racks on an entire wall and others are scattered on her desk where a phone rings repeatedly and a mammoth stuffed carnival prize snake curls watching overhead. If the music satisfies <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON>'s discriminating ear, there is a four-month wait between an audition at the Bluebird until a writer can perform on a Sunday night show. `` From the time they get here to the time I would sign them as an act on a feature show, it will be nine months to one year,'' she said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON>, a promising acoustic-folk artist, did his time on the Bluebird circuit and <PERSON> Kurland </PERSON> has, for the first time, decided to promote the undiscovered <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor-styled </PERSON> artist among her contacts in the record world. Despite the time it takes to get on stage, many songwriters hunger after a spot on the club's calendar. `` It is a songwriter's paradise,'' said <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavender </PERSON>, executive director of the <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> Songwriters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Bluebird plays a magnificent role -LRB- in the industry -RRB-. ... It is one of the greatest clubs in town. In my estimation, I think the Bluebird is the ultimate in that sort of thing -LRB- displaying songwriter's abilities -RRB-.''
