<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>1988 Kindles Hopes for Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Guns fell silent on several battlefronts in 1988, and hope emerged that mankind stood at the dawn of a more peaceful age. It seemed as though the world had decided it had enough of war. Blood was still being shed in some parts of the globe. But <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> opted for a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the Soviets began to withdraw troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> chose to work towards peace in southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The year began with the ink barely dry on the first superpower treaty to eliminate a class of nuclear weapons. Before the year was out, many missiles were destroyed. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> truce troops won the Nobel Peace Prize. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met not once, but twice, with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who announced unilateral reductions in military strength. `` Forces have already emerged in the world that in one way or another stimulate the arrival of a period of peace,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Among other developments, Olympic athletes from both East and West met in the Summer Games for the first time in 12 years in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Fears of North Korean sabotage of the Games proved unfounded, and the two Koreas took steps toward reconciliation. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> also mediated peace talks on the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, which occupies most of the northwest African territory, and the Polisario independence movement. <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s non-communist nations, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and the U.N.-recognized Cambodian government-in-exile worked toward getting Vietnamese occupying forces to withdraw from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders met to discuss the possibility of reuniting the divided <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> said it recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statements still did not go far enough. Meanwhile, Palestinians died at the rate of almost one a day in their anti-Israeli uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. And conflicts raged on in many other parts of the globe: _ <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> struggled through political turmoil _ <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> simmered with continued fighting in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and an uneasy truce in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> _ Moslem guerrillas continued their fight in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> against the Soviet-allied government _ The Sikhs still struggled for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, as did the Tamils in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, and other rebel groups in the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> _ Five thousand died in ethnic violence in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> _ Dozens died and thousands were forced to leave their homes because of domestic unrest in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in the southern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ And in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the streets of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> remained a battleground The nation came closer than ever to formal partitioning into Christian and Moslem sectors, and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> raiders struck repeatedly against the south in retaliation for anti-Israel guerrilla activity. Still, the year wound to a close with a sense of hope. `` There is a new mood of understanding and common sense,'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in accepting the peace prize Dec. 10. `` We can, and must, achieve what we have dreamed of for so long, that is to make the rule of law the standard rather than the exception in world affairs.''
