<HEAD>Crippen's `Go' Puts Americans Back in Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With tension high, the countdown clock for the launch of space shuttle Discovery ticked down to nine minutes, and then was stopped, deliberately, to be held there for 10 minutes while one man made the critical decision on whether to proceed toward liftoff. This was no ordinary countdown. It was to be <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s first shuttle flight since the Challenger explosion killed seven crew members 32 monthsture of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program was at stake. Memories of that tragedy were earlier. The fu on everyone's mind as five astronauts boarded Discovery on the morning of Sept. 29. One of the astronauts' own, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Crippen </PERSON>, a veteran of four shuttle missions, had the awesome responsibility to make the decision that would send them on their way, or keep them on the ground for another day. <PERSON> Crippen </PERSON>'s assignment was a product of Challenger. No one man held sole authority to say `` go'' or `` no-go'' on any of the previous 26 shuttle launches. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> decided it needed such a launch czar to avoid the communications failures that prevented the concerns of lower-level engineers about cold weather from reaching those making the decision to launch Challenger. The frigid temperature was cited by inve. Two months later, the count reached nine minutes on the second post-Challenger mission. Again, high altitude winds were a problem. This time they were too strong, but they moderated gradually throughout the morning. <PERSON> Crippen </PERSON> looked at the latest data and made his decision, dispatching <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> and five astronauts on a secret <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> mission during which they reportedly released a sophisticated reconnaissance satellite. It was another successful flight on <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s comeback trail. The successes set the stage for a stepped-up shuttle launch schedule in 1989. Seven flights are planned, including three scientifically prized missions that will deploy the <ORGANIZATION> Hubble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION> and dispatch payloads to <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> and Jupiter.
</TEXT>
