<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 If you're under 50, skip this story. If you read it, you may wish you were older. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rattner </PERSON> <PERSON> Heilman </PERSON> _ who is over 50 _ has compiled a book of bargains for those born at least half a century ago, with information varying from hotel, motel and restaurant discounts to over-50 bike tours and ski clubs. Titled `` Unbelievably Good Deals and Great Adventures That You Absolutely Ca n't Get Unless You're Over 50'' -LRB- Contemporary Books -RRB-, the paperback also deals with travel and tour tips, breaks on airfare and car rentals, perks in parks, even going back to school. The idea for the book started with Ms. <PERSON> Heilman </PERSON>'s national magazine article, which got a response indicating `` everybody is interested'' in the subject, she says. With about one-quarter of the nation's population in the over-50 category, `` everybody is jumping on the bandwagon and there are new things all the time,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Heilman </PERSON>. She has updated the original 1988 book with some new `` deals'' for a 1989 edition. `` On your 50th birthday,'' Ms. <PERSON> Heilman </PERSON> writes, `` you qualify for hundreds of special opportunities and money-saving offers that will have lots of people wishing they were older. All for a couple of good reasons. `` First, you deserve them, having successfully negotiated your way through life's white waters. `` And second, as the fastest-growing segment of the American population, you represent an enormous market of potential consumers, a fact that has become quite apparent to the business community.'' Her biggest piece of advice: `` Make a practice of asking if there are breaks to which you are entitled wherever you go, from movies to museums, concerts to historic sites, hotels to ski resorts, restaurants to riverboats, in this country and abroad. Do n't expect clerks or ticket agents to volunteer them to you.'' She adds: `` Remember to request your privileges before you pay or when you order or make reservations, and always carry proof of age or an over-50-club membership card, or, better yet, both.''
