<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: RVs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY704, NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Millions of mature Americans are spending their time, independence and money on traveling in recreation vehicles, reports a national association for the retired. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- estimates that nine million senior Americans use recreation vehicles each year. `` Mature travelers are good candidates for RV travel,'' says <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Noe </PERSON>, member services specialist for <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION>, `` because many have the time, discretionary funds and desire to see and experience the small towns, big cities, popular attractions and natural beauty of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` RVs provide them with an enjoyable, comfortable and economical way to take it all in and enjoy the social benefits of camaraderie on the road.'' A <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> survey of the recreation vehicle consumer reported that nearly 10 percent of heads of households over 50 who own vehicles own 30 percent of the RVs in use. <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> reports that RV trips account for 18 percent of all trips taken by those in the 55-59 age group. Seventy-two percent of all RV trips are made by travelers 50 years and older, <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> says. Recreation vehicles include motor homes, travel trailers, truck campers, folding camping trailers and van conversions.
