<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:WithDrivers-Vision     12-12 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature Years: With Drivers-Vision,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: With Drivers-Vision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Older adults generally do not have to give up driving because of aging changes in vision _ but they should recognize their limitations, advises the American <ORGANIZATION> Optometric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. More than 37 million Americans over 55 years old drive, and according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> they have a poorer accident record than drivers in their middle years. Failure to yield right-of-way, improper lane changes, passing and turning are among the most common traffic violations committed by older drivers, national studies have shown. According to the optometrists, changes in vision may interfere with older drivers' abilities to see and recognize what is on the road ahead, to see effectively at night, to see against the glare of oncoming headlights and to recover quickly from glare. Other factors include faulty judging of distances between themselves and other vehicles or objects, and the detection of movement from the side while looking straight ahead. Suggestions from the optometrists on how older drivers can compensate for vision changes include: _ Avoid driving at dusk. _ When driving at night, reduce speed, try to limit driving to well-lighted or familiar roads, and keep headlights, taillights and turn signals clean and properly adjusted. _ Take time to adjust to a new eyeglass or contact lens prescription before driving. _ Avoid frames with wide side pieces that may block side vision. _ Wear quality sunglasses on sunny or bright, cloudy days, but never wear sunglasses, or fashion-tinted lenses, when driving at night. _ Confine driving to places, speeds and hours in which they are comfortable and competent. _ Avoid pulling off alongside the highway. If necessary, use the car's four-way emergency flashers. _ Keep windshield and rear windows clean, inside and out, and replace worn wiper blades promptly. _ Keep rear view and outside mirrors clean and properly adjusted. Be aware of their limitations.
</TEXT>
