<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:NursingHomes     12-12 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Nursing Homes,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Nursing Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 40 percent of nursing homes failed to meet sanitary standards for food and nearly 30 percent failed to meet standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness, according to the federal government's first consumer guide to nursing homes. The survey also found that more than one-fourth of the nursing homes do not administer drugs properly. However, Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> that compiled and released the statistics, cautioned against reading more into the figures than is warranted. `` This is not the ultimate report card for nursing homes around the country,'' <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> told reporters. He said the `` met-unmet'' criteria for each of the 32 categories included in the state-by-state reports contains no measure of severity and represented a one-time `` snapshot'' of conditions at the nursing home's most recent unannounced inspection. To some degree, he said, it relied on the subjective judgment of the inspector. At the same time, <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> defended release of the report against industry criticism that it would mislead consumers. One complaint was, for example, that a nursing home might be given an `` unmet'' mark on proper administration of medication if one patient was five minutes late getting his or her medicine. `` If one person was five minutes late, I'm sure they would not have been dinged in the survey,'' <PERSON> Roper </PERSON> said. `` What we're looking at, what the surveyors look at is the pattern of care over time. `` We are not in the business of making arbitrary, bureaucratic judgments. We are trying to evaluate what is really happening to people in that nursing home.'' He added: `` What we are looking for ... is not nursing home providers that barely scrape by. We're looking for people who are good providers, consistently, over time, 365 days a year. And I have to believe that if that's where a nursing home operator has his or her nursing home, they are not going to be worried about being dinged on some trivial point.'' The 75-volume guide shows how each of the 15,000 nursing homes fared on 32 health, safety and care standards based on periodic inspections by state agencies. About 2,400 of the 15,000 received passing marks in all 32 categories. According to the survey, nearly 43 percent of the homes failed to meet sanitary standards for food. Almost 30 percent failed to meet standards for maintaining residents' personal cleanliness and 29 percent failed to administer drugs according to doctors' orders. However, the report also said that only a small percentage of the nursing homes failed to meet standards in many other categories. Overall among skilled homes, the failure rate exceeded 15 percent in only 10 categories. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Willging </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents more than 9,000 nursing homes, said the report `` is misleading _ it is going to confuse the public'' by making it appear conditions are worse than they are. He said that something like a cracked egg in a refrigerator could lead to a nursing home failing to meet a care standard. But <PERSON> Elma </PERSON> <PERSON> Holder </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> on Nursing Home Reform, said: `` We think the national statistics are misleading Conditions are worse.''
