<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Alzheimer's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The focus on Alzheimer's disease generally is on the patients, not their families. But a new program uses coloring books, a mascot dog and movies to show elementary school pupils how the debilitating ailment can be battled. For a few hours, the students put aside their reading, writing and arithmetic to look at a disease that may not afflict them for 60 years, if at all. The purpose of the effort is not so much to understand how the disease works but to show how the loved ones of an Alzheimer's sufferer can, with patience, helpful advice and love, minimize the worst of the disease's effects Alzheimer's, characterized by memory loss and other dementia, afflicts an estimated 5 million mostly elderly Americans. The southern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION>, which is in the third year of a federal <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> grant intended to promote community programs, developed the daylong seminar on Alzheimer's after meetings between school officials and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> of New Jersey-based <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, who spends summers there. <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> manufactures Hydergine, a drug that can ease some symptoms of Alzheimer's in milder cases. <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION> changed the emphasis because of mounting evidence that children are often acutely aware of and confused by the decline of a loved one. A coloring book titled `` Helping Grandma,'' by <ORGANIZATION> Westport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> art teacher <PERSON> Betsey </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, told the story of a grandmother who gradually begins to show signs of memory loss. `` Children are often kept in the dark about aging,'' said <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>. `` They automatically think that ` old' means ` sick.' But children are wonderfully resilient and surprisingly insightful when spoken to directly on the subject.'' The point of the coloring book, geared toward elementary school children, is to `` teach them understanding and to teach them that what she needs is support.'' Also, mature, well-behaved dogs from an animal shelter can provide some stability and love for an Alzheimer's sufferer, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON>, a black and white mongrel from a <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> animal shelter, has become the national poster dog for the so-called human-animal bonding campaign, and he travels with <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> to events on the subject. The Alzheimer's event was tried out earlier this year in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.
