<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Arthritis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Use the rubber end of a pencil or pen to push the buttons of a telephone or turn the pages of a book. Use an electric stapler to help reduce fatigue in hands, wrists and shoulders. If you are n't up to typing, use a dictating machine. These are among suggestions for office workers who suffer from arthritis to help ease their work. The advice comes from <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, who has had rheumatoid and psoriatic arthritis for nearly 20 years and is now a volunteer counselor for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> chapter of the Arthritis Foundation. `` Until recently,'' she said in a recent issue of AIMplus, an arthritis information magazine, `` people with arthritis found it very difficult to keep on working _ not because they did n't want to, but because the attitude of society in generally has been that a disabled person ` just could n't do the job.''' While attitudes have changed, she said, and many disabled persons are finding less difficulty in finding and keeping a job, `` some people with arthritis may find that their condition does somewhat limit their abilities to accomplish as much as they would like.'' She offers some other suggestions to ease that problem: _ Conserve energy by planning ahead; schedule the more demanding tasks for times of day when you are feeling your best. _ Make sure your chair provides firm support for your lower back and has armrests to help reduce fatigue in your shoulders. The chair should be high enough to get in and out of without strain, and low enough so you do n't have to hunch over while working. _ To ease strain on your neck, place text on a tying rack rather than keeping it flat beside your desk.
