of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>. Sixty percent of the more than 4,000 people surveyed were in the 65-plus age category; 20 percent in the 55-64 age group, and 20 percent were adults up to age 54. More than 2,500 responded to the survey. The study also found that the elderly strongly prefer the `` personal touch'' from sales people and dislike `` high pressure'' sales tactics. The survey had some advice for those doing the selling as well. `` Be patient with the elderly,'' <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> suggested. `` Do n't assume because of their age that they can not understand complex information They grasp things just like everybody else, but it may take them longer. `` Do n't give them too much clutter to wade through. Their eyesight may not be quite as good; use larger type in your printed material, slow down in your approach, simplify, and, above all, never think of the elderly as ` senile' or ` cranky' in their ways,'' she says. `` They resent these stereotypes.''
