 After the children grow up and leave home, there may be a problem left over: what to do about the piano. Do n't let it just sit in a corner of the living room gathering dust, says the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Piano </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which suggests parents of adult children who have left the nest can find many enjoyable ways to keep the piano an important part of their homes. A piano is not only a beautiful piece of furniture, but it represents an investment, both in time and money, according to the foundation. `` There are a lot of memories attached to our piano,'' says <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Krouse </PERSON>, a publisher from <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, who bought the family piano with his wife, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>, when they were first married. `` Even though my eldest daughter _ our piano enthusiast _ has moved out of the area, I would n't dream of giving it up.'' Although the Krouses are not piano players themselves, they have kept it in frequent use by hiring pianists to play at several parties they've hosted. And they have a few friends who play the piano when they visit. One way to enjoy your piano after the kids have stopped playing, suggests the foundation, is to take lessons yourself. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevitz </PERSON>, a retired mechanical engineer in <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, recently began piano lessons, marking the first time he's studied piano in nearly 50 years and the first time his piano has been used regularly since his stepdaughter moved out of the house `` When I retired I had all this new-found free time,'' says <PERSON> Sevitz </PERSON>. `` And the piano was n't getting much use, so I decided it was a good time to learn to play _ something I've wanted to do all my life.'' <PERSON> Sevitz </PERSON> signed up for a pia