<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Careers     12-12 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Careers,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Careers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Depending on where they work, aging white-collar workers face a job outlook ranging from `` crash-and-burn'' to a possible triple career ladder, according to a study of 25 `` Fortune 500'' companies. The state of the economy and the industry, the company `` personality,'' the nature of corporate leadership and the organizational structure were among the factors shaping company responses to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> survey. `` All of these factors can change over time, so you can not lock a company into a particular behavior pattern,'' says <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirshorn </PERSON>, research fellow at the university's Population Studies Center. `` It is clear, however, that a company under economic stress is much more likely to consider actions hurtful to older workers.'' Typical corporate responses indicated five distinct company policies toward elder employees, those over 55, <PERSON> Hirshorn </PERSON> notes. They were characterized as `` pro-active,'' `` performance-focused,'' `` at cross-purposes,'' `` positive means-negative ends'' and `` antagonistic.'' `` Pro-active'' companies deal most effectively with older workers, she explains, planning strategies that build in options for workers at all ages as well as options for the company as a whole. `` Dual or even triple career ladders are not uncommon in pro-active companies,'' she adds. `` They encourage lateral career changes and intentionally reassign workers at all ages to relieve boredom and stress.'' <PERSON> Hirshorn </PERSON> says `` performance-focused'' companies try to ignore age as a criterion altogether, consistently applying a reliable evaluation system to all workers. But occasionally, companies are at cross-purposes in their policies, she notes. `` The company ethos may hold older workers in high regard, and managers may even design some effective policies for them,'' she says. `` At the same time, they are designing others that have an unfortunate effect ... They do n't coordinate policies and plan for change.'' An example of such cross-purposes would be companies that offer limited opportunities for promotion or lateral moves, and massive, sweetened early retirement programs. Some companies are actively antagonistic toward older workers, and the hostility shows up in a variety of policies, <PERSON> Hirshorn </PERSON> found. `` I came across one insurance company where age bias ran deeply throughout the ranks,'' she recalls. `` Those who refused to relocate were fired, and since so few employees over 55 were promoted, many older workers left.''
</TEXT>
