<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--MatureYears:Briefs     12-12 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature Years: Briefs,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>MATURE YEARS: Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of 45 - to 64-year-olds in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will increase by 30 percent in the 1990s, according to a population study sponsored by Better Homes and Gardens magazine The age group will increase by 40 to 50 percent in the South and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, and by about 20 percent in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, the study reported.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 One-third of elderly Americans living in their communities say their health is excellent or very good, reports the Statistical Bulletin, a publication of the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The findings, among those aged 65 or over, are based on a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interview </ORGANIZATION> Survey conducted in 1983-84. The report said the proportion does not change among those aged 85 and over. However, those interviewed did not include elderly people in hospitals or nursing homes, the segment in poorest health. The proportion of blacks assessing their health as excellent or very good was one-fourth. The most frequently reported disability was arthritis; second was hypertension.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Hyatt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s first senior living community, a 223-unit rental housing complex for those over 62, is scheduled for completion in April 1989. Called Classic Residence, it will occupy 5.44 acres in <LOCATION> Teaneck </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 In order to detect lung disease, the National Jewish Center for Immunology and Respiratory Medicine, in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, suggests that senior citizens ask for a breathing test called spirometry as part of every physical examination. The spirometer measures the lungs' `` forced vital capacity,'' say researchers at the hospital, or how well a person can force air from the lungs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Multiple medical problems come with age, resulting in multiple drugs,'' says the director of geriatric programs at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> medical center, who warns users of possible over-medication or over-accumulation. `` Without careful monitoring,'' says Dr. <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hyde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, `` the drugs that keep our elderly alive longer, can also sharply minimize the quality of life.'' At the Daughters of <ORGANIZATION> Jacob </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geriatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where the average age of the residents is 87, about 80 to 90 percent of them take a `` medication holiday'' from non-essential medication each Monday. `` The program is designed to cleanse the body, decrease possible side effects and provide the opportunity to re-evaluate prescription patterns,'' says <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogelman </PERSON>, president of Daughters of <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>. `` Ultimately, some medications may be changed, some eliminated completely.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Rowing is one of the best fitness sports for older Americans, says <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> `` Fritz'' <PERSON> Hagerman </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> exercise physiologist and consultant to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rowing teams in the past five Olympics. In a recent rowing study including 14 men and women over age 60, <PERSON> Hagerman </PERSON> found that virtually all showed improvement in cardiovascular function. `` Rowing has tremendous potential among older people,'' says <PERSON> Hagerman </PERSON>, chairman of zoological and biomedical sciences at the university.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> professor says American men over 85 are a privileged minority, with more money, better health and more social contact than women the same age. According to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Longino </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an authority on aging demographics, a study of <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> data disclosed one of the big differences was that nearly half the men among <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s 2.2 million very old persons had spouses, while only one-tenth of the women were still married.
</TEXT>
