<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> boosted some incentives and extended others after other automakers made similar moves earlier this week, while <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> extended an offer of free gasoline for some car buyers. Announced Friday, the new <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> incentives ranged from $ 300 to $ 3,000 and expire in January or February, depending on the model of car and where it is purchased. Meantime, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s Oldsmobile Division said it was extending its offer for a year's free gasoline from Nov. 31 to Dec. 31 for some Cutlass Supreme buyers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to sell <ORGANIZATION> Michie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which publishes materials for the legal profession, to the <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a paper, forest products and electronic publishing concern, for about $ 226.5 million. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> said Friday in signing a letter of intent that the companies hoped to complete the deal before the end of the year. It would be the second major asset sale involving <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> since the giant publishing concern was acquired for $ 2.5 billion in early November by <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the British communications company run by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC and <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> said they would delay their 1.7 billion-pound, or $ 3.1 billion, joint bid for the British electronics firm <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC pending a high court hearing late next <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> obtained a preliminary injunction Friday from the High Court blocking the offer before a full court hearing on whether the bid infringes on the anti-competition provisions of the Treaty of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is denying speculation that a move to break up the sales force it shares with <ORGANIZATION> Continential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is intended to do anything but sell more tickets. But labor officials said Friday the move to separate the two carriers' sales forces, which were combined after <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought both airlines, may be an indication the company is being readied for sale.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> must wait in line to take action against <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> businessmen <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, a federal bankruptcy judge has ruled. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> said Thursday he has approved a request by attorneys representing the two Hunts to forestall any <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> action while the brothers work out their bankruptcy settlements. In a civil complaint against the Hunts, the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> claims the brothers and others rigged the price of silver futures between the fall of 1979 and March 1980.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market posted small gains Friday as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.78 to 2,143.49, closing out the week with a net gain of 51.21 points. The dollar was mixed against the major foreign currencies. Bond prices ended mixed in slow trading. Sugar futures prices soared to four-month highs; coffee, cattle, pork, energy and precious-metals futures all gained; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
