<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was higher in thin trading in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> late this morning, but traders said they expected no major movement in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ahead of Wednesday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for October. Gold prices also rose. Trading volume was light with few players keen to take a strong position before the trade figures are released and in advance of the bi-weekly meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday, when the West German central bank could decide to raise a key interest rate, dealers said. One trader with a branch of a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial bank in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> said the foreign exchange market expects the October trade deficit to be little changed from its $ 10.5-billion shortfall in September. She said a single-figure deficit would `` clearly be positive'' for the dollar, but cautioned that `` we've seen this year that this figure is pretty difficult to call accurately.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.49 yen to a closing 122.92 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 122.85 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.7378 West German marks, up from 1.7330; 1.4645 Swiss francs, up from 1.4605; 5.9415 French francs, up from 5.9240; 1.9622 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9560; 1,283.20 Italian lire, up from 1,280.25; 1.1988 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1970 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.8420, compared with $ 1.8490 Friday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 421 a troy ounce, up from $ 420.70 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 421, unchanged from the opening bid. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 421 up from $ 420.30 bid late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 2.10 to close at a bid $ 422.29. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.16 a troy ounce, unchanged from Friday.
</TEXT>
