<HEAD>Stocks Plunge, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices plunged on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today, while the dollar edged up against the Japanese yen as investors remained on the sidelines ahead of trade reports, dealers said. The dollar closed at 122.92 yen, up 0.49 yen from Friday's close of 122.43 yen. The currency opened at 122.70 yen and traded between 122.70-123 .00 yen The 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> lost 121.13 points or 0.41 percent to finish trading at 29,672.29. The index, a 34.52-point winner Friday, gained 40.35 points in early morning trading but erased the gain and continued to drop. The dollar's higher opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed its firmness in the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> market that opened earlier, dealers said. The dollar moved higher as foreign investors purchased the currency in morning trading but fluctuated around 122.80 yen, failing to rise beyond the 123-yen level, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Once it reached the upper part of the 122-yen range, the dollar hardly moved,'' the dealer said. He said trading was thin because many currency players were cautious ahead of the release of trade figures this week. Japanese trade figures for November were to be released later today. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is to report the nation's trade figure for October on Wednesday. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said Sunday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> that the dollar should stabilize because its further decline would raise import prices and lead to inflation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said in a lecture at a meeting called the'89 <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Forum that cutting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fiscal deficits and preventing inflation are vital for restoring trust in the dollar. On the stock exchange, share prices fell as investors stayed on the sidelines in anticipation of the release of Japanese and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures this week, said <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. Frequent fluctuations of the index and lack of direction in trading are typical toward the end of a year, <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> said. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 600 million shares in inactive trading.
</TEXT>
