<HEAD>Unions Hope To Bring Spain To Standstill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s major trade unions, unhappy over the economic austerity of Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>'s government, are taking to the streets to demand a bigger share in the country's new prosperity A broad spectrum of society _ including autoworkers, actresses, soccer players and sportswriters _ say they will support Wednesday's general strike called by the socialist <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and the communist-dominated <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Strike organizers say they want to bring the country of 38 million to a standstill to force a change in the government's economic policies The unions also called for a demonstration on Friday in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and said if the government does not respond, more demonstrations will follow. Since taking office in December 1982, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> has encouraged moderate wage increases to stem inflation, prod economic growth and create jobs to cut <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s 19.3 percent unemployment rate _ the highest in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Due partly to lower wage increases backed in the past by the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has been booming since 1986. More than 600,000 new jobs have been created, although growing numbers of youths and women entering the market have kept unemployment high. Annual inflation has dropped from 14.5 percent to 5.1 percent. There have been reports of huge profits by Spanish banks and corporations. Now, the unions are demanding a share of the wealth for workers who sacrificed higher pay in the past few years to help pull <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> out of a 10-year economic recession. The causes of the economic problems included the sharp rise in oil prices after the oil embargo of the early 1970s, when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s energy needs were met by imported crude, and protectionism under <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s 1939-1975 rule What set off the strike call was the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>' passage Oct. 28 of a youth employment plan It allows businesses who hire 18 - to 25-year-olds for six to eight months at wages below the minimum to reduce their contributions to the government social security plan The government said the plan will create incentives to hire youths. An estimated 40 percent of the age group have never held a job. Unions say the plan exploits young people, benefits businesses, and jeopardizes jobs and pay for older workers. The nationwide general strike would be the first in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> since October 1934, when a leftist-inspired work stoppage turned into an insurrection that was put down by troops commanded by Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> under orders from the then-conservative government of the Second Republic. Analysts do not expect violence this time, but the feud between union leaders and top <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials has taken on the hallmarks of a dramatic showdown. <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Redondo </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, has compared remarks from <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> executive <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Benegas </PERSON> criticizing the planned strike to comments by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> propaganda chief <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Goebbels </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, in turn, has accused the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of `` sliding toward the red,'' falling under the influence of the more combative communist union. When right-wing and centrist opposition parties, with <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> support, tried to pass a motion to urge the unions to call off the strike, two small leftist parties voted against it. Approval required a unanimous vote. Newspapers described the incident as a sign of the ineffectiveness of the parties and parliament in breaking the union-government impasse. After union-government wage talks broke down in the autumn, the unions began accusing the <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> government of arrogance and lack of `` social sensitivity.'' In a recent news conference, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> acknowledged that some arrogance could have creeped into his government but said this was no reason to stage a general strike.
</TEXT>
