<HEAD>EEC Concludes Textiles Agreement With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it had concluded a new four-year agreement on trade in textiles with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The agreement, to replace the existing pact which expires at the end of the year, will increase slightly the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s imports of textiles from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The accord also places new restrictions on selected textile imports including synthetic yarn, knitted gloves and suits. In addition, some textile products that were not subject to quotas under the existing agreement will be brought under quota coverage, the commission said. Textiles account for about one third of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s exports to the EEC. They rose to 1.24 billion European currency units, or $ 1.47 billion in 1987 from 893.6 million Ecus, or $ 1.06 million in 1986.
