<SECOND>PM-Tenneco-Future,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenneco Still Profitable After Oil and Gas Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The decision to sell off <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was a difficult one, but the mammoth $ 7.3 billion sale still leaves <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> with five profitable businesses. After the sale, the Houston-based company remains the city's largest public company, with 1988 revenue close to $ 13 billion, and projected revenue of about $ 14 billion in 1990 `` I think it will surprise a lot of people to realize that we are as big as this without the oil company,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said in a wide-ranging interview published in Sunday's editions of the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> sale was difficult not only because of the impact on the nearly 9,000 oil company and corporate employees involved, but also because of <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s new identity as a `` diversified industrial corporation.'' The company's other businesses include shipbuilding, automotive, chemicals, packaging and natural gas pipeline operations, which are all making money. One business making money is Case IH, the construction and farm equipment company that <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> formed in 1985 when JI Case acquired the agricultural implement division of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harvester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 513 million. Since then, <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> has plowed more than $ 700 million in capital expenditures into the subsidiary. Case IH has become the company's biggest business, but it has yet to show a profit <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> has designated 1989 as the make-or-break year for Case IH. If the profit are not there, Case IH could have a `` for sale'' sign hanging on its corporate door. But <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Khlopin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> doubts that <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> has plans to divest any other operations. `` Nothing this company has said has led anyone to believe they would sell anything other than exploration and production,'' he said. `` They're building up, not ripping down.'' Although Case IH's performance has fallen short of expectations, <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said, the Harvester acquisition and the subsequent consolidation and reorganization of Case IH were planned as a five-year project. What the company did not count on was the recession in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm belt that resulted in North American tractor sales falling from 90,000 in 1984 to 61,000 in 1986 and 1987, or last summer's drought that made many farmers postpone new equipment purchases. To help matters, <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> installed a new management team at the Case IH headquarters in <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis </LOCATION>. The new president, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashford </PERSON>, previously headed <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION>, which more than doubled its operating income during his five years as the top executive. <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s other business segments are demonstrating growth and improved profit at rates ranging from modest to booming, <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said. Natural gas transmission is <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s original business and its second largest source of revenue after agricultural and construction equipment. Since the natural gas transmission industry is mature, overall growth opportunities are limited, he said. Nevertheless, the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> is a consistently strong earner and supplier of cash flow, <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said. Its 20,000-mile system from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> serves one of the two areas where demand for natural gas is growing. Increases in federal defense spending since 1981 have helped <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> grow at a compound annual rate of 15.6 percent, but <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> acknowledged that defense expenditures probably will be cut in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. An $ 8 billion backlog that includes construction of two aircraft carriers and two submarines, along with future contracts for modernization and upgrading of existing <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels, should ensure at least incremental growth, the <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> chairman said. Packaging Corporation of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> offers the best potential for solid growth, <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said. Although it is the second-smallest <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> unit by revenues, <ORGANIZATION> PCA </ORGANIZATION> should have the second-highest operating profits for 1988 and should grow at an annual rate of 15 percent to 20 percent over the next five years, he said. Cardboard boxes are <ORGANIZATION> PCA </ORGANIZATION>'s primary product. <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said $ 65 million of <ORGANIZATION> PCA </ORGANIZATION>'s projected 1988 operating income of $ 220 million will come from specialty products the company did not make five years ago. <PERSON> Albright </PERSON> & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, a specialty chemicals producer and <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s smallest subsidiary, should grow an average of 20 percent for the next five years, the chairman said. <PERSON> Albright </PERSON> & amp; <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> is a major supplier of phosphates for detergents, soaps and shampoos, primarily in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and is the world's largest producer of sodium chlorate, used to bleach paper products. <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> has grown at a 13 percent rate for the past five years and is the leading manufacturer of mufflers, exhaust systems and shock absorbers for the replacement parts and accessories market. <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>'s other two major business segments _ natural gas pipelines and shipbuilding _ also will be solid performers, though not as the others, <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said.
