<HEAD>Reports Raise Hopes that Higher Interest Rates Are Working</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales fell by a larger-than-expected 0.5 percent in November as producer prices rose 0.3 percent, less than forecast, the government said Monday, raising hopes that higher interest rates were slowing down consumer spending and inflation. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 7.5 points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,742.8 after the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> issued its two reports late in the morning. But the index had been down as much as 11.8 points shortly before the economic figures were released. The pound held steady at about $ 1.8405. Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> pushed up interest rates to 13 percent from a decade low of 7.5 percent in June to discourage consumer spending and curb inflation, which has picked up to an annual rate of 6.4 percent from 3.3 percent in January. Private economists had forecast a rise or fall of 0.2 percent in retail sales and a 0.4-percent gain in producer prices. `` There are fairly clear signs that growth in retail sales is a lot slower than it was earlier this year,'' said economist <PERSON> Gwyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hacche </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's in the right direction.'' But he added: `` I would n't expect there to be clear evidence of the kind of slowdown we want probably for a few months. Really, the growth has got to come down quite a lot further.'' Retail sales were up 5.2 percent from November 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said. By comparison, retail sales volume rose 2.0 percent in October from the previous month and was up 6.2 percent from a year earlier. Producer output prices, or prices of manufactured goods, were up 4.8 percent from November 1987, the department reported. By comparison, output prices rose 0.4 percent in October from the previous month and were up 4.7 percent from a year earlier. These figures were n't seasonally adjusted.
