N> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> earlier this month issued an order preventing Popeyes' owner <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> from buying <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s stock until 10 working days after Popeyes revealed information on its buyout offer. Popeyes' first takeover deadline was Nov. 30, but has been extended to Friday. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> says he already owns 3.2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s stock and has been offered 14.6 million shares _ or about 40.6 percent _ of the 35.9 million outstanding shares of <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s stock Meanwhile, Church's has been courting offers from other investors, but also has become the subject of a class-action suit filed by a shareholder who claims the offer by Popeyes is adequate and that the Church's board's refusal to accept it could cost shareholders huge profits.
