<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Societe </PERSON> <PERSON> Generale </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Belgique </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s largest holding company, Monday forecast a loss of between 500 million and 2 billion Belgian francs _ between $ 13.5 and $ 54 million _ this year due to restructuring costs But the company said it expected much better results next year, possibly more than doubling the 3.611 billion francs, or $ 97.5 million, profit made last year. <ORGANIZATION> SGB </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that its operating results would have totaled about 10 billion francs, or $ 270.2 million, in 1988 if restructuring costs were not subtracted. Those costs, however, were estimated to be between 10.5 billion francs and 12 billion francs, or the equivalent of $ 283.8 to $ 324.3 million, wiping out the profit and leaving the estimated loss of 500 million to 2 billion francs. The company predicted that it would post operating results of about 12 billion francs in 1989 but declined to give a specific net profit forecast because the extent of restructuring costs was uncertain for that year. Meanwhile in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, French company <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, now the leading <ORGANIZATION> SGB </ORGANIZATION> shareholder, announced that that <ORGANIZATION> Compagnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Electricite </ORGANIZATION> would sell its 3.3 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> SGB </ORGANIZATION> in order to acquire a 2.8 percent holding. Belgian <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, second SGB shareholder, confirmed that Sodecom, the holding company which contained 42 percent of <ORGANIZATION> SGB </ORGANIZATION>, was being divided into three new units. One will be fully controlled by <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, a second by <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> and the two companies will share the third. <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> said that an effort will be made to return 12 percent of <ORGANIZATION> SGB </ORGANIZATION> shares to the public. Only two percent are currently traded and an additional 5 percent is being placed with institutional investors.
