<HEAD>Investor Group Offers Nearly $700 Million for Pennwalt Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An investment partnership offered almost $ 700 million cash today for <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a large Philadelphia-based chemical concern that makes industrial products such as caustic soda and chlorine. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor group <ORGANIZATION> Centaur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, which already owns 12.7 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>'s approximately 7.6 million shares outstanding, said it would pay other stockholders $ 100 a share for the rest. <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rocketed higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after the announcement, from $ 83 at Friday's close to $ 98 a share around mid-day today. Company officials declined to comment on the offer. But <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>, a rumored takeover target for months, had taken several defensive steps to thwart any unwelcome suitors, including the $ 460 million sale of pharmaceutical operations three months ago and a stock repurchase completed last week. `` We believe that our offer represents a fair price and is in the best interest of <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>'s shareholders,'' Centaur principals <PERSON> Abbey </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrin </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> management. The partners, who claimed to have assembled bank financing to make the purchase, said they were willing to negotiate any aspect of their offer including price. At the same time, the partners indicated they would resort to more hostile means to buy <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>, saying they had moved to invalidate the company's so-called `` poison pill'' shareholders ri