<HEAD>Scramble Under Way for New TV Stations in Portugal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It has all the ingredients for the kind of soap opera television viewers love: an intriguing former prime minister, international big business and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> fighting for wealth and power. But this is not <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. This is <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. And a real-life battle for control of one or two new, commercial television channels is brewing in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s poorest nation. Most observers say former Social Democrat Prime Minister <PERSON> Fransisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON> <PERSON> Balsemao </PERSON>, publisher of the country's most respected weekly paper, Expresso, is in the best position to win the first concession. But British press baron <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> are also eager to profit by bringing information, opinion and, above all, advertising, into the homes of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s 10 million inhabitants. RTP, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s 32-year-old, two-channel state television system, already carries advertising. According to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Televisao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION>, the commercial arm of RTP, 72.9 percent of <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> watch TV every day. <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> says this is the highest rate in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The most popular programs _ usually early evening `` TV novels'' like `` <PERSON> Roque </PERSON> <PERSON> Santeiro </PERSON>'' imported from Portuguese-speaking <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> _ find up to 90 percent of the country's viewing population glued to the screen. `` There is certainly demand for more choice _ new stations,'' said <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, sales director at <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION>, adding that many Portuguese, especially in poorer, isolated, rural areas have little other entertainment. `` They're all waiting for private TV because they think it will bring better programs.'' But some enterprising Portuguese can not wait. High-powered satellite dishes, capable of picking up neighboring <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s two programs and several Eurosatellite channels, have sprouted on more affluent rooftops in <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oporto </LOCATION> and the southern Algarve. At 200,000 escudos -LRB- about $ 1,300 -RRB- per dish, the antennae are too expensive for the average Portuguese, whose minimum monthly wage is 27,100 escudos -LRB- $ 179 -RRB- _ about half that of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and a quarter of the minimum monthly wage in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Poorer areas often solve the problem by pooling cash to buy communal dishes that can pick up programs from abroad for easy _ but illegal _ retransmission by cable to individual homes. Plans to introduce commercial television via private extension of the regular network were first discussed in 1982 but only now are likely to become a reality. In October Social Democrat Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> and the main opposition <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> reached an agreement to secure the necessary two-thirds parliamentary majority on a vote expected next spring to change the constitutional clause that restricts private ownership of TV stations. But the government could set up new channels by concession now without having to transfer ownership. `` It's very much a question of political will,'' <PERSON> Balsemao </PERSON> said, and, according to <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, a new commercial channel could be up and running by the end of 1989. <PERSON> Balsemao </PERSON> has already attracted support from <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> publishing circles and a minority participation from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s independent <ORGANIZATION> Granada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION>, to register SIC _ <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION>. He sees privatization of RTP-2, the second state-owned channel, as the quickest way to bring commercial television to <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. `` The longer the government waits, the more inroads foreign TV interests will make here, and the more difficult it will be for new <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> stations to break into the market.'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and publisher of a new European newspaper, could be one of the foreign interests. <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> has set up a joint venture with <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> communications concern <ORGANIZATION> Emaudio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> connected with Socialist President <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> and has already started to make inroads into the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> media market. `` Our principal objective is to control a regular TV channel, but we plan to go ahead with the launch of a Portuguese satellite channel by 1990 at the latest,'' <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Junqueiro </PERSON>, mastermind of <PERSON> Emaudio </PERSON>'s TV plans, said. Emaudio is already making headway in the expanding newspaper market here. Two weeks ago, it launched the first of two planned newspapers _ a non-glossy, investigative weekly called <PERSON> Primeira </PERSON> <PERSON> Pagina </PERSON>. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> plans to launch a daily called `` 24 Horas'' by the end of January. <PERSON> Magalhaes </PERSON> <PERSON> Crespo </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Administrative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Renascenca </ORGANIZATION>, the Church's nationwide radio network, and frontman for the future <ORGANIZATION> Televisao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catolica </ORGANIZATION>, says the Church's position as a mainstay of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s education system gives it a right to own a TV channel Market surveys show 29 percent of adult listeners tune in to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Renascenca </ORGANIZATION>, a figure twice that of the combined audience of its two state-owned competitors. But many are wary of the objectivity of a Church-controlled channel. `` It's true we are conservative in our outlook,'' <PERSON> Crespo </PERSON> said. `` But, in the case of our radio station, we never mix comment with information.'' More channels may not mean better television, <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` If these new channels want to make profits, they will have to resort to showing low-cost repeats of old films.'' It costs 10 times as much to produce a home-grown product, he said, than to buy a foreign import.
