<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv13   12-12 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 13,0721</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday, Dec. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>It's True: Success Produces Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many business consultants make a very good living analyzing corporate weaknesses and devising fix-up procedures that include new people, equipment and processes. Much time is involved. Lots of money. Repeated conferences too. Computer reports and graphs `` prove'' the erudition of the consultants. Indeed, if impressions were the measure of results these analyses would be invaluable. Contrast this complicated procedure with another approach, championed by a respected consultant, in which you focus on one problem or an aspect of one, attack it immediately with existing talent and produce immediate results. `` I've never seen a company in which it can not be done,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaffer </PERSON>, who has written a remarkable book of common sense and canny insight, buttressed by more than 25 years of experience. While companies `` search far and wide for esoteric formulas to get them back in the running, some very powerful solutions lie close at hand,'' he says. <PERSON> Schaffer </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, has demonstrated his theories in big companies and small, and now relates the story in `` The Breakthrough Strategy: Using Short-Term Success to Build The High Performance Organization.'' It confirms some widely held suspicions that management problems are n't as complicated as they might seem, that they seldom require the immediate purchase of new equipment, and that they can be solved today rather than tomorrow. Overly simplified, <PERSON> Schaffer </PERSON> preaches results-based management development, of which this is an example: In January 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters informed <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Quinn </PERSON>, manager of its <LOCATION> Calvert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> plant, that a corporate study to evaluate the facility's future was underway. The reason: Costs of its key chemical products were overly high and its market was eroding. After 37 years of operation, the future of the plant and the jobs of its 400 employees were on the line. Seventeen improvement teams, organized months before to tackle the plant's myriad problems, had failed to produce significant gains, partly because their efforts were too broad. Now they sought to focus on one critical element. The results showed up. In just eight weeks they were able to raise by 20 percent the feed rate of raw materials into one kiln among the many used to produce chemical reactions. Success! This first success changed the character of their turnaround efforts. Now they felt they could produce change. The team moved on to other kilns with productive results. Then they moved on to other projects, one at a time. Over the next six months the plant's managers were able to reduce overall production costs by 18 percent, focusing on one task at a time, benefiting from the enthusiasm and confidence generated by their successes. <PERSON> Schaffer </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schaffer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, is a devout believer in the principle that problems refined to their elements can be simple to deal with, whereas problems taken as a whole can be impossibly difficult. His approach is to get results at once, utilizing the personnel and other resources already existing within a company. Why, he asks, does a crisis so often produce its own solution, where months of earlier effort had failed? Why? Because a crisis produces a real sense of urgency, a personal challenge to workers, a sense of shared commitment to a well-defined goal, a freedom to experiment with new ideas, and a feeling of imminent success. He calls them `` zest factors.'' While he does n't believe in creating artificial crises, he does think it important to recognize the lessons that crises produce. Zest factors can be used to mobilize effective action. In his book, produced by <ORGANIZATION> Ballinger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Harper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Row, he describes how initial successes become launching pads for a continuing process of improvement. He asserts that companies can build their basic capacity to compete in the long-term while _ in fact, because of _ obtaining a succession of small but immediate and tangible successes. Rarely, does a business consultant offer you simplicity of approach, low cost, immediate results and a procedure for a continuing, never ending series of improvements.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday, Dec. 13.</NOTE>
