<HEAD>Grand Met Raises Offer for Pillsbury; Company Chairmen Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 new grafs to UPDATE with Pillsbury rejecting
higher tender offer, editing to conform; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Grand Met said...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grand Metropolitan PLC of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> today increased its cash tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> common stock by $ 3 per share to $ 63, but <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> quickly rejected the proposal as it had a separate offer for a richer, negotiated deal. Late Sunday, Grand Met had said it would amend its tender offer in a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The amended offer values <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s more than 86 million outstanding shares at about $ 5.42 billion. But <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors immediately rejected the $ 63-per-share offer as `` inadequate and not in the best interests of the company and its shareholders.'' Grand Met said Sunday it decided to raise its formal tender offer after Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> declined to endorse its offer to pay $ 65 a share for a friendly, negotiated acquisition. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> had said earlier Sunday night that Grand Met was willing to raise its offer to as much as $ 66 a share. Both companies issued statements saying that <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> met over the weekend with Grand Met Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> but did not reach an agreement. The jockeying occurred ahead of a hearing this afternoon in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chancery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s `` poison pill'' anti-takeover measures, the cornerstone of its defense against Grand Met. The British company's offer is conditioned on the removal of the pill. As of Friday night, stockholders had tendered 87.4 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> shares to Grand Met under its $ 60 bid. Grand Met, a major hotel and beverage conglomerate, has declined to buy any of the shares until the court rules on <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s defense. Court Chancellor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> has told participants that after oral arguments today, he will make a decision by the end of this week. At an initial meeting Friday evening, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> indicated he was prepared to increase Grand Met's offer to $ 63 a share. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> responded that he `` was not willing to discuss at this time'' a price which was not in the range of $ 68 to $ 73 a share, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s statement said. On Saturday morning, Grand Met indicated it was making a formal offer of $ 65 a share for a negotiated acquisition, according to both companies' statements. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said its board of directors met Sunday but there was `` no enthusiasm'' for the $ 65-a-share proposal. At a meeting Sunday afternoon, <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> indicated that although $ 65 was his official final offer, $ 66 a share `` could be available,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s statement. According to Grand Met's statement, <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> said Friday night the British company was willing to pay $ 63 per share and `` perhaps a little more'' in a negotiated acquisition, but did n't specify how much more. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said its board has authorized <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> to be available for any discussions with Grand Met officials `` which are designed to maximize values to <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> shareholders.'' The fight to take over <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, a company that includes the Burger King fast-food chain as well as a variety of products bearing the <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> brand, has coincided with the even bigger takeover of food and tobacco giant <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>, which was bought in a leveraged buyout last week in a deal estimated to be worth about $ 25 billion.
