<HEAD>Church's Chicken Decides To Close Unprofitable Units</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Popeyes, no apostrophe, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Church's <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting a hostile takeover takeover bid from a rival restaurant chain, said Monday it was closing 120 unprofitable restaurants and taking writeoffs of up to $ 27 million. Church's is scrambling to fend off the hostile overtures from the parent of New Orleans-based Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and Biscuits, whose latest $ 8-per-share, $ 290 million offer expires Friday. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Renaud </PERSON>, Church's president and chief executive officer, said the restaurant closings in 20 states involved outlets that lost $ 7.4 million in the past 12 months. He said the losses from the restaurants were affecting the company's cash flow as it struggled with tough economic situations and the takeover attempt. There will be 24 closings in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; 12 in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>; 10 in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, nine in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, seven in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, six in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and three to four each in several other states. `` There was just too much chicken competition in those areas. We just overbuilt,'' <PERSON> Renaud </PERSON> said. `` We were taking big losses for a long time. These units were just a big drain. `` They should have been closed a year ago, but this is just part of my plan to make the company profitable again,'' he said. <PERSON> Renaud </PERSON> said the comapny would take write-offs of between $ 22 million and $ 27 million for its current fiscal year. Church's stock dipped 25 cents to $ 7.75 a share Monday in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. Church's, which has gone through several management changes and poor sales over the past two years, had 1,500 restaurants before the closures, second behind <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>. Church's expects sales this year of $ 520 million, down from $ 570 million in 1986 and $ 633 million in 1984. Popeyes, the nation's third-largest chicken chain with about 725 restaurants, expects to have sales of $ 485 million this year. Church's board of directors has rejected Popeyes' offer as inadequate and is challenging various aspects of it in federal court as well as seeking possible other suitors. A federal judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> earlier this month issued an order preventing Popeyes from buying Church's stock until 10 working days after Popeyes disclosed further information on its buyout offer. Popeyes' first takeover deadline was Nov. 30, but has been extended to Friday. Popeyes Chairman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> says he already owns 3.2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s stock and says he has been tendered 14.6 million _ about 40.6 percent _ of <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s 35.9 million outstanding shares under the $ 8 a share offer.
