<HEAD>Dollar Up In Light Trading, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar strengthened marginally against major foreign currencies Monday but exchange dealers said trading was extremely slow, reflecting a reluctance to do business in advance of the government's market-moving monthly trade report. Gold prices eased. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 420.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 422.50 late Friday. Currency strategists read little significance into the dollar's small gain, saying it largely was due to internal market influences of supply and demand, not any outside news But some said speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would move to tighten interest rates may have strengthened the dollar a bit. Higher interest rates make dollar-denominated investments more attractive. Many dealers said the overwhelming force shaping the market's behavior was reticence to take any risky positions before the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report on the October trade deficit, due Wednesday The highly unpredictable monthly trade numbers are seen as one of the most visible symbols of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic strength and competitiveness abroad, with an enormous potential to influence financial markets. A large trade deficit would likely depress the dollar's value, while a small deficit would help stabilize or boost the currency. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.49 yen to close at 122.92 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar was quoted at 122.83 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar fetched 122.80 yen, up from 122.49 yen late Friday. The British pound fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.8418 from $ 1.8490 on Friday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, sterling fetched $ 1.8435, down from $ 1.8495 late Friday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates on Friday, included: 1.7415 West German marks, up from 1.7352; 1.4643 Swiss francs, up from 1.4620; 1.1970 Canadian dollars, up from evels late Friday included: 1.7410 West German marks, up from 1.7330; 1.4650 Swiss francs, up from 1.4605; 5.9520 French francs, up from 5.9240; 1.9635 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9560; 1,282.75 Italian lire, up from 1,280.25; and 1.1983 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1970. In bullion trading, gold for current delivery fell $ 2.80 a troy ounce from late Friday's level to $ 420.10 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> gold fell $ 1 an ounce to $ 419.75. Gold fell $ 1.05 an ounce in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> to $ 419.25 and fell $ 2.10 in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to $ 422.29. Silver bullion for current delivery fell 0.6 cent a troy ounce on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION> to $ 6.169. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> silver fell 2 cents an ounce to $ 6.14.
