<HEAD>Unisys Elects Two Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> elected two new directors as it and announced a reorganization of its management Monday in what was described as part of a long-term strategy to `` sell solutions, not machines.'' <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindelow </PERSON>, a senior vice president, will resign from the company at the end of the year in connection with the management shuffle. <PERSON> Lindelow </PERSON>'s responsibilities would have been reduced and he decided to look for another job, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> said the reduction of <PERSON> Lindelow </PERSON>'s responsibilities was not a reflection of his abilities. The computer company also extended its stock repurchase plan and declared dividends at a board meeting Monday in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The chief financial officer of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON>, was elected to the board of directors and promoted to executive vice president. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ely </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, currently chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Convergent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, also was elected to the board and will assume the position of executive vice president with the completion of the <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> acquisition of Convergent, a maker of small but speedy computer workstations. <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> said the acquisition of Convergent allowed the company to reorganize its management and its engineering and manufacturing divisions. <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> said the company's long-term strategy focuses on three areas: small computers, such as the Convergent machines; large, traditional mainframe computers; and networking, which is the process of allowing different computer systems to communicate with each other. `` It's part of our overall strategy, which is selling solutions, not machines,'' he said. `` We believe the customer does not care about the machine as much as the customer cares about what the machine will do for him,'' <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> said. Under the new management, <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> will be responsible for implementing the company's financial and strategic plans. <PERSON> Ely </PERSON> will become president of a newly formed <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Also under the new management, the current president of Convergent, <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yansouni </PERSON>, will be a <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> corporate vice president. A current <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president and director, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Unruh </PERSON>, will be responsible for all commercial marketing operations. He currently is in charge of international marketing operations and the implementation of the annual financial plan. A <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president, <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caswell </PERSON>, will become president of a newly formed <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, responsible for marketing the mainframe systems and peripheral products. The reorganization is expected to be implemented during the first quarter of 1989, after Convergent shareholders vote on the acquisition Dec. 22. In <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, the board declared a quarterly dividend of 25 cents per common share and a 93.75 cent dividend on the company's Series A cumulative convertible preferred stock. The board also extended for one year its periodic repurchase of the company's common and preferred stock, which was implemented last year. During 1988, the company purchased nearly 2 million of its authorized 10 million shares and reissued about half to fund stock option and other employee benefit plans. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> is a $ 10 billion manufacturer of commercial information systems, defense systems and related services. It has more than 90,000 employees and 60,000 customers in more than 100 countries.
