<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge On Supplies Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices fell steeply Monday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after the exchange reported the first increase in nearly a month in deliverable supplies of the metal. On other markets, precious metals mostly were lower; livestock and meat futures moved sharply higher; energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures fell. Copper settled 1 cent to 4.40 cents lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with the spot contract for delivery in December at $ 1.585 a pound and the more actively traded March contract at $ 1.352 a pound. Daily increases in the amount of warehoused copper registered with the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> have been rare since October 1987, when the <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION> copper inventory stood at nearly 90,000 short tons. Late last week, the exchange reported that warehouse stocks had dropped to 5,204 tons and copper for December delivery on the exchange soared to an all-time high of $ 1.6475 a pound. But copper traders who had expected the trend to continue were shocked Monday morning when the <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION> reported that warehouse stocks had risen to 6,545 tons, a 24 percent increase from last week's tally `` That was an unpleasant surprise to the market,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>, metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The Comex last reported an increase in copper stocks on Nov. 17. Meanwhile, the world's other major copper futures market, the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reported a 1,925-ton decline in its warehouse stocks of copper, which was a smaller decrease than traders had expected, <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON> said. Platinum futures prices fell sharply in a technically inspired sell-off, dragging a gold prices lower as well, but silver futures were mixed, analysts said. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, platinum settled $ 8.60 to $ 11.10 lower with January at $ 589.10 a troy ounce. On the Comex, gold settled $ 2.80 to $ 3.10 lower with February at $ 424.60 a troy ounce; silver was 0.7 cent lower to 0.4 cent higher with March at $ 6.298 a troy ounce. Pork futures rose strongly on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on speculation that last week's drop in slaughters meant hog kills had passed their seasonal peak, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Agri-Visor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. Strong retail demand and the arrival of wintry conditions in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> also contributed to the advance in pork futures, he said `` Farmers just havent' been willing to move hogs with the kind of temperatures we've had because it stresses them a little more,'' <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON> said. Cattle futures rallied in sympathy with the pork complex and in reaction to renewed demand, he said. Live cattle settled .25 cent to .60 cent higher with December at 72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to 1 cent higher with January at 83.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .63 cent to 1.20 cents higher with December at 42.77 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.03 cent to 1.35 cent higher with February at 44.60 cents a pound. Home heating oil prices closed sharply higher and lent support to crude oil futures after sub-zero temperatures hit the Northeast, analysts said. Gasoline futures retreated. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents 22 cents higher with January at $ 16.06 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent to .70 cent higher with January at 50.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .11 cent to .40 cent lower with January at 44.20 cents a gallon. Grain futures finished higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors of impending grain sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> while soybean prices settled mostly lower in response to weekend rains in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a monthly grain supply-demand report after the close in which it increased its estimate for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat stockpile at the end of the current marketing year to 533 million bushels from 528 million bushels. Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.28 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 -LCB- cents to 4 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.61 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 5 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.07 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 4 \ cents lower to 4 -RCB- cents higher with January at $ 7.69 \ a Stock index futures fell moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGAN