<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     12-12 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Change in Tender Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Disney-held company seeking to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> amended its takeover offer Monday to meet a federal court order that was blocking the bid. <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its hostile $ 42-a-share bid for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> was now contingent on whether a judge in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> invalidated or rescinded the <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> employee stock ownership plan being challenged by <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>. Analysts said the move would not dramatically alter <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s $ 2.6 billion tender offer, which has been in abeyance pending court action In <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Caleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on Monday ordered <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> to modify the language of the offer and issue a news release on the changes. The <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, Calif.-based television concern, wholly owned by the <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> family, met the conditions immediately. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> said it would purchase <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> shares under its $ 42 offer only if the employee stock plan was invalidated by <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> is challenging the plan. Previously, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> had maintained that the deal could have proceeded merely if the 10 million shares in the stock plan were ruled not part of the company's outstanding shares. If the $ 300 million plan is invalidated, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> would try to buy 62 million outstanding shares. If not, it would be faced with acquiring about 72 million shares under an earlier $ 40-a-share offer, analysts said. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> owns 5 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said the company had no comment on the development. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> last month ordered the district court to issue a preliminary injunction blocking the takeover bid until <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> clarified its position on the employee stock plan. The plan places 14 percent of the company stock in employee hands, a move <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> claims was designed intentionally to defend against its hostile takeover bid. Under <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law, a hostile bidder must acquire at least 85 percent of a company. Cambridge-based Polaroid, which introduced instant snapshots in 1948, is incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think this implies a change in the approach of <LOCATION> Shamrock </LOCATION> to the offer or really any material change in the offer,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. Arguments in the chancery court case are scheduled for Friday. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> said it would extend its offer for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> past next Monday's expiration date to wait for a court ruling.
