<FIRST>r f AM-LatinDebt     12-12 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Latin Debt,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group of Eight Meet to Discuss Latin American Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economic and finance ministers from seven <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nations agreed Monday to take `` urgent'', collective measures to reduce their foreign debt. The so-called Group of Eight also agreed in a closed-door meeting to present the measures, which were undisclosed, to their respective presidents. The group is composed of ministers from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> dropped out of the group last year due to internal political turmoil. Together, the eight member countries owe around $ 400 billion in foreign debt along with $ 25 billion in interest due in 1989. The measures should be accompanied by a call for cut in interst rates below the market rate, according to Brazilian Finance Minister <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON>. In the six years since the world debt crisis erupted, this is the first time that debtor nations have proposed an apparently unconventional, collective answer to the debt question, some observers said. At past meetings some members have stressed that each country's particular characteristics make a case-by-case direct resolution of their respective debts with creditors the more appropriate path to follow. During the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> meeting, as in past years, the Group of Eight avoided talk of a debt cartel.
</TEXT>
